{"title_page": "Shiva Ayyadurai", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name              = Shiva Ayyadurai\n|image             = V.A.Shiva.2012.jpg\n|caption           = Ayyadurai in 2012\n|birth_name        = Vellayappa Ayyadurai Shiva\n|birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1963|12|2}}\n|birth_place       = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n|party             = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]<ref name=\"Massachusetts 2020 General Election\">{{cite web |title=Massachusetts 2020 General Election |url=https://www.thegreenpapers.com/G20/MA |website=The Green Papers|accessdate=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|partner          = [[Fran Drescher]] (2014-2016)\n|education         = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]], [[Master of Science|MS]], [[Master of Engineering|MEng]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n|website           = {{URL|vashiva.com}}\n|module            = {{Infobox scientist\n|embed             = yes\n|fields            = [[Systems biology]]<br>[[Computer science]]<br>[[Scientific visualization]]<br>[[Traditional medicine]]\n|doctoral_advisor  = Forbes Dewey\n|academic_advisors = [[Robert S. Langer]]}}\n}}\n'''V. A. Shiva Ayyadurai''' (born '''Vellayappa Ayyadurai Shiva''',<ref name=\"mittech\"/> December 2, 1963)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/va.shiva.ayyadurai/about|title=V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref><ref name=\"history by lawsuit\"/> is an [[Indian Americans|Indian American]] [[scientist]], [[engineer]], and [[entrepreneur]]. <!-- do not edit the next sentence, unless there is consensus -- see Talk page -->He is notable for his widely disputed claim to be the \"inventor of [[email]]\",<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rajan |first1=Nadangopal |title=The inventor of email is still alive, insists India-born scientist |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/technology/tech-news-technology/the-inventor-of-email-is-still-alive-says-india-born-scientist/ |accessdate=5 July 2018 |work=The Indian Express |quote=\"CORRECTION: THE INVENTOR OF EMAIL IS STILL ALIVE,\" screams an e-mail not from the deceased Ray Tomlinson, but Dr VA  Shiva Ayyadurai.}}</ref> based on the electronic mail [[software]] called \"EMAIL\" he wrote as a [[New Jersey]] [[high school]] student in the late 1970s.<ref name=SmithsonianStatement /><ref name=chomsky-idgns /> Initial reports that repeated Ayyadurai's assertion\u2014from organizations such as ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and the [[Smithsonian Institution]]\u2014were followed by public retractions.<ref name=SmithsonianStatement /><ref name=washingtonpost>{{cite news|last=Kolawole|first=Emi|title=Smithsonian acquires documents from inventor of 'EMAIL' program|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/on-innovations/va-shivaayyadurai-inventor-of-e-mail-honored-by-smithsonian/2012/02/17/gIQA8gQhKR_story.html|accessdate=11 June 2012|newspaper=Washington Post|date=February 17, 2012|quote=\"incorrectly referred to V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai as the inventor of electronic messaging\"}}</ref> These corrections were triggered by objections from historians and [[ARPANET]] pioneers who pointed out that [[History of email|email was already actively used]] in the early 1970s.<ref name=\"history by lawsuit\">{{cite web|last1=Mullin|first1=Joe|last2=Farivar|first2=Cyrus|title=History by lawsuit: After Gawker's demise, the 'inventor of e-mail' targets Techdirt|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2017/06/shivas-war-one-mans-quest-to-convince-the-world-that-he-invented-e-mail/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=16 June 2017|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nAyyadurai also gained recognition for two reports: the first questioning the working conditions of India's largest scientific agency; the second questioning the safety of [[genetically modified food|genetically modified]] [[soybean]]s. Ayyadurai holds four degrees from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT), including a [[Ph.D.]] in [[biological engineering]], and is a [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright]] grant recipient.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.mit.edu/2007/east-west-0917|title=East Meets West: Armed with 4 MIT Degrees, Shiva Ayyadurai Embarks on New Adventure|last=Trafton|first=Anne|date=September 17, 2007|work=MIT Tech Talk|publisher=MIT|quote=\"In the 26 years since he first arrived at MIT as a freshman, V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai has earned four MIT degrees and started two multimillion dollar companies. This fall, he will use his most recent degree, a Ph.D. in computational systems biology, and a Fulbright Scholarship to explore one of his lifelong interests: the intersection of Eastern and Western medicine.\"|access-date=10 November 2016|via=}}</ref> He garnered 3.4% of the vote as an [[Independent politician|independent]] candidate in the [[United States Senate election in Massachusetts, 2018|2018 United States Senate election in Massachusetts]] and is running as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] in the [[2020 United States Senate election in Massachusetts|2020 U.S. Senate election in Massachusetts]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nShiva Ayyadurai was born Vellayappa Ayyadurai Shiva in 1963, in Bombay (now [[Mumbai]]), [[Maharashtra]].<ref name=\"mittech\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://vashiva.com/yes-a-darkie-invented-email-get-over-it/|title=Yes, A \"Darkie\" Invented Email. Get Over It. - V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai, Inventor of Email|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-13}}</ref><ref name=\"lokvani\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lokvani.com/lokvani/article.php?article_id=4379|title=Lokvani Talks to Dr. Shiva Ayyadurai|last=Saigal|first=Ranjani|date=November 3, 2007|publisher=lokvani.com|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> He grew up in the Muhavur village in [[Rajapalayam]], [[Tamil Nadu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaperbeta.timesofindia.com/Article.aspx?eid=31807&articlexml=Its-very-difficult-to-compare-an-employer-with-30082015101051|title= It's very difficult to compare an employer with an inventor: Shiva Ayyadurai |work=The Times of India|accessdate=2018-08-25|date=2015-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/be-job-providers-and-not-job-seekers/article4958821.ece|title= Be job providers and not job seekers |work=The Hindu|date=2013-07-27|accessdate=2018-08-25}}</ref> At the age of seven, he left with his family to live in the United States.<ref name=\"timmons\"/>\n\nIn 1978, as a 14-year-old high school student, Ayyadurai attended a summer program at the [[Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences]] of [[New York University]] (NYU) to study [[computer programming]]. While a student at [[Livingston High School (New Jersey)|Livingston High School]] in New Jersey, Ayyadurai volunteered at the [[University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey|University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey]] (UMDNJ) where his mother worked.<ref name=future>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=K3bVUladlakC&pg=PA160&lpg=PA160&dq=UMDNJ+research+fellow+ayyadurai#v=onepage&q=UMDNJ%20research%20fellow%20ayyadurai&f=false|title=Future Visions on Biomedicine and Bioinformatics 1|first=Swamy|last=Laxminarayan|publisher=[[Springer (publisher)|Springer]]|date=January 1, 2011|isbn=9783642150517}}</ref> There he created an email system to emulate the paper-based interoffice mail system then in use at the medical school.<ref name=\"future\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |last=Garlin |first=Caleb |url=https://www.wired.com/2012/06/noam-chomsky-email/ |title=Who Invented Email? Just Ask ... Noam Chomsky |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=June 16, 2012 |access-date=2017-08-25}}</ref> In 1982, he registered the [[copyright]] for his software, called \"EMAIL\", as well as for the program's user documentation.<ref name=\"SmithsonianStatement\" />\n\nAyyadurai's [[undergraduate degree]] from MIT was in [[electrical engineering]] and [[computer science]]; he took a [[master's degree]] in visual studies from the [[MIT Media Laboratory]] on [[scientific visualization]]; concurrently, he completed another master's degree in mechanical engineering, also from MIT; and in 2007, he obtained a Ph.D. in biological engineering from MIT in [[systems biology]], with his [[thesis]] focusing on modeling the whole cell by integrating molecular pathway models.<ref name=east>{{cite web|url=http://web.mit.edu/newsoffice/2007/east-west-0917.html|accessdate=9 June 2012|title=East meets West|date=September 17, 2007|work=MIT News|first=Anne|last=Trafton|publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology}}</ref><ref>{{cite document|title=DSpace@MIT: Scalable computational architecture for integrating biological pathway models|publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology|year=2007|first=Shiva|last=Ayyadurai|hdl = 1721.1/42384}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|first1=VA Shiva|last1=Ayyadurai|first2=C. Forbes Jr. |last2=Dewey |journal=Cellular and Molecular Bioengineering |date=March 2011|volume=4|issue=1|pages=28\u201345|doi=10.1007/s12195-010-0143-x|title=CytoSolve: A Scalable Computational Method for Dynamic Integration of Multiple Molecular Pathway Models|pmid=21423324|pmc=3032229}}</ref> In 2007, he was awarded a Fulbright U.S. Student Program grant to study the integration of [[Siddha medicine|Siddha]], a system of [[traditional medicine]] developed in [[South India]], with modern systems biology.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.fulbrightonline.org/component/filter/?view=filter|title=V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai, MIT, Biology, India, 2007, \"Pathways to Siddha and Systems Biology\"|website=Fulbright U.S. Student Program|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=east/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Millennium Cybernetics===\nIn 1994, Ayyadurai founded a company called Millennium Cybernetics, which produces [[email management]] software originally called Xiva and now called EchoMail.<ref name=\"mittech\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/400629/dr-e-mail-will-see-you-now/|title=Dr. Email Will See You Now|last=Shapley|first=Deborah|date=January 1, 2000|work=MIT Technology Review|accessdate=2016-08-11|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000511125636/http://www.techreview.com/articles/jan00/shapley.htm|archivedate=May 11, 2000|url-status=dead}}</ref> The software analyzes incoming email messages to organizations before either replying automatically or forwarding it to the most relevant department. By 2001, customers included [[Kmart]], [[American Express]], and [[Calvin Klein]], as well as more than thirty [[United States Senator|U.S. senators]] to help handle constituent email. EchoMail competed with more established [[customer relationship management]] software that had an email component.<ref name=\"mittech\" /><ref name=\"bulkeley\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB1005776873756157960|title=Echomail provides an answer for the avalanche of e-mail|author=William Bulkeley|date=November 15, 2011|accessdate=2016-11-08|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On its website, EchoMail describes Ayyadurai as the \"Inventor of Email\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://echomail.com/|title=EchoMail|publisher=echomail.com|accessdate=2018-01-13|quote=[http://www.inventorofemail.com/ The Inventor of Email\u2122]}}</ref>\n\n===CSIR India===\nIn 2009, Ayyadurai was hired by India's [[Council of Scientific and Industrial Research]] (CSIR), India's largest science agency, by its director general, [[Samir K. Brahmachari]]. CSIR was mandated to create a new company, CSIR Tech, that would establish businesses using the research conducted by the country's many publicly owned laboratories. Ayyadurai reported that he had spent months trying to create a business plan for CSIR Tech, but received no response from Brahmachari. Ayyadurai then distributed a draft plan, which was not authorized by CSIR, to the agency's scientists that requested feedback and criticized management. His job offer was subsequently withdrawn five months after the position was offered.<ref name=timmons>{{cite news|last=Timmons|first=Heather|title=Some Indians Find It Tough to Go Home Again|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/28/business/global/28return.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=11 June 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=November 27, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Nature\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.nature.com/news/2009/091109/full/462152a.html|title=Report row ousts top Indian scientist |journal=Nature | date=November 9, 2009 |accessdate=19 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nBrahmachari said that \"the offer was withdrawn as [Ayyadurai] did not accept the [[terms and conditions]] and demanded unreasonable compensation.\"  In its report, ''[[The New York Times]]'' said that \"going public with such accusations is highly unusual. Mr. Ayyadurai circulated his paper not just to the agency's scientists but to journalists, and wrote about his situation to [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Manmohan Singh]].\" In that letter, Ayyadurai said his report was intended to explore institutional barriers to CSIR's entrepreneurial mandate. He said that CSIR scientists reported that \"they work in a [[medieval]], [[feudalism|feudal]] environment\" that required a \"major overhaul\". The letter was co-authored by a colleague, Deepak Sardana. [[Pushpa Mittra Bhargava|Pushpa Bhargava]], founding director of the CSIR's Centre for Cellular and Molecular Biology in Hyderabad, endorsed the letter, calling Ayyadurai's sacking the worst of many cases he had seen of \"vindictiveness in the CSIR\" and accused CSIR administration of being \"impervious to healthy and fair criticism\". The incident was seen as an example of the difficulty some Indian [[expatriate]] professionals may encounter returning home after growing accustomed to the more direct management style of the U.S.<ref name=\"timmons\" /><ref name=\"Nature\" />\n\n===Genetically modified food===\nIn 2015, Ayyadurai published a paper that applied systems biology, which uses [[mathematical model]]ing, to predict the chemical composition of genetically modified (GM) soybeans, and whether or not they were [[substantial equivalence|substantially equivalent]] to unmodified soybeans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theecologist.org/News/news_round_up/2950586/gmo_and_glyphosate_wars_rage.html |author=Oliver Tickell |title=GMO and glyphosate wars rage |publisher=The Ecologist |date=July 16, 2015 |accessdate=2016-11-09}}</ref> The paper claimed that GM soybeans have lower levels of the [[antioxidant]] [[glutathione]] and higher levels of [[carcinogen]]ic [[formaldehyde]], making the modified soybean substantially different, contrary to previous safety assessments.<ref>{{cite news|author=Vishwanath Kulkarni |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/opinion/safety-assessments-of-gmos-are-nonexistent/article7674558.ece |title=Safety assessments of GMOs are non-existent |newspaper=The Hindu Business Line |date=September 21, 2015 |accessdate=2016-11-09}}</ref> Shortly after publication, Ayyadurai embarked on a speaking tour of the U.S. At the [[National Press Club]], he said that genetic modification had \"fundamentally modified the metabolic system of the soy\", disrupting the \"beautiful way of detoxifying [formaldehyde]\" present in non-GM soy.<ref>Ayyadurai, V.A. Shiva. (2015) \"[https://www.facebook.com/va.shiva.ayyadurai/videos/vb.212669305456262/963543970368788/?type=2&theater Systems Biology reveals GMO testing is flawed]\", ''Facebook''. Retrieved August 26, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe [[European Food Safety Agency]] evaluated the paper and determined that \"the author's conclusions are not supported\" due to the lack of information on the input into the model, the fact that the model was not validated and because no measurements of soybeans were made to establish whether GM soy actually contained elevated levels of formaldehyde.<ref>{{cite journal|author=European Food Safety Authority |title=EFSA scientific advice to EC on new scientific information in relation to the risk assessment of genetically modified organisms |journal=EFSA Supporting Publications |volume=12 |issue=11 |date=November 3, 2015 |doi=10.2903/sp.efsa.2015.EN-885 }}</ref> Plant scientist [[Kevin Folta]] noted that there was \"no evidence ever published ... that shows a difference in formaldehyde between GM and non-GM varieties\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geneticliteracyproject.org/2015/07/21/kevin-folta-debunks-pay-for-play-paper-supposedly-finding-formaldehyde-in-gmos/|title=Kevin Folta debunks pay for play paper finding formaldehyde in GMOs|publisher=Genetic Literacy Project |date=July 21, 2015 |first=Kevin |last=Folta |authorlink=Kevin Folta|accessdate=2016-11-09}}</ref> Ayyadurai later cited the study as evidence of a lack of safety standards for GM foods and bet [[Monsanto]] a $10 million building if they could prove that they were safe. Monsanto did not take up the challenge but stated that GM food did indeed undergo safety assessments that \"are more rigorous and thorough than assessments of any other food crop in history\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Tanya Lewis |url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/scientist-bets-millions-that-gmos-unsafe-2015-11 |title=Scientist bets millions that GMOs unsafe |website=Business Insider |date=November 12, 2015 |accessdate=2016-11-09}}</ref> In 2016, Ayyadurai promised to donate $10 million to [[Hillary Clinton]]'s [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016|presidential campaign]] if she could disprove his research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://patch.com/new-jersey/montclair/nj-scientist-gives-hillary-clinton-10-million-gmo-challenge-0 |title=NJ Scientist Gives Hillary Clinton a $10 Million GMO Challenge |publisher=Patch |date=February 1, 2016 |accessdate=2016-11-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\nOn March 17, 2017, Ayyadurai filed as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate in the 2018 United States Senate election in Massachusetts, running against incumbent [[Elizabeth Warren]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2017/03/man-who-claims-he-invented-e-mail-is-now-running-for-us-senate/|title=Man who claims he invented e-mail is now running for US Senate|last=Farivar|first=Cyrus|date=March 29, 2017|work=Ars Technica|access-date=2017-03-30|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/news/politics/2017/02/28/cambridge-man-who-says-he-invented-email-says-he-will-challenge-elizabeth-warren-in-2018|title=Cambridge man who says he invented email says he will challenge Elizabeth Warren in 2018|last=DeCosta-Klip|first=Nik |date=February 28, 2017 |work=Boston.com|access-date=2017-03-17|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC|language=}}</ref> On November 11, 2017, he announced he would run as an independent<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/news/2017/11/11/shiva-ayyadurai-independent/|title=Shiva Ayyadurai Is Running for Senate as an Independent|last=Buell|first=Spencer|date=2017-11-11|work=Boston Magazine|access-date=2017-11-11|language=en-US}}</ref> and ultimately garnered 3.4% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/11/06/us/elections/results-massachusetts-elections.html|title=Massachusetts Election Results|last=|first=|date=|work=New York Times|access-date=2018-11-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAyyadurai said that Senator Warren was at the top of a U.S. \"neo-[[caste system]]\" composed of \"academics, career politicians and lawyer/lobbyists\", a \"spineless clan\" who never expect to be challenged. He said he would take a science and engineering perspective on problem solving, focusing on immigration, education and innovation. He called for secure borders and an end to [[Sanctuary city|sanctuary cities]], support for more choices in [[public education]], and for more scrutiny of \"[[pay-to-play]]\" science research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/news/2017/05/08/republican-entrepreneur-waging-2018-bid-against.html|title=Republican entrepreneur waging 2018 bid against Elizabeth Warren|last=Young|first=Shannon|date=May 8, 2017|website=Boston Business Journal|access-date=2017-05-21}}</ref> Ayyadurai has accused Warren of voting in favor of the [[Farmer Assurance Provision]] and against a GM labeling bill sponsored by Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] of [[Vermont]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://shiva4senate.com/press-conference-elizabeth-warren-marty-walsh-collusion/|title=Press Conference: Elizabeth Warren + Marty Walsh Collusion - Shiva For Senate in Massachusetts|date=25 October 2017|publisher=}}</ref> However, the Act was reportedly passed to avoid a [[government shutdown]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/monsanto-protection-act/|title=FACT CHECK: Monsanto Protection Act|publisher=}}</ref> and Warren petitioned the [[Food and Drug Administration]] for \"regulations to ensure that the labeling of GMO products is fair, standardized and transparent.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2013/09/elizabeth-warren-joins-gmo-labeling-fray-096928|title=Warren joins GMO labeling fray|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Ayyadurai spoke at the [[Boston Free Speech rally]], a gathering which drew large counter-protests and whose speaker line-up included [[right-wing extremist]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/08/14/senate-candidate-plans-address-free-speech-rally-common/CzFnJ4c4u1wOjojtdeLUzM/story.html |title=US Senate candidate plans to address 'free speech' rally on Common |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=August 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/08/17/speakers-list-for-boston-free-speech-rally-include-right-wing-extremist/6xWnzHZwrjq8svoRbPN1NP/story.html |title=Speakers list for 'free speech' rally includes right-wing extremists |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=August 17, 2017}}</ref> Ayyadurai later disputed how the event was characterized, tweeting that the \"establishment\" wanted to block attendance and media coverage and sought a \"[[race war|Race War]] to divide us\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2017/08/19/gop_senate_candidate_shiva_ayyadurais_speech_at_boston_free_speech_rally.html|title=GOP Senate Candidate Shiva Ayyadurai Called For Peace And Love At Boston 'Free Speech Rally' |last=Harris|first=Tim|date=August 19, 2017|website=www.realclearpolitics.com|access-date=2017-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/18/us/demonstration-race-free-speech-boston-charlottesville.html|title=Protesters Flood Streets, and Trump Offers a Measure of Praise |first1=Katharine Q. |last1=Seelye |first2=Alan |last2=Blinder |last3=Bidgood |first3=Jess |date=August 18, 2017 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=2017-08-25 |language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In April 2018, the city of [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]] threatened Ayyadurai with daily [[fine (penalty)|fines]] for an alleged zoning code violation if he did not remove a banner on his campaign bus. The banner featured his campaign slogan, \"Only a real Indian can defeat a fake Indian\", together with a digitally altered image depicting Warren in a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] headdress, a reference to her claim to be of part [[Cherokee]] descent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/real-indian-running-against-elizabeth-warren-shiva-ayyadurai-sues-signs-calling-her-fake-indian/|title=\"Real Indian\" running against Sen. Elizabeth Warren defends sign calling her \"Fake Indian\" |first=Christina |last=Capatides |date=April 24, 2018 |work=[[CBS News]] |access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> The city reversed its position the following month and Ayyadurai, in turn, dropped a lawsuit alleging that his free speech rights had been violated.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2018/may/17/cambridge-rescinds-order-remove-anti-warren-fake-i/|title=Cambridge rescinds order to remove anti-Warren 'fake Indian' campaign signs|last=Richardson|first=Valerie|date=May 17, 2018|work=The Washington Times|access-date=2018-05-19|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAyyadurai is running as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] in the [[2020 United States Senate election in Massachusetts|2020 U.S. Senate election in Massachusetts]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2020/01/29/meet-year-old-who-asking-legislature-let-her-vote-this-year-presidential-primary/jRGO7IBieu5c9vGeSHm1LK/story.html|title=Meet the 17-year-old who is asking the Legislature to let her vote in this year's presidential primary - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2018/10/17/shiva-ayyadurai-provocative-candidate-who-represents-our-bizarre-political-climate/o2bh5D3wkie8qqvjYRUHYI/story.html|title=Shiva Ayyadurai: the candidate who represents our bizarre political climate - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19 misinformation===\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] Ayyadurai used social media to spread various conspiracy theories and misinformation about the pandemic. In January 2020 he claimed that the coronavirus was patented by the [[Pirbright Institute]], but the patent he referenced relates to ''[[avian coronavirus]]'', which infects birds, not [[SARS-CoV-2]], the virus responsible for the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Funke |first1=Daniel |last2=Kertscher |first2=Tom |title=Fact-checking hoaxes and conspiracies about the coronavirus |url=https://www.politifact.com/article/2020/jan/24/fact-checking-hoaxes-and-conspiracies-about-corona/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=PolitiFact |date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAyyadurai claimed to be a 'student of medicine' during a March 30, 2020 interview with Next News Network despite having no medical or immunology credentials<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=youtu.be&v=xf-qv9o8nq8&fbclid=IwAR3zbFBxRR5_63rBzAo499l2FFpaaKkIW7WD8f9Bx8Vj9LAPLnYlmEYrVxY&app=desktop}}</ref>. He described an unsupported model of immunologic health. During the interview, he also disputed the fact that [[HIV]] is linked with [[AIDS]]; alleging [[Anthony Fauci]]'s mentor [[Robert Gallo]], winner of Nobel Prize in Physiology of Medicine in 2008 for his work on the discovery of HIV, fabricated the evidence linking HIV with AIDS and created a 'bogus' HIV test, referring to the HIV ELISA test that is commonly used today with a 99-100% sensitivity <ref>{{cite journal |pmid=2146552}}</ref>\n\nHe alleged that the coronavirus was spread by the \"[[deep state]]\" and accused [[Anthony Fauci]], director of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases, of being a \"Deep State Plant\". Ayyadurai called for Fauci to be fired.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goforth |first1=Claire |title=Why Dr. Fauci has become conspiracy theorists' coronavirus scapegoat |url=https://www.dailydot.com/debug/coronavirus-conspiracy-theorists-fire-fauci-shiva-ayyadurai/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=The Daily Dot |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020 he published an open letter to president [[Donald Trump]] where he wrote that a national lockdown was unnecessary and advocated that large doses of vitamins could prevent and cure the disease.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Charlie |title=Republican Senate hopeful Shiva Ayyadurai calls for firing of U.S. pandemic-control czar Dr. Anthony Fauci |url=https://www.straight.com/news/republican-senate-hopeful-shiva-ayyadurai-calls-for-firing-of-us-pandemic-control-czar-dr |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=The Georgia Straight |date=5 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shiva4senate.com/immune-and-economic-health-for-america-coronavirus/|title=Immune and Economic Health for America Coronavirus|last=Shiva|first=Ayyadurai|date=March 23, 2020|website=Shiva For Senate in Massachusetts|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==\"EMAIL\" invention controversy==\nAyyadurai makes the widely disputed claim to be the \"inventor of email\". His claim is based on the software he wrote as a 14-year-old student at Livingston High School in New Jersey. In 1979\u2014some sources say 1978\u2014he wrote an implementation of an interoffice email system, which he called ''EMAIL''.<ref name=SmithsonianStatement /><ref name=chomsky-idgns />\n\nA November 2011 ''[[Time Magazine|Time]]'' Techland interview by Doug Aamoth, entitled \"The Man Who Invented Email\", argued that EMAIL represented the birth of email \"as we currently know it\". In that interview, Ayyadurai recalled that Les Michelson, the former particle scientist at [[Brookhaven National Labs]] who assigned Ayyadurai the project, had the idea of creating an electronic mail system that uses the header conventions of a hardcopy memorandum. Ayyadurai recalled Michelson as saying: \"Your job is to convert that into an electronic format. Nobody's done that before.\"<ref name=techland>{{cite news|last=Aamoth|first=Doug|title=The Man Who Invented Email|url=http://techland.time.com/2011/11/15/the-man-who-invented-email/|accessdate=11 June 2012|newspaper=Time Magazine: Techland|date=November 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, the Smithsonian [[National Museum of American History]] announced that Ayyadurai had donated \"a trove of documents and code\" related to EMAIL. Initially, the museum\u2014inaccurately\u2014cited the program as one of the first to include the now common \"subject and body fields, [[inbox]]es, [[outbox]]es, cc, bcc, attachments, and others. He based these elements directly off of the interoffice mail memos the doctors had been using for years, in hopes of convincing people to actually use the newfangled technology.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.smithsonianmag.com/aroundthemall/2012/02/a-piece-of-email-history-comes-to-the-american-history-museum/|title=A Piece of Email History Comes to the American History Museum|date=February 22, 2012|accessdate=11 June 2012|first=Joseph|last=Stromberg|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]]}}</ref>\n\nAyyadurai's claims drew editorial clarifications and corrections, as well as criticism from industry observers. In a followup to its acquisition announcement, the Smithsonian stated that it was not claiming that Ayyadurai had invented email, but rather that the materials were historically notable for other reasons related to trends in computer education and the role of computers in medicine.<ref name=\"SmithsonianStatement\">{{Cite press release |url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/news/pressrelease.cfm?key=29&newskey=1465 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427014952/http://americanhistory.si.edu/news/pressrelease.cfm?key=29&newskey=1465 |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 27, 2012 |title=Statement from the National Museum of American History: Collection of Materials from V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai |date=February 23, 2012|accessdate=19 February 2013|publisher=National Museum of American History |quote=\"Exchanging messages through computer systems, what most people call 'email', predates the work of Ayyadurai.\"}}</ref> The Smithsonian statement distinguished Ayyadurai's achievement by noting that historians in the field, \"have largely focused on the use of large networked computers, especially those linked to the ARPANET in the early 1970s\". The statement pointed out that Ayyadurai's approach instead \"focused on communications between linked computer terminals in an ordinary office situation\".<ref name=\"SmithsonianStatement\" /> ''The Washington Post'' also followed up with a correction of errors in its earlier report on the Smithsonian acquisition, stating that it incorrectly referred to Ayyadurai as the inventor of electronic messaging; the 'bcc', 'cc', 'to' and 'from' fields existed previously; Ayyadurai had not been honored as the \"inventor of email\".<ref name=\"washingtonpost\" />\n\nWriting for ''[[Gizmodo]]'', [[Sam Biddle]] argued that email was developed a decade before EMAIL, beginning with [[Ray Tomlinson]]'s sending the first text letter between two [[ARPANET]]-connected computers in 1971.<ref>i.e. the first ''network'' email using the \"@\" syntax; email between users on the same mainframe was already common.</ref> Biddle quoted Tomlinson: \"[We] had most of the headers needed to deliver the message (to:, cc:, etc.) as well as identifying the sender (from:) and when the message was sent (date:) and what the message was about.\"  Biddle allowed for the possibility that Ayyadurai may have coined the term \"EMAIL\" and used the header terms without being aware of earlier work, but maintained that the historical record isn't definitive on either point. Biddle wrote that \"laying claim to the name of a product that's the generic term for a universal technology gives you acres of weasel room. But creating a type of airplane named AIRPLANE doesn't make you [[Wilbur Wright]].\"<ref name=\"giz120305\">{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Biddle |work=[[Gizmodo]] |title=Corruption, Lies, and Death Threats: The Crazy Story of the Man Who Pretended to Invent Email |url=https://gizmodo.com/5888702/corruption-lies-and-death-threats-the-crazy-story-of-the-man-who-pretended-to-invent-email |date=March 5, 2012 |accessdate=5 March 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306204240/http://gizmodo.com/5888702/corruption-lies-and-death-threats-the-crazy-story-of-the-man-who-pretended-to-invent-email|archivedate=2012-03-06}}</ref>\n\nThomas Haigh, a historian of information technology at the [[University of Wisconsin]], wrote that \"Ayyadurai is, to the best of my knowledge, the only person to have claimed for him or herself the title 'inventor of email'.\" Haigh argued that while EMAIL was impressive for a teenager's work, it contained no features that were not present on previous electronic mail systems and had no obvious influence on later systems. \"The most striking thing about Ayyadurai's claim to have invented electronic mail is how late it comes. Somehow it took him thirty years to alert the world to [his] greatest achievement\".<ref name=SIGCIS-Haigh>{{cite web|title=Did V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai Invent Email?|url=http://www.sigcis.org/ayyadurai|publisher=SIGCIS: Special Interest Group Computers, Information and Society|accessdate=9 June 2012|date=April 17, 2012|first=Thomas|last=Haigh}}</ref> Haigh wrote that by 1980, \"electronic mail had been in use at MIT for 15 years, Xerox had built a modern, mouse-driven graphical email system for office communication, Compuserve was selling email access to the public, and email had for many years been the most popular application on what was soon to become the Internet.\" <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Haigh|first1=Thomas|title=Seven Lessons from Bad History|journal=Communications of the ACM|date=September 2012|volume=55|issue=9|page=26|url=http://www.tomandmaria.com/tom/Writing/CACM-SevenLessons.pdf|accessdate=16 September 2014|doi=10.1145/2330667.2330676}}</ref>\n\nDavid Crocker, a member of the ARPANET research community, writing in the ''Post'', said, \"The reports incorrectly credited [EMAIL's] author, a 14-year old in the late 1970s, as the 'inventor' of email, long after it had become an established service on the ARPANET.\"<ref name=DavidCrockerWaPo>{{cite news|last=Crocker|first=David|title=A history of e-mail: Collaboration, innovation and the birth of a system|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/on-innovations/a-history-of-e-mail-collaboration-innovation-and-the-birth-of-a-system/2012/03/19/gIQAOeFEPS_story.html|accessdate=10 June 2012|newspaper=Washington Post|date=March 20, 2012}}</ref> Another computer historian, Marc Weber, a curator at the [[Computer History Museum]], said that by 1978, \"nearly all the features we're familiar with today had appeared on one system or another over the previous dozen years\", including [[emoticons]], [[mailing list]]s, [[flame war]]s, and [[spam mail]].<ref name=BostonMag />\n\nAfter the controversy unfolded, MIT disassociated itself from Ayyadurai's EMAIL Lab and funding was dropped. MIT also revoked Ayyadurai's contract to lecture at the bioengineering department.<ref name=\"BostonMag\" />\n\nAyyadurai characterized the earlier work of Tomlinson, [[Tom Van Vleck]] and others as [[text messaging]], rather than an electronic version of an interoffice mail system.<ref name=techland /><ref name=BostonMag>{{cite news|last=Nanos|first=Janelle|title=Return to Sender|url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/2012/05/shiva-ayyaduri-email-us-postal-service/|accessdate=11 June 2012|newspaper=Boston Magazine|date=June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307102703/https://www.bostonmagazine.com/2012/05/30/shiva-ayyaduri-email-us-postal-service/#|archive-date=2018-03-07|url-status=live}}</ref> Responding to his critics on his personal website,<ref name=giz120305 /><ref name=BostonMag /> Ayyadurai described EMAIL as \"the first of its kind\u2014a fully integrated, database-driven, electronic translation of the interoffice paper mail system derived from the ordinary office situation.\" He maintained that EMAIL was the first electronic mail system to integrate an easy-to-use [[user interface]], a [[word processor]], a [[relational database]], and a modular inter-communications protocol \"integrated together in one single and holistic platform to ensure high-reliability and user-friendliness network-wide.\"<ref name=AyyaduraiResponse>{{cite web|last=Ayyadurai|first=VA Shiva|title=EMAIL (UMDNJ, 1978)|url=http://www.inventorofemail.com/va-shiva-personal-statement-inventor-of-email.asp|work=The Inventor of Email: innovation any time, any place, by anybody|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref> Ayyadurai presented a [[press release]] on his webpage asserting that his undergraduate professor [[Noam Chomsky]], of MIT's Department of Linguistics and Philosophy, also supported his claims.<ref name=chomsky-idgns>{{cite web|url=http://www.computerworld.com/article/2503255/enterprise-applications/noam-chomsky-disputes-email-history.html|first=Joab|last=Jackson|title=Noam Chomsky disputes email history|publisher=Computerworld/IDGNS}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn March 2016, Ayyadurai alleged that the overlooking of his achievements was a result of [[racism]] and a conspiracy between mainstream media and the [[military\u2013industrial complex]], particularly [[Raytheon]], where Tomlinson worked on ARPANET. After Tomlinson's death, Ayyadurai told ''[[The Hindu]]'' that he believed that news outlets retracted their stories about him because, \"Raytheon advertises in publications like the ''[[Huffington Post]]'' and [[CNN]]\" and that if he were \"a white guy and had a copyright for email, I would have my photo on every stamp in the world.\"<ref name=\"the-hindu-raymond\">{{cite news|newspaper=The Hindu |date=March 7, 2016 |title=Not everybody loves Raymond|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/technology/who-invented-email-ray-tomlinson-or-shiva-ayyadurai/article8323987.ece}}</ref> The day after Tomlinson's death, Ayyadurai tweeted: \"I'm the low-caste, dark-skinned, Indian, who DID invent #email. Not Raytheon, who profits for war & death. Their mascot Tomlinson dies a liar\".<ref name=\"tweet-2016-03-06\">{{cite web|last=Ayyadurai|first=VA Shiva|title=Tweet from @va_shiva, March 6, 2016|url=https://twitter.com/va_shiva/status/706670699713335297}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Gawker'' ===\nIn May 2016, Ayyadurai filed suit against [[Gawker Media]] for $35 million, alleging that their website ''Gawker'' published \"false and [[defamation|defamatory]] statements\", causing \"substantial damage to Dr. Ayyadurai's personal and professional reputation and career.\" The filing also named writer Sam Biddle, executive editor John Cook, and Gawker founder and CEO [[Nick Denton]]. Gawker Media responded that, \"These claims to have invented email have been repeatedly debunked by the Smithsonian Institute{{sic}}, Gizmodo, the Washington Post and others.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/news/2016/05/10/cambridge-man-who-claims-he-invented-email-sues.html|title=Cambridge man who claims he invented email sues Gawker for $35M - Boston Business Journal|last=Harris|first=David L.|date=May 10, 2016|website=Boston Business Journal|access-date=2016-05-16}}</ref><ref>[https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/2829697/Gov-Uscourts-Mad-180248-1-0.pdf ''Shiva Ayyadurai v. Gawker Media, et. al''., Complaint] (D. Mass, filed May 10, 2016)</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, the by-then-bankrupt Gawker Media [[Settlement (litigation)|settled]] the lawsuit with Ayyadurai for $750,000 as part of a broader settlement with wrestler [[Hulk Hogan]] and journalist Ashley Terrill, all of whom were represented by attorney [[Charles Harder]].<ref name=gizsettle>{{Cite news|url=https://gizmodo.com/internet-pioneers-slam-750-000-settlement-for-the-man-1788503950|title=Internet Pioneers Slam $750,000 Settlement for the 'Man Who Invented Email'|author=Mario Aguilar}}</ref> In a statement, Ayyadurai said that \"history will reflect that this settlement is a victory for truth\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/03/business/media/gawker-hulk-hogan-settlement.html|title=Gawker and Hulk Hogan Reach $31 Million Settlement|last=Ember|first=Sydney|date=November 2, 2016 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-11-04}}</ref> Biddle denounced the settlement and said he fully stood by his reporting.<ref name=giz1788495465>{{cite news|url=https://gizmodo.com/gawker-media-will-settle-with-hulk-hogan-and-other-liti-1788495465 | title=Gawker Media Will Settle With Hulk Hogan and Other Litigants for $32 Million |author=J.K. Trotter |work=Gizmodo |date=November 2, 2016 |accessdate=2016-11-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mattdrange/2016/11/02/gawker-media-close-to-reaching-settlement-with-hulk-hogan/|title=Gawker Reaches Settlement With Hulk Hogan For $31 Million|last=Mac|first=Ryan|date=November 2, 2016|work=|newspaper=Forbes|access-date=2016-11-03|via=}}</ref> Denton wrote that \"we expected to prevail\" in the Ayyadurai and Terrill lawsuits, \"but all-out legal war with\" billionaire [[Peter Thiel]], who financially backed Harder, was untenable in terms of cost, time and human toll.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nickdenton.org/a-hard-peace-e161e19bfaf|title=A hard peace|last=Denton|first=Nick|date=November 2, 2016|newspaper=nickdenton.com: Being myself|access-date=2016-11-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502211504/https://nickdenton.org/a-hard-peace-e161e19bfaf#|archive-date=2018-05-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Katie Hafner]], the author of several books on Internet history\u2014including one on the development of ARPANET email\u2014said, \"This situation is both bizarre and appalling in that here we are simply trying to get the record straight, and [Ayyadurai has] managed to make money off claims that appear to be misleading.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gizmodo.com/internet-pioneers-slam-750-000-settlement-for-the-man-1788503950|title=Internet Pioneers Slam $750,000 Settlement for the 'Man Who Invented Email'|last=Aguilar|first=Mario|newspaper=Gizmodo|language=en-US|access-date=2016-11-10}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Techdirt'' ===\nIn January 2017, Ayyadurai, again represented by Harder, filed a $15 million libel lawsuit on similar grounds against ''[[Techdirt]]'' founder [[Mike Masnick]] and two other parties for a series of articles published beginning in September 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/proclaimed-inventor-email-files-defamation-lawsuit-techdirts-michael-masnick-961008|title=Self-Proclaimed Inventor of Email Files Defamation Lawsuit Against Techdirt's Mike Masnick|last=Gardner|first=Eriq|date=January 5, 2017|work=|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2017-01-07|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2017/01/05/email-inventor-techdirt/|title='Inventor of Email' Slaps Tech Site With $15M Libel Suit for Mocking His Claim|last=Roberts|first=Jeff John|date=January 5, 2017|website=Fortune|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-07}}</ref><ref>[https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/3252883/Techdirt-Emaillawsuit.pdf ''Shiva Ayyadurai v. Floor64 Inc et. al''., Complaint] (D. Mass, filed January 4, 2017)</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20170111/11440836465/techdirts-first-amendment-fight-life.shtml|title=Techdirt's First Amendment Fight For Its Life|last=Masnick|first=Mike|date=January 11, 2017|work=|newspaper=Techdirt|access-date=2017-01-16|via=}}</ref> In February, Masnick, represented by the firm Prince Lobel, filed two [[Motion (legal)#To dismiss|motions to dismiss]]. One motion argued that the articles were constitutionally protected opinion and written about a [[public figure]] without [[actual malice]]. The second motion asked for dismissal under [[Strategic lawsuit against public participation#California|California's anti-SLAPP law]] that compensates defendants for some legal expenses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.co.uk/tech-policy/2017/02/techdirt-lawyers-ask-judge-to-throw-out-defamation-suit-over-inventor-of-e-mail/|title=Techdirt lawyers ask judge to throw out suit over 'Inventor of E-mail' |last=Mullin|first=Joe|date=February 18, 2017|newspaper=Ars Technica UK|access-date=2017-02-20|work=|language=en-us|via=}}</ref><ref>[https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/3468184/13-Main.pdf Memorandum of Floor64, Inc. and Michael Masnick in support of motion to dismiss pursuant to Fed. R. Civ. P. 12(B)(5) and 12(B)(6)] (D. Mass, filed February 17, 2017)</ref><ref>[https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/3468242/Techdirt-Memo-in-Support-of-Special-MN-to-Strike.pdf  Memorandum of defendants Floor64, Inc. and Michael Masnick in support of their special motion to strike plaintiff's complaint pursuant to the California Anti-SLAPP law] (D. Mass, filed February 17, 2017)</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, United States District Judge [[F. Dennis Saylor IV|F. Dennis Saylor]] dismissed the defamation claims against ''Techdirt'', but declined to strike the complaint under the anti-SLAPP law. In his ruling, Saylor wrote that definitions of \"email\" vary widely. Therefore, \"whether plaintiff's claim to have invented e-mail is 'fake' depends upon the operative definition of 'e-mail.' Because the definition does not have a single, objectively correct answer, the claim is incapable of being proved true or false.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ia800807.us.archive.org/7/items/gov.uscourts.mad.185980/gov.uscourts.mad.185980.48.0.pdf|title=Memorandum and Order on Defendants' Motion to Dismiss and to Strike|last=Saylor IV|first=F. Dennis|date=August 6, 2017|website=United States District Court, District of Massachusetts}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2017/09/1st-amendment-wins-in-self-proclaimed-e-mail-inventors-techdirt-libel-suit/|title=1st Amendment wins in self-proclaimed e-mail inventor's Techdirt libel suit|last=Kravets|first=David|date=September 7, 2017|work=Ars Technica|access-date=2017-09-09|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nThe two parties filed cross-[[appeal]]s with the [[United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit|U.S. Court of Appeals for the First Circuit]] but settled out of court in May 2019, with no money changing hands. ''Techdirt'' 's articles remain online with an added link to a rebuttal on Ayyadurai's website.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Farivar |first1=Cyrus |title=Defamation lawsuit brought by self-proclaimed email 'inventor' settles |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/defamation-lawsuit-brought-self-proclaimed-email-inventor-settles-n1007196 |accessdate=June 5, 2019 |work=NBC News |date=May 17, 2019 |url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529140115/https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/defamation-lawsuit-brought-self-proclaimed-email-inventor-settles-n1007196 |archivedate=May 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/joint-press-statement-on-behalf-of-dr-shiva-ayyadurai-and-techdirt-michael-masnick-and-leigh-beadon-300849406.html|title=Joint Press Statement On Behalf Of Dr. Shiva Ayyadurai And Techdirt, Michael Masnick, And Leigh Beadon|last=Harder LLP|date=May 14, 2019|website=PR Newswire|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Other actions ===\nIn January 2017, Harder threatened the [[Diaspora (social network)|Diaspora Foundation]] with legal action unless it removed three posts by Roy Schestowitz that Harder alleged were \"defamatory\" towards Ayyadurai.<ref name=diaspora/> (The Diaspora Foundation is part of the Free Software Support Network, which is in turn run by [[Eben Moglen]] and the [[Software Freedom Law Center]].)<ref name=diaspora>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2017/01/lawyer-for-inventor-of-e-mail-sends-threat-letter-over-social-media-posts/|title=Lawyer for 'inventor of e-mail' sends threat letter over social media posts|last=Mullin|first=Joe|date=January 16, 2017|newspaper=Ars Technica|access-date=2017-02-20|work=|last2=Farivar|first2=Cyrus|language=en-us|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nBeginning in 2014, Ayyadurai was romantically connected with the actress [[Fran Drescher]]. On September 7, 2014, Ayyadurai and Drescher participated in a ceremony at Drescher's beach house. Both tweeted that they had gotten married,<ref>{{cite tweet |first=Fran |last=Drescher |date=2014-09-07|title=Surprise!!!!! We got married!|user=frandrescher|number=508781239877128194}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |author=VA Shiva Ayyadurai |date=September 7, 2014 |title=I married my warrior princess @frandrescher who my mom in Gods great Heaven sent. Be The Light - Know the Truth - Find Your Way |user=va_shiva |number=508833431661182976 |url=https://twitter.com/va_shiva/status/508833431661182976 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909023638/https://twitter.com/va_shiva/status/508833431661182976 |archivedate=September 9, 2014 }}</ref> and the event was widely reported as such.<ref name=\"LATimesMarriage\">{{cite news|last1=Saad|first1=Nardine|title=Fran Drescher of 'The Nanny' marries Shiva Ayyadurai|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-fran-drescher-married-wedding-shiva-ayyadurai-20140908-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times |date=September 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.people.com/article/fran-drescher-marries-shiva-ayyadura|title = Fran Drescher Marries Shiva Ayyadurai|last = Gabrielle|first = Olya|date = September 9, 2014|work = People|access-date =  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Fran Drescher Marries Boyfriend Shiva Ayyadurai, aka the Inventor of Email?!|url = http://www.eonline.com/news/576704/fran-drescher-marries-boyfriend-shiva-ayyadurai-aka-the-inventor-of-email|accessdate = 2015-07-08|date = September 7, 2014|website = E!|last = Vulpo|first = Mike}}</ref> Ayyadurai later said it was not \"a formal wedding or marriage\", but a celebration of their \"friendship in a spiritual ceremony with close friends and her family\".<ref>{{cite web|title = Interview with Dr. V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai, The Inventor of Email and Systems Scientist|url = http://tamilnadu.com/entertainment/personalities/interview-with-dr-v-a-shiva-ayyadurai-the-inventor-of-email-and-systems-scientist.html|website = Tamil Nadu|accessdate = |date = November 25, 2014|last = Kumar|first = Vipin}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = About Dr. V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai - V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai, Inventor of Email|url = http://vashiva.com/about-va-shiva-ayyadurai/|accessdate = July 9, 2015|website = VA Shiva|publisher = V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai}}</ref> The couple split up in September 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://komonews.com/news/entertainment/actress-fran-drescher-splits-from-husband|title=Actress Fran Drescher splits from husband|last=|first=|date=September 4, 2016|work=[[KOMO-TV|Komonews.com]]|agency=World Entertainment News Network|access-date=|via=}}</ref>\n==Books==\n* {{cite book |title=The Internet Publicity Guide: How To Maximize Your Marketing And Promotion In Cyberspace |author=V. A. Shiva |isbn=978-1880559604 |year=1997 |publisher=Allworth Press |location=New York |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/internetpublicit0000shiv }}\n* {{cite book |title=All-American Indian: This Fight Is Your Fight - The Battle to Save America from the Elites Who Think They Know Better\n|author=V. A. Shiva Ayyadurai |isbn=978-0998504926 | year=2017 | publisher=General Interactive, LLC}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://vashiva.com/}}\n*[http://inventorofemail.com/Shiva-Ayyadurai.asp Ayyadurai's response to ''Techdirt'']\n*[https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190518/23370542236/laying-out-all-evidence-shiva-ayyadurai-did-not-invent-email.shtml ''Techdirt'' 's response to Ayyadurai]\n\n{{Scholia}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ayyadurai, Shiva}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:American male scientists of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Livingston High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Livingston, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Siddha medicine]]\n[[Category:American people of Tamil descent]]\n[[Category:People from Virudhunagar district]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 United States elections]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name              = Shiva Ayyadurai\n|image             = V.A.Shiva.2012.jpg\n|caption           = Ayyadurai in 2012\n|birth_name        = Vellayappa Ayyadurai Shiva\n|birth_date        = {{birth date and age|1963|12|2}}\n|birth_place       = [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]]\n|party             = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]<ref name=\"Massachusetts 2020 General Election\">{{cite web |title=Massachusetts 2020 General Election |url=https://www.thegreenpapers.com/G20/MA |website=The Green Papers|accessdate=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n|death_date        = \n|death_place       = \n|partner          = [[Fran Drescher]] (2014-2016)\n|education         = [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]], [[Master of Science|MS]], [[Master of Engineering|MEng]], [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]])\n|website           = {{URL|vashiva.com}}\n|module            = {{Infobox scientist\n|embed             = yes\n|fields            = [[Systems biology]]<br>[[Computer science]]<br>[[Scientific visualization]]<br>[[Traditional medicine]]\n|doctoral_advisor  = Forbes Dewey\n|academic_advisors = [[Robert S. Langer]]}}\n}}\n'''V. A. Shiva Ayyadurai''' (born '''Vellayappa Ayyadurai Shiva''',<ref name=\"mittech\"/> December 2, 1963)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/va.shiva.ayyadurai/about|title=V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref><ref name=\"history by lawsuit\"/> is an [[Indian Americans|Indian American]] [[scientist]], [[engineer]], and [[entrepreneur]]. <!-- do not edit the next sentence, unless there is consensus -- see Talk page -->He is notable for his widely disputed claim to be the \"inventor of [[email]]\",<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rajan |first1=Nadangopal |title=The inventor of email is still alive, insists India-born scientist |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/technology/tech-news-technology/the-inventor-of-email-is-still-alive-says-india-born-scientist/ |accessdate=5 July 2018 |work=The Indian Express |quote=\"CORRECTION: THE INVENTOR OF EMAIL IS STILL ALIVE,\" screams an e-mail not from the deceased Ray Tomlinson, but Dr VA  Shiva Ayyadurai.}}</ref> based on the electronic mail [[software]] called \"EMAIL\" he wrote as a [[New Jersey]] [[high school]] student in the late 1970s.<ref name=SmithsonianStatement /><ref name=chomsky-idgns /> Initial reports that repeated Ayyadurai's assertion\u2014from organizations such as ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and the [[Smithsonian Institution]]\u2014were followed by public retractions.<ref name=SmithsonianStatement /><ref name=washingtonpost>{{cite news|last=Kolawole|first=Emi|title=Smithsonian acquires documents from inventor of 'EMAIL' program|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/on-innovations/va-shivaayyadurai-inventor-of-e-mail-honored-by-smithsonian/2012/02/17/gIQA8gQhKR_story.html|accessdate=11 June 2012|newspaper=Washington Post|date=February 17, 2012|quote=\"incorrectly referred to V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai as the inventor of electronic messaging\"}}</ref> These corrections were triggered by objections from historians and [[ARPANET]] pioneers who pointed out that [[History of email|email was already actively used]] in the early 1970s.<ref name=\"history by lawsuit\">{{cite web|last1=Mullin|first1=Joe|last2=Farivar|first2=Cyrus|title=History by lawsuit: After Gawker's demise, the 'inventor of e-mail' targets Techdirt|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2017/06/shivas-war-one-mans-quest-to-convince-the-world-that-he-invented-e-mail/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=16 June 2017|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nAyyadurai also gained recognition for two reports: the first questioning the working conditions of India's largest scientific agency; the second questioning the safety of [[genetically modified food|genetically modified]] [[soybean]]s. Ayyadurai holds four degrees from the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] (MIT), including a [[Ph.D.]] in [[biological engineering]], and is a [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright]] grant recipient.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.mit.edu/2007/east-west-0917|title=East Meets West: Armed with 4 MIT Degrees, Shiva Ayyadurai Embarks on New Adventure|last=Trafton|first=Anne|date=September 17, 2007|work=MIT Tech Talk|publisher=MIT|quote=\"In the 26 years since he first arrived at MIT as a freshman, V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai has earned four MIT degrees and started two multimillion dollar companies. This fall, he will use his most recent degree, a Ph.D. in computational systems biology, and a Fulbright Scholarship to explore one of his lifelong interests: the intersection of Eastern and Western medicine.\"|access-date=10 November 2016|via=}}</ref> He garnered 3.4% of the vote as an [[Independent politician|independent]] candidate in the [[United States Senate election in Massachusetts, 2018|2018 United States Senate election in Massachusetts]] and is running as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] in the [[2020 United States Senate election in Massachusetts|2020 U.S. Senate election in Massachusetts]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nShiva Ayyadurai was born Vellayappa Ayyadurai Shiva in 1963, in Bombay (now [[Mumbai]]), [[Maharashtra]].<ref name=\"mittech\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://vashiva.com/yes-a-darkie-invented-email-get-over-it/|title=Yes, A \"Darkie\" Invented Email. Get Over It. - V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai, Inventor of Email|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-13}}</ref><ref name=\"lokvani\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lokvani.com/lokvani/article.php?article_id=4379|title=Lokvani Talks to Dr. Shiva Ayyadurai|last=Saigal|first=Ranjani|date=November 3, 2007|publisher=lokvani.com|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> He grew up in the Muhavur village in [[Rajapalayam]], [[Tamil Nadu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://epaperbeta.timesofindia.com/Article.aspx?eid=31807&articlexml=Its-very-difficult-to-compare-an-employer-with-30082015101051|title= It's very difficult to compare an employer with an inventor: Shiva Ayyadurai |work=The Times of India|accessdate=2018-08-25|date=2015-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/be-job-providers-and-not-job-seekers/article4958821.ece|title= Be job providers and not job seekers |work=The Hindu|date=2013-07-27|accessdate=2018-08-25}}</ref> At the age of seven, he left with his family to live in the United States.<ref name=\"timmons\"/>\n\nIn 1978, as a 14-year-old high school student, Ayyadurai attended a summer program at the [[Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences]] of [[New York University]] (NYU) to study [[computer programming]]. While a student at [[Livingston High School (New Jersey)|Livingston High School]] in New Jersey, Ayyadurai volunteered at the [[University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey|University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey]] (UMDNJ) where his mother worked.<ref name=future>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=K3bVUladlakC&pg=PA160&lpg=PA160&dq=UMDNJ+research+fellow+ayyadurai#v=onepage&q=UMDNJ%20research%20fellow%20ayyadurai&f=false|title=Future Visions on Biomedicine and Bioinformatics 1|first=Swamy|last=Laxminarayan|publisher=[[Springer (publisher)|Springer]]|date=January 1, 2011|isbn=9783642150517}}</ref> There he created an email system to emulate the paper-based interoffice mail system then in use at the medical school.<ref name=\"future\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |last=Garlin |first=Caleb |url=https://www.wired.com/2012/06/noam-chomsky-email/ |title=Who Invented Email? Just Ask ... Noam Chomsky |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=June 16, 2012 |access-date=2017-08-25}}</ref> In 1982, he registered the [[copyright]] for his software, called \"EMAIL\", as well as for the program's user documentation.<ref name=\"SmithsonianStatement\" />\n\nAyyadurai's [[undergraduate degree]] from MIT was in [[electrical engineering]] and [[computer science]]; he took a [[master's degree]] in visual studies from the [[MIT Media Laboratory]] on [[scientific visualization]]; concurrently, he completed another master's degree in mechanical engineering, also from MIT; and in 2007, he obtained a Ph.D. in biological engineering from MIT in [[systems biology]], with his [[thesis]] focusing on modeling the whole cell by integrating molecular pathway models.<ref name=east>{{cite web|url=http://web.mit.edu/newsoffice/2007/east-west-0917.html|accessdate=9 June 2012|title=East meets West|date=September 17, 2007|work=MIT News|first=Anne|last=Trafton|publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology}}</ref><ref>{{cite document|title=DSpace@MIT: Scalable computational architecture for integrating biological pathway models|publisher=Massachusetts Institute of Technology|year=2007|first=Shiva|last=Ayyadurai|hdl = 1721.1/42384}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|first1=VA Shiva|last1=Ayyadurai|first2=C. Forbes Jr. |last2=Dewey |journal=Cellular and Molecular Bioengineering |date=March 2011|volume=4|issue=1|pages=28\u201345|doi=10.1007/s12195-010-0143-x|title=CytoSolve: A Scalable Computational Method for Dynamic Integration of Multiple Molecular Pathway Models|pmid=21423324|pmc=3032229}}</ref> In 2007, he was awarded a Fulbright U.S. Student Program grant to study the integration of [[Siddha medicine|Siddha]], a system of [[traditional medicine]] developed in [[South India]], with modern systems biology.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.fulbrightonline.org/component/filter/?view=filter|title=V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai, MIT, Biology, India, 2007, \"Pathways to Siddha and Systems Biology\"|website=Fulbright U.S. Student Program|accessdate=8 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=east/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Millennium Cybernetics===\nIn 1994, Ayyadurai founded a company called Millennium Cybernetics, which produces [[email management]] software originally called Xiva and now called EchoMail.<ref name=\"mittech\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/400629/dr-e-mail-will-see-you-now/|title=Dr. Email Will See You Now|last=Shapley|first=Deborah|date=January 1, 2000|work=MIT Technology Review|accessdate=2016-08-11|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000511125636/http://www.techreview.com/articles/jan00/shapley.htm|archivedate=May 11, 2000|url-status=dead}}</ref> The software analyzes incoming email messages to organizations before either replying automatically or forwarding it to the most relevant department. By 2001, customers included [[Kmart]], [[American Express]], and [[Calvin Klein]], as well as more than thirty [[United States Senator|U.S. senators]] to help handle constituent email. EchoMail competed with more established [[customer relationship management]] software that had an email component.<ref name=\"mittech\" /><ref name=\"bulkeley\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB1005776873756157960|title=Echomail provides an answer for the avalanche of e-mail|author=William Bulkeley|date=November 15, 2011|accessdate=2016-11-08|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On its website, EchoMail describes Ayyadurai as the \"Inventor of Email\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://echomail.com/|title=EchoMail|publisher=echomail.com|accessdate=2018-01-13|quote=[http://www.inventorofemail.com/ The Inventor of Email\u2122]}}</ref>\n\n===CSIR India===\nIn 2009, Ayyadurai was hired by India's [[Council of Scientific and Industrial Research]] (CSIR), India's largest science agency, by its director general, [[Samir K. Brahmachari]]. CSIR was mandated to create a new company, CSIR Tech, that would establish businesses using the research conducted by the country's many publicly owned laboratories. Ayyadurai reported that he had spent months trying to create a business plan for CSIR Tech, but received no response from Brahmachari. Ayyadurai then distributed a draft plan, which was not authorized by CSIR, to the agency's scientists that requested feedback and criticized management. His job offer was subsequently withdrawn five months after the position was offered.<ref name=timmons>{{cite news|last=Timmons|first=Heather|title=Some Indians Find It Tough to Go Home Again|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/28/business/global/28return.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=11 June 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=November 27, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Nature\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.nature.com/news/2009/091109/full/462152a.html|title=Report row ousts top Indian scientist |journal=Nature | date=November 9, 2009 |accessdate=19 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nBrahmachari said that \"the offer was withdrawn as [Ayyadurai] did not accept the [[terms and conditions]] and demanded unreasonable compensation.\"  In its report, ''[[The New York Times]]'' said that \"going public with such accusations is highly unusual. Mr. Ayyadurai circulated his paper not just to the agency's scientists but to journalists, and wrote about his situation to [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Manmohan Singh]].\" In that letter, Ayyadurai said his report was intended to explore institutional barriers to CSIR's entrepreneurial mandate. He said that CSIR scientists reported that \"they work in a [[medieval]], [[feudalism|feudal]] environment\" that required a \"major overhaul\". The letter was co-authored by a colleague, Deepak Sardana. [[Pushpa Mittra Bhargava|Pushpa Bhargava]], founding director of the CSIR's Centre for Cellular and Molecular Biology in Hyderabad, endorsed the letter, calling Ayyadurai's sacking the worst of many cases he had seen of \"vindictiveness in the CSIR\" and accused CSIR administration of being \"impervious to healthy and fair criticism\". The incident was seen as an example of the difficulty some Indian [[expatriate]] professionals may encounter returning home after growing accustomed to the more direct management style of the U.S.<ref name=\"timmons\" /><ref name=\"Nature\" />\n\n===Genetically modified food===\nIn 2015, Ayyadurai published a paper that applied systems biology, which uses [[mathematical model]]ing, to predict the chemical composition of genetically modified (GM) soybeans, and whether or not they were [[substantial equivalence|substantially equivalent]] to unmodified soybeans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theecologist.org/News/news_round_up/2950586/gmo_and_glyphosate_wars_rage.html |author=Oliver Tickell |title=GMO and glyphosate wars rage |publisher=The Ecologist |date=July 16, 2015 |accessdate=2016-11-09}}</ref> The paper claimed that GM soybeans have lower levels of the [[antioxidant]] [[glutathione]] and higher levels of [[carcinogen]]ic [[formaldehyde]], making the modified soybean substantially different, contrary to previous safety assessments.<ref>{{cite news|author=Vishwanath Kulkarni |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/opinion/safety-assessments-of-gmos-are-nonexistent/article7674558.ece |title=Safety assessments of GMOs are non-existent |newspaper=The Hindu Business Line |date=September 21, 2015 |accessdate=2016-11-09}}</ref> Shortly after publication, Ayyadurai embarked on a speaking tour of the U.S. At the [[National Press Club]], he said that genetic modification had \"fundamentally modified the metabolic system of the soy\", disrupting the \"beautiful way of detoxifying [formaldehyde]\" present in non-GM soy.<ref>Ayyadurai, V.A. Shiva. (2015) \"[https://www.facebook.com/va.shiva.ayyadurai/videos/vb.212669305456262/963543970368788/?type=2&theater Systems Biology reveals GMO testing is flawed]\", ''Facebook''. Retrieved August 26, 2018.</ref>\n\nThe [[European Food Safety Agency]] evaluated the paper and determined that \"the author's conclusions are not supported\" due to the lack of information on the input into the model, the fact that the model was not validated and because no measurements of soybeans were made to establish whether GM soy actually contained elevated levels of formaldehyde.<ref>{{cite journal|author=European Food Safety Authority |title=EFSA scientific advice to EC on new scientific information in relation to the risk assessment of genetically modified organisms |journal=EFSA Supporting Publications |volume=12 |issue=11 |date=November 3, 2015 |doi=10.2903/sp.efsa.2015.EN-885 }}</ref> Plant scientist [[Kevin Folta]] noted that there was \"no evidence ever published ... that shows a difference in formaldehyde between GM and non-GM varieties\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geneticliteracyproject.org/2015/07/21/kevin-folta-debunks-pay-for-play-paper-supposedly-finding-formaldehyde-in-gmos/|title=Kevin Folta debunks pay for play paper finding formaldehyde in GMOs|publisher=Genetic Literacy Project |date=July 21, 2015 |first=Kevin |last=Folta |authorlink=Kevin Folta|accessdate=2016-11-09}}</ref> Ayyadurai later cited the study as evidence of a lack of safety standards for GM foods and bet [[Monsanto]] a $10 million building if they could prove that they were safe. Monsanto did not take up the challenge but stated that GM food did indeed undergo safety assessments that \"are more rigorous and thorough than assessments of any other food crop in history\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Tanya Lewis |url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/scientist-bets-millions-that-gmos-unsafe-2015-11 |title=Scientist bets millions that GMOs unsafe |website=Business Insider |date=November 12, 2015 |accessdate=2016-11-09}}</ref> In 2016, Ayyadurai promised to donate $10 million to [[Hillary Clinton]]'s [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016|presidential campaign]] if she could disprove his research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://patch.com/new-jersey/montclair/nj-scientist-gives-hillary-clinton-10-million-gmo-challenge-0 |title=NJ Scientist Gives Hillary Clinton a $10 Million GMO Challenge |publisher=Patch |date=February 1, 2016 |accessdate=2016-11-09}}</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\nOn March 17, 2017, Ayyadurai filed as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate in the 2018 United States Senate election in Massachusetts, running against incumbent [[Elizabeth Warren]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2017/03/man-who-claims-he-invented-e-mail-is-now-running-for-us-senate/|title=Man who claims he invented e-mail is now running for US Senate|last=Farivar|first=Cyrus|date=March 29, 2017|work=Ars Technica|access-date=2017-03-30|language=en-us}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/news/politics/2017/02/28/cambridge-man-who-says-he-invented-email-says-he-will-challenge-elizabeth-warren-in-2018|title=Cambridge man who says he invented email says he will challenge Elizabeth Warren in 2018|last=DeCosta-Klip|first=Nik |date=February 28, 2017 |work=Boston.com|access-date=2017-03-17|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners, LLC|language=}}</ref> On November 11, 2017, he announced he would run as an independent<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/news/2017/11/11/shiva-ayyadurai-independent/|title=Shiva Ayyadurai Is Running for Senate as an Independent|last=Buell|first=Spencer|date=2017-11-11|work=Boston Magazine|access-date=2017-11-11|language=en-US}}</ref> and ultimately garnered 3.4% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/11/06/us/elections/results-massachusetts-elections.html|title=Massachusetts Election Results|last=|first=|date=|work=New York Times|access-date=2018-11-11|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAyyadurai said that Senator Warren was at the top of a U.S. \"neo-[[caste system]]\" composed of \"academics, career politicians and lawyer/lobbyists\", a \"spineless clan\" who never expect to be challenged. He said he would take a science and engineering perspective on problem solving, focusing on immigration, education and innovation. He called for secure borders and an end to [[Sanctuary city|sanctuary cities]], support for more choices in [[public education]], and for more scrutiny of \"[[pay-to-play]]\" science research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/news/2017/05/08/republican-entrepreneur-waging-2018-bid-against.html|title=Republican entrepreneur waging 2018 bid against Elizabeth Warren|last=Young|first=Shannon|date=May 8, 2017|website=Boston Business Journal|access-date=2017-05-21}}</ref> Ayyadurai has accused Warren of voting in favor of the [[Farmer Assurance Provision]] and against a GM labeling bill sponsored by Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] of [[Vermont]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://shiva4senate.com/press-conference-elizabeth-warren-marty-walsh-collusion/|title=Press Conference: Elizabeth Warren + Marty Walsh Collusion - Shiva For Senate in Massachusetts|date=25 October 2017|publisher=}}</ref> However, the Act was reportedly passed to avoid a [[government shutdown]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/monsanto-protection-act/|title=FACT CHECK: Monsanto Protection Act|publisher=}}</ref> and Warren petitioned the [[Food and Drug Administration]] for \"regulations to ensure that the labeling of GMO products is fair, standardized and transparent.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2013/09/elizabeth-warren-joins-gmo-labeling-fray-096928|title=Warren joins GMO labeling fray|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2017, Ayyadurai spoke at the [[Boston Free Speech rally]], a gathering which drew large counter-protests and whose speaker line-up included [[right-wing extremist]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/08/14/senate-candidate-plans-address-free-speech-rally-common/CzFnJ4c4u1wOjojtdeLUzM/story.html |title=US Senate candidate plans to address 'free speech' rally on Common |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=August 14, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2017/08/17/speakers-list-for-boston-free-speech-rally-include-right-wing-extremist/6xWnzHZwrjq8svoRbPN1NP/story.html |title=Speakers list for 'free speech' rally includes right-wing extremists |work=[[The Boston Globe]] |date=August 17, 2017}}</ref> Ayyadurai later disputed how the event was characterized, tweeting that the \"establishment\" wanted to block attendance and media coverage and sought a \"[[race war|Race War]] to divide us\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2017/08/19/gop_senate_candidate_shiva_ayyadurais_speech_at_boston_free_speech_rally.html|title=GOP Senate Candidate Shiva Ayyadurai Called For Peace And Love At Boston 'Free Speech Rally' |last=Harris|first=Tim|date=August 19, 2017|website=www.realclearpolitics.com|access-date=2017-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/18/us/demonstration-race-free-speech-boston-charlottesville.html|title=Protesters Flood Streets, and Trump Offers a Measure of Praise |first1=Katharine Q. |last1=Seelye |first2=Alan |last2=Blinder |last3=Bidgood |first3=Jess |date=August 18, 2017 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=2017-08-25 |language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In April 2018, the city of [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]] threatened Ayyadurai with daily [[fine (penalty)|fines]] for an alleged zoning code violation if he did not remove a banner on his campaign bus. The banner featured his campaign slogan, \"Only a real Indian can defeat a fake Indian\", together with a digitally altered image depicting Warren in a [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] headdress, a reference to her claim to be of part [[Cherokee]] descent.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/real-indian-running-against-elizabeth-warren-shiva-ayyadurai-sues-signs-calling-her-fake-indian/|title=\"Real Indian\" running against Sen. Elizabeth Warren defends sign calling her \"Fake Indian\" |first=Christina |last=Capatides |date=April 24, 2018 |work=[[CBS News]] |access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> The city reversed its position the following month and Ayyadurai, in turn, dropped a lawsuit alleging that his free speech rights had been violated.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2018/may/17/cambridge-rescinds-order-remove-anti-warren-fake-i/|title=Cambridge rescinds order to remove anti-Warren 'fake Indian' campaign signs|last=Richardson|first=Valerie|date=May 17, 2018|work=The Washington Times|access-date=2018-05-19|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAyyadurai is running as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] in the [[2020 United States Senate election in Massachusetts|2020 U.S. Senate election in Massachusetts]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2020/01/29/meet-year-old-who-asking-legislature-let-her-vote-this-year-presidential-primary/jRGO7IBieu5c9vGeSHm1LK/story.html|title=Meet the 17-year-old who is asking the Legislature to let her vote in this year's presidential primary - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2018/10/17/shiva-ayyadurai-provocative-candidate-who-represents-our-bizarre-political-climate/o2bh5D3wkie8qqvjYRUHYI/story.html|title=Shiva Ayyadurai: the candidate who represents our bizarre political climate - The Boston Globe|website=BostonGlobe.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n===COVID-19 misinformation===\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] Ayyadurai used social media to spread various conspiracy theories and misinformation about the pandemic. In January 2020 he claimed that the coronavirus was patented by the [[Pirbright Institute]], but the patent he referenced relates to ''[[avian coronavirus]]'', which infects birds, not [[SARS-CoV-2]], the virus responsible for the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Funke |first1=Daniel |last2=Kertscher |first2=Tom |title=Fact-checking hoaxes and conspiracies about the coronavirus |url=https://www.politifact.com/article/2020/jan/24/fact-checking-hoaxes-and-conspiracies-about-corona/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=PolitiFact |date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nAyyadurai claimed to be a 'student of medicine' during a March 30, 2020 interview with Next News Network despite having no medical or immunology credentials<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=youtu.be&v=xf-qv9o8nq8&fbclid=IwAR3zbFBxRR5_63rBzAo499l2FFpaaKkIW7WD8f9Bx8Vj9LAPLnYlmEYrVxY&app=desktop}}</ref>. He described an unsupported model of immunologic health. During the interview, he also disputed the fact that [[HIV]] is linked with [[AIDS]]; alleging [[Anthony Fauci]]'s mentor [[Robert Gallo]], winner of Nobel Prize in Physiology of Medicine in 2008 for his work on the discovery of HIV, fabricated the evidence linking HIV with AIDS and created a 'bogus' HIV test, referring to the HIV ELISA test that is commonly used today with a 99-100% sensitivity <ref>{{cite journal |pmid=2146552}}</ref>. \n\nHe alleged that the coronavirus was spread by the \"[[deep state]]\" and accused [[Anthony Fauci]], director of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases, of being a \"Deep State Plant\". Ayyadurai called for Fauci to be fired.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goforth |first1=Claire |title=Why Dr. Fauci has become conspiracy theorists' coronavirus scapegoat |url=https://www.dailydot.com/debug/coronavirus-conspiracy-theorists-fire-fauci-shiva-ayyadurai/ |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=The Daily Dot |date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020 he published an open letter to president [[Donald Trump]] where he wrote that a national lockdown was unnecessary and advocated that large doses of vitamins could prevent and cure the disease.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Charlie |title=Republican Senate hopeful Shiva Ayyadurai calls for firing of U.S. pandemic-control czar Dr. Anthony Fauci |url=https://www.straight.com/news/republican-senate-hopeful-shiva-ayyadurai-calls-for-firing-of-us-pandemic-control-czar-dr |accessdate=8 April 2020 |work=The Georgia Straight |date=5 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shiva4senate.com/immune-and-economic-health-for-america-coronavirus/|title=Immune and Economic Health for America Coronavirus|last=Shiva|first=Ayyadurai|date=March 23, 2020|website=Shiva For Senate in Massachusetts|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>\n\n==\"EMAIL\" invention controversy==\nAyyadurai makes the widely disputed claim to be the \"inventor of email\". His claim is based on the software he wrote as a 14-year-old student at Livingston High School in New Jersey. In 1979\u2014some sources say 1978\u2014he wrote an implementation of an interoffice email system, which he called ''EMAIL''.<ref name=SmithsonianStatement /><ref name=chomsky-idgns />\n\nA November 2011 ''[[Time Magazine|Time]]'' Techland interview by Doug Aamoth, entitled \"The Man Who Invented Email\", argued that EMAIL represented the birth of email \"as we currently know it\". In that interview, Ayyadurai recalled that Les Michelson, the former particle scientist at [[Brookhaven National Labs]] who assigned Ayyadurai the project, had the idea of creating an electronic mail system that uses the header conventions of a hardcopy memorandum. Ayyadurai recalled Michelson as saying: \"Your job is to convert that into an electronic format. Nobody's done that before.\"<ref name=techland>{{cite news|last=Aamoth|first=Doug|title=The Man Who Invented Email|url=http://techland.time.com/2011/11/15/the-man-who-invented-email/|accessdate=11 June 2012|newspaper=Time Magazine: Techland|date=November 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, the Smithsonian [[National Museum of American History]] announced that Ayyadurai had donated \"a trove of documents and code\" related to EMAIL. Initially, the museum\u2014inaccurately\u2014cited the program as one of the first to include the now common \"subject and body fields, [[inbox]]es, [[outbox]]es, cc, bcc, attachments, and others. He based these elements directly off of the interoffice mail memos the doctors had been using for years, in hopes of convincing people to actually use the newfangled technology.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.smithsonianmag.com/aroundthemall/2012/02/a-piece-of-email-history-comes-to-the-american-history-museum/|title=A Piece of Email History Comes to the American History Museum|date=February 22, 2012|accessdate=11 June 2012|first=Joseph|last=Stromberg|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]]}}</ref>\n\nAyyadurai's claims drew editorial clarifications and corrections, as well as criticism from industry observers. In a followup to its acquisition announcement, the Smithsonian stated that it was not claiming that Ayyadurai had invented email, but rather that the materials were historically notable for other reasons related to trends in computer education and the role of computers in medicine.<ref name=\"SmithsonianStatement\">{{Cite press release |url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/news/pressrelease.cfm?key=29&newskey=1465 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427014952/http://americanhistory.si.edu/news/pressrelease.cfm?key=29&newskey=1465 |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 27, 2012 |title=Statement from the National Museum of American History: Collection of Materials from V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai |date=February 23, 2012|accessdate=19 February 2013|publisher=National Museum of American History |quote=\"Exchanging messages through computer systems, what most people call 'email', predates the work of Ayyadurai.\"}}</ref> The Smithsonian statement distinguished Ayyadurai's achievement by noting that historians in the field, \"have largely focused on the use of large networked computers, especially those linked to the ARPANET in the early 1970s\". The statement pointed out that Ayyadurai's approach instead \"focused on communications between linked computer terminals in an ordinary office situation\".<ref name=\"SmithsonianStatement\" /> ''The Washington Post'' also followed up with a correction of errors in its earlier report on the Smithsonian acquisition, stating that it incorrectly referred to Ayyadurai as the inventor of electronic messaging; the 'bcc', 'cc', 'to' and 'from' fields existed previously; Ayyadurai had not been honored as the \"inventor of email\".<ref name=\"washingtonpost\" />\n\nWriting for ''[[Gizmodo]]'', [[Sam Biddle]] argued that email was developed a decade before EMAIL, beginning with [[Ray Tomlinson]]'s sending the first text letter between two [[ARPANET]]-connected computers in 1971.<ref>i.e. the first ''network'' email using the \"@\" syntax; email between users on the same mainframe was already common.</ref> Biddle quoted Tomlinson: \"[We] had most of the headers needed to deliver the message (to:, cc:, etc.) as well as identifying the sender (from:) and when the message was sent (date:) and what the message was about.\"  Biddle allowed for the possibility that Ayyadurai may have coined the term \"EMAIL\" and used the header terms without being aware of earlier work, but maintained that the historical record isn't definitive on either point. Biddle wrote that \"laying claim to the name of a product that's the generic term for a universal technology gives you acres of weasel room. But creating a type of airplane named AIRPLANE doesn't make you [[Wilbur Wright]].\"<ref name=\"giz120305\">{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Biddle |work=[[Gizmodo]] |title=Corruption, Lies, and Death Threats: The Crazy Story of the Man Who Pretended to Invent Email |url=https://gizmodo.com/5888702/corruption-lies-and-death-threats-the-crazy-story-of-the-man-who-pretended-to-invent-email |date=March 5, 2012 |accessdate=5 March 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306204240/http://gizmodo.com/5888702/corruption-lies-and-death-threats-the-crazy-story-of-the-man-who-pretended-to-invent-email|archivedate=2012-03-06}}</ref>\n\nThomas Haigh, a historian of information technology at the [[University of Wisconsin]], wrote that \"Ayyadurai is, to the best of my knowledge, the only person to have claimed for him or herself the title 'inventor of email'.\" Haigh argued that while EMAIL was impressive for a teenager's work, it contained no features that were not present on previous electronic mail systems and had no obvious influence on later systems. \"The most striking thing about Ayyadurai's claim to have invented electronic mail is how late it comes. Somehow it took him thirty years to alert the world to [his] greatest achievement\".<ref name=SIGCIS-Haigh>{{cite web|title=Did V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai Invent Email?|url=http://www.sigcis.org/ayyadurai|publisher=SIGCIS: Special Interest Group Computers, Information and Society|accessdate=9 June 2012|date=April 17, 2012|first=Thomas|last=Haigh}}</ref> Haigh wrote that by 1980, \"electronic mail had been in use at MIT for 15 years, Xerox had built a modern, mouse-driven graphical email system for office communication, Compuserve was selling email access to the public, and email had for many years been the most popular application on what was soon to become the Internet.\" <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Haigh|first1=Thomas|title=Seven Lessons from Bad History|journal=Communications of the ACM|date=September 2012|volume=55|issue=9|page=26|url=http://www.tomandmaria.com/tom/Writing/CACM-SevenLessons.pdf|accessdate=16 September 2014|doi=10.1145/2330667.2330676}}</ref>\n\nDavid Crocker, a member of the ARPANET research community, writing in the ''Post'', said, \"The reports incorrectly credited [EMAIL's] author, a 14-year old in the late 1970s, as the 'inventor' of email, long after it had become an established service on the ARPANET.\"<ref name=DavidCrockerWaPo>{{cite news|last=Crocker|first=David|title=A history of e-mail: Collaboration, innovation and the birth of a system|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/on-innovations/a-history-of-e-mail-collaboration-innovation-and-the-birth-of-a-system/2012/03/19/gIQAOeFEPS_story.html|accessdate=10 June 2012|newspaper=Washington Post|date=March 20, 2012}}</ref> Another computer historian, Marc Weber, a curator at the [[Computer History Museum]], said that by 1978, \"nearly all the features we're familiar with today had appeared on one system or another over the previous dozen years\", including [[emoticons]], [[mailing list]]s, [[flame war]]s, and [[spam mail]].<ref name=BostonMag />\n\nAfter the controversy unfolded, MIT disassociated itself from Ayyadurai's EMAIL Lab and funding was dropped. MIT also revoked Ayyadurai's contract to lecture at the bioengineering department.<ref name=\"BostonMag\" />\n\nAyyadurai characterized the earlier work of Tomlinson, [[Tom Van Vleck]] and others as [[text messaging]], rather than an electronic version of an interoffice mail system.<ref name=techland /><ref name=BostonMag>{{cite news|last=Nanos|first=Janelle|title=Return to Sender|url=http://www.bostonmagazine.com/2012/05/shiva-ayyaduri-email-us-postal-service/|accessdate=11 June 2012|newspaper=Boston Magazine|date=June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180307102703/https://www.bostonmagazine.com/2012/05/30/shiva-ayyaduri-email-us-postal-service/#|archive-date=2018-03-07|url-status=live}}</ref> Responding to his critics on his personal website,<ref name=giz120305 /><ref name=BostonMag /> Ayyadurai described EMAIL as \"the first of its kind\u2014a fully integrated, database-driven, electronic translation of the interoffice paper mail system derived from the ordinary office situation.\" He maintained that EMAIL was the first electronic mail system to integrate an easy-to-use [[user interface]], a [[word processor]], a [[relational database]], and a modular inter-communications protocol \"integrated together in one single and holistic platform to ensure high-reliability and user-friendliness network-wide.\"<ref name=AyyaduraiResponse>{{cite web|last=Ayyadurai|first=VA Shiva|title=EMAIL (UMDNJ, 1978)|url=http://www.inventorofemail.com/va-shiva-personal-statement-inventor-of-email.asp|work=The Inventor of Email: innovation any time, any place, by anybody|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref> Ayyadurai presented a [[press release]] on his webpage asserting that his undergraduate professor [[Noam Chomsky]], of MIT's Department of Linguistics and Philosophy, also supported his claims.<ref name=chomsky-idgns>{{cite web|url=http://www.computerworld.com/article/2503255/enterprise-applications/noam-chomsky-disputes-email-history.html|first=Joab|last=Jackson|title=Noam Chomsky disputes email history|publisher=Computerworld/IDGNS}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn March 2016, Ayyadurai alleged that the overlooking of his achievements was a result of [[racism]] and a conspiracy between mainstream media and the [[military\u2013industrial complex]], particularly [[Raytheon]], where Tomlinson worked on ARPANET. After Tomlinson's death, Ayyadurai told ''[[The Hindu]]'' that he believed that news outlets retracted their stories about him because, \"Raytheon advertises in publications like the ''[[Huffington Post]]'' and [[CNN]]\" and that if he were \"a white guy and had a copyright for email, I would have my photo on every stamp in the world.\"<ref name=\"the-hindu-raymond\">{{cite news|newspaper=The Hindu |date=March 7, 2016 |title=Not everybody loves Raymond|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/technology/who-invented-email-ray-tomlinson-or-shiva-ayyadurai/article8323987.ece}}</ref> The day after Tomlinson's death, Ayyadurai tweeted: \"I'm the low-caste, dark-skinned, Indian, who DID invent #email. Not Raytheon, who profits for war & death. Their mascot Tomlinson dies a liar\".<ref name=\"tweet-2016-03-06\">{{cite web|last=Ayyadurai|first=VA Shiva|title=Tweet from @va_shiva, March 6, 2016|url=https://twitter.com/va_shiva/status/706670699713335297}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Gawker'' ===\nIn May 2016, Ayyadurai filed suit against [[Gawker Media]] for $35 million, alleging that their website ''Gawker'' published \"false and [[defamation|defamatory]] statements\", causing \"substantial damage to Dr. Ayyadurai's personal and professional reputation and career.\" The filing also named writer Sam Biddle, executive editor John Cook, and Gawker founder and CEO [[Nick Denton]]. Gawker Media responded that, \"These claims to have invented email have been repeatedly debunked by the Smithsonian Institute{{sic}}, Gizmodo, the Washington Post and others.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/boston/news/2016/05/10/cambridge-man-who-claims-he-invented-email-sues.html|title=Cambridge man who claims he invented email sues Gawker for $35M - Boston Business Journal|last=Harris|first=David L.|date=May 10, 2016|website=Boston Business Journal|access-date=2016-05-16}}</ref><ref>[https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/2829697/Gov-Uscourts-Mad-180248-1-0.pdf ''Shiva Ayyadurai v. Gawker Media, et. al''., Complaint] (D. Mass, filed May 10, 2016)</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, the by-then-bankrupt Gawker Media [[Settlement (litigation)|settled]] the lawsuit with Ayyadurai for $750,000 as part of a broader settlement with wrestler [[Hulk Hogan]] and journalist Ashley Terrill, all of whom were represented by attorney [[Charles Harder]].<ref name=gizsettle>{{Cite news|url=https://gizmodo.com/internet-pioneers-slam-750-000-settlement-for-the-man-1788503950|title=Internet Pioneers Slam $750,000 Settlement for the 'Man Who Invented Email'|author=Mario Aguilar}}</ref> In a statement, Ayyadurai said that \"history will reflect that this settlement is a victory for truth\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/03/business/media/gawker-hulk-hogan-settlement.html|title=Gawker and Hulk Hogan Reach $31 Million Settlement|last=Ember|first=Sydney|date=November 2, 2016 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-11-04}}</ref> Biddle denounced the settlement and said he fully stood by his reporting.<ref name=giz1788495465>{{cite news|url=https://gizmodo.com/gawker-media-will-settle-with-hulk-hogan-and-other-liti-1788495465 | title=Gawker Media Will Settle With Hulk Hogan and Other Litigants for $32 Million |author=J.K. Trotter |work=Gizmodo |date=November 2, 2016 |accessdate=2016-11-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mattdrange/2016/11/02/gawker-media-close-to-reaching-settlement-with-hulk-hogan/|title=Gawker Reaches Settlement With Hulk Hogan For $31 Million|last=Mac|first=Ryan|date=November 2, 2016|work=|newspaper=Forbes|access-date=2016-11-03|via=}}</ref> Denton wrote that \"we expected to prevail\" in the Ayyadurai and Terrill lawsuits, \"but all-out legal war with\" billionaire [[Peter Thiel]], who financially backed Harder, was untenable in terms of cost, time and human toll.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nickdenton.org/a-hard-peace-e161e19bfaf|title=A hard peace|last=Denton|first=Nick|date=November 2, 2016|newspaper=nickdenton.com: Being myself|access-date=2016-11-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180502211504/https://nickdenton.org/a-hard-peace-e161e19bfaf#|archive-date=2018-05-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Katie Hafner]], the author of several books on Internet history\u2014including one on the development of ARPANET email\u2014said, \"This situation is both bizarre and appalling in that here we are simply trying to get the record straight, and [Ayyadurai has] managed to make money off claims that appear to be misleading.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gizmodo.com/internet-pioneers-slam-750-000-settlement-for-the-man-1788503950|title=Internet Pioneers Slam $750,000 Settlement for the 'Man Who Invented Email'|last=Aguilar|first=Mario|newspaper=Gizmodo|language=en-US|access-date=2016-11-10}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Techdirt'' ===\nIn January 2017, Ayyadurai, again represented by Harder, filed a $15 million libel lawsuit on similar grounds against ''[[Techdirt]]'' founder [[Mike Masnick]] and two other parties for a series of articles published beginning in September 2014.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/proclaimed-inventor-email-files-defamation-lawsuit-techdirts-michael-masnick-961008|title=Self-Proclaimed Inventor of Email Files Defamation Lawsuit Against Techdirt's Mike Masnick|last=Gardner|first=Eriq|date=January 5, 2017|work=|newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2017-01-07|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2017/01/05/email-inventor-techdirt/|title='Inventor of Email' Slaps Tech Site With $15M Libel Suit for Mocking His Claim|last=Roberts|first=Jeff John|date=January 5, 2017|website=Fortune|publisher=|access-date=2017-01-07}}</ref><ref>[https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/3252883/Techdirt-Emaillawsuit.pdf ''Shiva Ayyadurai v. Floor64 Inc et. al''., Complaint] (D. Mass, filed January 4, 2017)</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20170111/11440836465/techdirts-first-amendment-fight-life.shtml|title=Techdirt's First Amendment Fight For Its Life|last=Masnick|first=Mike|date=January 11, 2017|work=|newspaper=Techdirt|access-date=2017-01-16|via=}}</ref> In February, Masnick, represented by the firm Prince Lobel, filed two [[Motion (legal)#To dismiss|motions to dismiss]]. One motion argued that the articles were constitutionally protected opinion and written about a [[public figure]] without [[actual malice]]. The second motion asked for dismissal under [[Strategic lawsuit against public participation#California|California's anti-SLAPP law]] that compensates defendants for some legal expenses.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.co.uk/tech-policy/2017/02/techdirt-lawyers-ask-judge-to-throw-out-defamation-suit-over-inventor-of-e-mail/|title=Techdirt lawyers ask judge to throw out suit over 'Inventor of E-mail' |last=Mullin|first=Joe|date=February 18, 2017|newspaper=Ars Technica UK|access-date=2017-02-20|work=|language=en-us|via=}}</ref><ref>[https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/3468184/13-Main.pdf Memorandum of Floor64, Inc. and Michael Masnick in support of motion to dismiss pursuant to Fed. R. Civ. P. 12(B)(5) and 12(B)(6)] (D. Mass, filed February 17, 2017)</ref><ref>[https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/3468242/Techdirt-Memo-in-Support-of-Special-MN-to-Strike.pdf  Memorandum of defendants Floor64, Inc. and Michael Masnick in support of their special motion to strike plaintiff's complaint pursuant to the California Anti-SLAPP law] (D. Mass, filed February 17, 2017)</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, United States District Judge [[F. Dennis Saylor IV|F. Dennis Saylor]] dismissed the defamation claims against ''Techdirt'', but declined to strike the complaint under the anti-SLAPP law. In his ruling, Saylor wrote that definitions of \"email\" vary widely. Therefore, \"whether plaintiff's claim to have invented e-mail is 'fake' depends upon the operative definition of 'e-mail.' Because the definition does not have a single, objectively correct answer, the claim is incapable of being proved true or false.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ia800807.us.archive.org/7/items/gov.uscourts.mad.185980/gov.uscourts.mad.185980.48.0.pdf|title=Memorandum and Order on Defendants' Motion to Dismiss and to Strike|last=Saylor IV|first=F. Dennis|date=August 6, 2017|website=United States District Court, District of Massachusetts}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2017/09/1st-amendment-wins-in-self-proclaimed-e-mail-inventors-techdirt-libel-suit/|title=1st Amendment wins in self-proclaimed e-mail inventor's Techdirt libel suit|last=Kravets|first=David|date=September 7, 2017|work=Ars Technica|access-date=2017-09-09|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nThe two parties filed cross-[[appeal]]s with the [[United States Court of Appeals for the First Circuit|U.S. Court of Appeals for the First Circuit]] but settled out of court in May 2019, with no money changing hands. ''Techdirt'' 's articles remain online with an added link to a rebuttal on Ayyadurai's website.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Farivar |first1=Cyrus |title=Defamation lawsuit brought by self-proclaimed email 'inventor' settles |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/defamation-lawsuit-brought-self-proclaimed-email-inventor-settles-n1007196 |accessdate=June 5, 2019 |work=NBC News |date=May 17, 2019 |url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529140115/https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/defamation-lawsuit-brought-self-proclaimed-email-inventor-settles-n1007196 |archivedate=May 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/joint-press-statement-on-behalf-of-dr-shiva-ayyadurai-and-techdirt-michael-masnick-and-leigh-beadon-300849406.html|title=Joint Press Statement On Behalf Of Dr. Shiva Ayyadurai And Techdirt, Michael Masnick, And Leigh Beadon|last=Harder LLP|date=May 14, 2019|website=PR Newswire|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Other actions ===\nIn January 2017, Harder threatened the [[Diaspora (social network)|Diaspora Foundation]] with legal action unless it removed three posts by Roy Schestowitz that Harder alleged were \"defamatory\" towards Ayyadurai.<ref name=diaspora/> (The Diaspora Foundation is part of the Free Software Support Network, which is in turn run by [[Eben Moglen]] and the [[Software Freedom Law Center]].)<ref name=diaspora>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2017/01/lawyer-for-inventor-of-e-mail-sends-threat-letter-over-social-media-posts/|title=Lawyer for 'inventor of e-mail' sends threat letter over social media posts|last=Mullin|first=Joe|date=January 16, 2017|newspaper=Ars Technica|access-date=2017-02-20|work=|last2=Farivar|first2=Cyrus|language=en-us|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nBeginning in 2014, Ayyadurai was romantically connected with the actress [[Fran Drescher]]. On September 7, 2014, Ayyadurai and Drescher participated in a ceremony at Drescher's beach house. Both tweeted that they had gotten married,<ref>{{cite tweet |first=Fran |last=Drescher |date=2014-09-07|title=Surprise!!!!! We got married!|user=frandrescher|number=508781239877128194}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |author=VA Shiva Ayyadurai |date=September 7, 2014 |title=I married my warrior princess @frandrescher who my mom in Gods great Heaven sent. Be The Light - Know the Truth - Find Your Way |user=va_shiva |number=508833431661182976 |url=https://twitter.com/va_shiva/status/508833431661182976 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140909023638/https://twitter.com/va_shiva/status/508833431661182976 |archivedate=September 9, 2014 }}</ref> and the event was widely reported as such.<ref name=\"LATimesMarriage\">{{cite news|last1=Saad|first1=Nardine|title=Fran Drescher of 'The Nanny' marries Shiva Ayyadurai|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-fran-drescher-married-wedding-shiva-ayyadurai-20140908-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times |date=September 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.people.com/article/fran-drescher-marries-shiva-ayyadura|title = Fran Drescher Marries Shiva Ayyadurai|last = Gabrielle|first = Olya|date = September 9, 2014|work = People|access-date =  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Fran Drescher Marries Boyfriend Shiva Ayyadurai, aka the Inventor of Email?!|url = http://www.eonline.com/news/576704/fran-drescher-marries-boyfriend-shiva-ayyadurai-aka-the-inventor-of-email|accessdate = 2015-07-08|date = September 7, 2014|website = E!|last = Vulpo|first = Mike}}</ref> Ayyadurai later said it was not \"a formal wedding or marriage\", but a celebration of their \"friendship in a spiritual ceremony with close friends and her family\".<ref>{{cite web|title = Interview with Dr. V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai, The Inventor of Email and Systems Scientist|url = http://tamilnadu.com/entertainment/personalities/interview-with-dr-v-a-shiva-ayyadurai-the-inventor-of-email-and-systems-scientist.html|website = Tamil Nadu|accessdate = |date = November 25, 2014|last = Kumar|first = Vipin}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = About Dr. V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai - V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai, Inventor of Email|url = http://vashiva.com/about-va-shiva-ayyadurai/|accessdate = July 9, 2015|website = VA Shiva|publisher = V.A. Shiva Ayyadurai}}</ref> The couple split up in September 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://komonews.com/news/entertainment/actress-fran-drescher-splits-from-husband|title=Actress Fran Drescher splits from husband|last=|first=|date=September 4, 2016|work=[[KOMO-TV|Komonews.com]]|agency=World Entertainment News Network|access-date=|via=}}</ref>\n==Books==\n* {{cite book |title=The Internet Publicity Guide: How To Maximize Your Marketing And Promotion In Cyberspace |author=V. A. Shiva |isbn=978-1880559604 |year=1997 |publisher=Allworth Press |location=New York |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/internetpublicit0000shiv }}\n* {{cite book |title=All-American Indian: This Fight Is Your Fight - The Battle to Save America from the Elites Who Think They Know Better\n|author=V. A. Shiva Ayyadurai |isbn=978-0998504926 | year=2017 | publisher=General Interactive, LLC}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://vashiva.com/}}\n*[http://inventorofemail.com/Shiva-Ayyadurai.asp Ayyadurai's response to ''Techdirt'']\n*[https://www.techdirt.com/articles/20190518/23370542236/laying-out-all-evidence-shiva-ayyadurai-did-not-invent-email.shtml ''Techdirt'' 's response to Ayyadurai]\n\n{{Scholia}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ayyadurai, Shiva}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:American male scientists of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Livingston High School (New Jersey) alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Institute of Technology alumni]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Livingston, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Siddha medicine]]\n[[Category:American people of Tamil descent]]\n[[Category:People from Virudhunagar district]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2018 United States elections]]\n", "name_user": "TylerDurden8823", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCOVID-19 misinformation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shiva_Ayyadurai"}
{"title_page": "Cardiac contractility modulation", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical intervention\n| name         = Cardiac Contractility Modulation\n| synonym      =\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| alt          = \n| pronounce    = \n| specialty    = Heart Failure, Electrophysiology, Cardiology\n| synonyms     = \n| ICD10        = \n| ICD9         = \n| ICD9unlinked = \n| CPT          = \n| MeshID       = \n| LOINC        = \n| other_codes  = \n| MedlinePlus  = \n| eMedicine    = \n}}\n\n'''Cardiac Contractility Modulation''' is a [[therapy]] which is intended for the treatment of patients with moderate to severe [[heart failure]] ([[New York Heart Association Functional Classification|NYHA class II\u2013IV]]) with symptoms despite optimal medical therapy who can benefit from an improvement in cardiac output. The short- and long-term use of this therapy enhances the strength of ventricular [[Muscle contraction|contraction]] and therefore the heart's pumping capacity by modulating (adjusting) the [[myocardial contractility]]. This is provided by a [[Artificial cardiac pacemaker|pacemaker]]-like device that applies [[Action potential#Refractory period|non-excitatory electrical signals]] adjusted to and synchronized with the electrical action in the [[Heart#Cardiac cycle|cardiac cycle]].<ref name=\"Abraham 20132\">{{cite journal|last=Abraham|first=W.T.|author2=S.A. Smith|date=Feb 2013|title=Devices in the management of advanced, chronic heart failure|journal=Nat Rev Cardiol|volume=10|issue=2|pages=98\u2013110|doi=10.1038/nrcardio.2012.178|pmc=3753073|pmid=23229137}}</ref><ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\">{{cite journal|last=Giallauria|first=F.|display-authors=etal|date=Aug 2014|title=Effects of cardiac contractility modulation by non-excitatory electrical stimulation on exercise capacity and quality of life: an individual patient's data meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials|journal=Int J Cardiol|volume=175|issue=2|pages=352\u2013357|doi=10.1016/j.ijcard.2014.06.005|pmid=24975782}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 10, 2014--></ref><ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\">{{cite journal|last=Borggrefe|first=M.|author2=D. Burkhoff|date=Jul 2012|title=Clinical effects of cardiac contractility modulation (CCM) as a treatment for chronic heart failure|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/d6c70f07e57473d9ad72ea30318a41f74ac2bd57|journal=Eur J Heart Fail|volume=14|issue=7|pages=703\u2013712|doi=10.1093/eurjhf/hfs078|pmid=22696514}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 11, 2014--></ref>\n\nIn Cardiac Contractility Modulation therapy, electrical stimulation is applied to the cardiac muscle during the absolute [[Action potential#Refractory period|refractory period]]. In this phase of the cardiac cycle, electrical signals cannot trigger new [[cardiac muscle]] contractions, hence this type of stimulation is known as a non-excitatory stimulation. However, the electrical signals increase the influx of [[calcium]] [[ion]]s into the cardiac muscle cells ([[cardiomyocytes]]).<ref name=\"Butter 20082\">{{cite journal|last=Butter|first=C.|display-authors=etal|date=May 2008|title=Cardiac Contractility Modulation Electrical Signals Improve Myocardial Gene Expression in Patients With Heart Failure|journal=J Am Coll Cardiol|volume=51|issue=18|pages=1784\u20131789|doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2008.01.036|pmid=18452785}}</ref><ref name=\"Yu 20092\">{{cite journal|last=Yu|first=C.M.|display-authors=etal|date=Dec 2009|title=Impact of cardiac contractility modulation on left ventricular global and regional function and remodeling|journal=JACC Cardiovasc Imaging|volume=2|issue=12|pages=1341\u20131349|doi=10.1016/j.jcmg.2009.07.011|pmid=20083066}}</ref>&nbsp;In contrast to other electrical stimulation treatments for heart failure, such as [[pacemaker]] therapy or [[implantable cardioverter defibrillator]]s (ICD), Cardiac Contractility Modulation does not directly affect cardiac rhythm. Rather, the aim is to enhance the heart's natural contraction (the native cardiac contractility) sustainably over long periods of time. Furthermore, unlike most interventions that increase cardiac contractility, Cardiac Contractility Modulation is not associated with an unfavorable increase in oxygen demand by the heart (measured in terms of Myocardial Oxygen Consumption or MVO<sub>2</sub>). This may be explained by the beneficial effect the therapy has in improving cardiac efficiency.<ref name=\"Marcus 19832\">{{cite book|title=The Coronary Circulation in Health and Disease|last=Marcus|first=Melvin L.|date=1983|publisher=McGraw Hill|isbn=978-0070402935|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/coronarycirculat0000marc}}</ref><ref name=\"Butter 20073\">{{cite journal|last=Butter|first=C.|display-authors=etal|date=Mar 2007|title=Enhanced inotropic state of the failing left ventricle by cardiac contractility modulation electrical signals is not associated with increased myocardial oxygen consumption|journal=J Card Fail|volume=13|issue=2|pages=137\u2013142|doi=10.1016/j.cardfail.2006.11.004|pmid=17395055}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 11, 2014--></ref><ref name=\"Goliasch 20123\">{{cite journal|last=Goliasch|first=G.|display-authors=etal|date=Mar 2012|title=The effect of device-based cardiac contractility modulation therapy on myocardial efficiency and oxidative metabolism in patients with heart failure|journal=Eur J Nucl Med Mol Imaging|volume=39|issue=3|pages=408\u2013415|doi=10.1007/s00259-011-1977-8|pmid=22083298}}</ref>&nbsp;A meta-analysis in 2014<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" />&nbsp;and an overview of device-based treatment options in heart failure in 2013<ref name=\"Abraham 20134\">{{cite journal|last=Abraham|first=W.T.|author2=S.A. Smith|date=Feb 2013|title=Devices in the management of advanced, chronic heart failure|journal=Nat Rev Cardiol|volume=10|issue=2|pages=98\u2013110|doi=10.1038/nrcardio.2012.178|pmc=3753073|pmid=23229137}}</ref> concluded that Cardiac contractility modulation treatment is safe,<ref name=\"Abraham 20132\" /><ref name=\"Abraham 20134\" /> that it is generally beneficial to patients<ref name=\"Abraham 20132\" /><ref name=\"Abraham 20134\" /> and that the treatment increases the [[Cardiac stress test|exercise tolerance]] (ET) and [[quality of life]] (QoL) of patients.<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /> Furthermore, preliminary long-term [[Survival analysis|survival data]] shows that Cardiac contractility modulation is associated with lower long-term [[Cause of death|mortality]] in heart failure patients when compared with expected rates among similar patients not treated with Cardiac contractility modulation.<ref name=\"Kuschyk 20152\">{{cite journal|last=Kuschyk|first=J.|display-authors=etal|date=Jan 2015|title=Efficacy and survival in patients with cardiac contractility modulation: Long-term single center experience in 81 patients|journal=Int J Cardiol|volume=183|issue=|pages=76\u201381|doi=10.1016/j.ijcard.2014.12.178|pmid=25662055}}</ref>\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Medical uses ==\n\n===FDA Approval===\nBased on the results of the pivotal FIX-HF-5C trial <ref>{{cite journal|last=Abraham|first=W.|display-authors=etal|date=Oct 2018|title=A Randomized Controlled Trial to Evaluate the Safety and Efficacy of Cardiac Contractility Modulation|journal=JACC Heart Failure|volume=6|issue=10|pages=874-883|doi=10.1016/j.jchf.2018.04.010}}</ref>\nThe FDA approved Cardiac Contractility Modulation therapy for use in the United States on March 21, 2019.\n\n=== FDA Indication ===\nThe FDA approved the OPTIMIZER Smart System, which delivers Cardiac Contractility Modulation therapy, as indicated to improve 6-minute hall walk distance, quality of life, and functional status of NYHA Class III heart failure patients who remain symptomatic despite guideline directed medical therapy, who are in normal sinus rhythm, are not indicated for Cardiac Resynchronization Therapy, and have a left ventricular ejection fraction ranging from 25% to 45%.\n\n=== CE Mark ===\nBased on the results of clinical trials,<ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\" /><ref name=\"Kuschyk 2014a2\">{{cite journal|last=Kuschyk|first=J.|date=2014|title=Der Besondere Stellenwert der Kardialen Kontraktilit\u00e4tsmodulation in der Devicetherapie|url=http://cme.medlearning.de/herzmedizin/kardialen_kontraktilitaetsmodulation/cme.htm|journal=Herzmedizin|accessdate=Jun 6, 2014}}</ref>  Cardiac contractility modulation devices are approved and available for clinical use in all [[European Union]] countries and in [[Australia]], [[Turkey]], [[India]] and [[Hong Kong]], as well as in other countries that recognize [[CE marking]] for [[medical device]]s.\n\n=== CE Indication ===\n[[Image:SinusRhythmLabels.svg|thumb|Schematic representation of normal [[sinus rhythm]] as seen on an ECG. The QRS complex is shown in the center.]]Based on the approval of Cardiac Contractility Modulation devices, the therapy is a treatment option for patients that are at least 18 years old who suffer from [[Heart failure#Left-sided failure|heart failure symptoms]] due to left ventricular systolic dysfunction (LVSD) despite adequate medical treatment. Further clinical research are under way to identify which patient group within the scope of the device approval benefits most from Cardiac Contractility Modulation treatment.<ref name=\"Abraham 20132\" /><ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /><ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\" /><ref name=\"clinicaltrials2\">[http://clinicaltrials.gov/show/NCT01381172 clinicaltrials.gov Announcement of a study that will further investigate safety and efficacy of CCM devices]</ref>\n\nCriteria for the classification of patients with left ventricular systolic heart failure include the severity of the disease based on functional parameters (NYHA classification), the average percentage of blood volume ejected by the left ventricle with each heart beat (left ventricular [[ejection fraction]] or LVEF) and the duration of the QRS complex seen in the electrocardiogram (ECG). Most clinical studies on Cardiac Contractility Modulation therapy have involved heart failure patients who were classified initially as NYHA Class II, III or IV and had a normal QRS duration (QRS duration \u2264 120 ms). The efficacy of Cardiac Contractility Modulation on patients in an earlier stage of heart failure has not yet been studied.<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /><ref name=\"Kuck 20133\">{{cite journal|last=Kuck|first=K.-H.|display-authors=etal|date=Jan 2014|title=New devices in heart failure: an European Heart Rhythm Association report: developed by the European Heart Rhythm Association; endorsed by the Heart Failure Association|url=http://europace.oxfordjournals.org/content/europace/16/1/109.full.pdf|journal=Europace|volume=16|issue=1|pages=109\u2013128|doi=10.1093/europace/eut311|pmid=24265466|accessdate=Oct 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA subsequent evaluation study (subgroup analysis) has already suggested a particular patient group that responds exceptionally well to Cardiac Contractility Modulation therapy. The patients were characterized by a disease severity of NYHA class III and a left ventricular ejection fraction of \u2265 25%.<ref name=\"Abraham 20132\" /><ref name=\"Abraham 20112\">{{cite journal|last=Abraham|first=W.T.|display-authors=etal|date=Sep 2011|title=Subgroup Analysis of a Randomized Controlled Trial Evaluating the Safety and Efficacy of Cardiac Contractility Modulation in Advanced Heart Failure|journal=J Card Fail|volume=17|issue=9|pages=710\u2013717|doi=10.1016/j.cardfail.2011.05.006|pmid=21872139}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 13, 2014--></ref>\n\nAlthough studies on Cardiac Contractility Modulation therapy have focused on patients with a normal QRS duration (i.e. \u2264 120 ms), it is possible to use the therapy in patients who meet the treatment indication but who do not have a normal QRS duration.<ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\" /><ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\">{{cite journal|last=Burkhoff|first=D.|date=Dec 2011|title=Does Contractility Modulation Have a Role in the Treatment of Heart Failure?|journal=Curr Heart Fail Rep|volume=8|issue=4|pages=260\u2013265|doi=10.1007/s11897-011-0067-3|pmid=21656201}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 11, 2014--></ref><ref name=\"Butter 20112\">{{cite journal|last=Butter|first=C.|date=Mar 2011|title=Verbesserung der linksventrikul\u00e4ren Kontraktilit\u00e4t durch Stimulation in der absoluten Refrakt\u00e4rperiode. Kardiale Kontraktilit\u00e4tsmodulation.|journal=Herzschr Elektrophys|volume=22|issue=1|pages=27\u201333|doi=10.1007/s00399-011-0120-7|pmid=21365468}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 15, 2014--></ref>\n\nA preliminary study has previously shown that Cardiac Contractility Modulation may be safe and effective in such patients who have not responded to [[cardiac resynchronization therapy]] (CRT).<ref name=\"Nagele 20082\">{{cite journal|last=Nagele|first=H.|author2=S. Behrens|author3=C. Eisermann|date=Dec 2008|title=Cardiac Contractility Modulation in Non-responders to Cardiac Resynchronization Therapy|url=http://europace.oxfordjournals.org/content/europace/10/12/1375.full.pdf|journal=Europace|volume=10|issue=12|pages=1375\u20131380|doi=10.1093/europace/eun257|pmid=18776196|accessdate=Oct 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Therapeutic gap ===\nCardiac resynchronization therapy (CRT; also known as biventricular pacing) has proven to be an effective treatment in heart failure.<ref name=\"ESC Guideline2\">{{cite journal|last=McMurray|first=J.J.V.|display-authors=etal|date=2012|title=ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of acute and chronic heart failure 2012|url=http://eurheartj.oxfordjournals.org/content/ehj/33/14/1787.full.pdf|journal=European Heart Journal|volume=33|issue=14|pages=1787\u20131847|doi=10.1093/eurheartj/ehs104|pmid=22611136|accessdate=Oct 10, 2014}}</ref> However, CRT is generally recommended exclusively for patients with a preserved sinus rhythm and a prolonged QRS complex (\u2265 120 ms) who also suffer from [[left bundle branch block]] (LBBB), or for patients without left bundle branch block but who have a preserved sinus rhythm and a QRS complex with a width of \u2265 150 ms.<ref name=\"ESC Guideline2\" /> However, only 30-40% of all heart failure patients show such a prolonged QRS complex, and therefore the 60-70% of patients who have a normal QRS complex cannot be treated with CRT. In addition, around 30% of the patients eligible for CRT treatment do not respond to CRT.<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /><ref name=\"Kuck 20133\" /><ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" />\n\nUntil recently, the only other available device-based treatment was the [[left ventricular assist device]] (LVAD). LVAD therapy is indicated in patients with severe illness and is associated with several hours of surgery (involving a [[cardiopulmonary bypass]]). It is usually considered as a therapy providing a \u201cbridge to transplant\u201d for heart failure patients classified as NYHA class IV, and is intended to support heart function until a [[Heart transplantation|heart transplant]] is received.<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /><ref name=\"Kuck 20133\" /><ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" /> Current research results suggest that the therapeutic gap described above could now be closed by the Cardiac contractility modulation therapy.<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /><ref name=\"Kuck 20133\" /><ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" /> Additionally, a long-term study showed that the Cardiac Contractility Modulation was able to stop the common and prognostically unfavorable long-term prolongation of QRS duration in heart failure patients. This result was interpreted as signaling the safety of the treatment and as an indicator that patients could benefit from Cardiac contractility modulation therapy in the long term. If the QRS-stabilizing effect were to be confirmed in further studies, the Cardiac Contractility Modulation would become the first device-based treatment for heart failure with the potential to halt QRS prolongation, a factor associated with a poor prognosis.<ref name=\"R\u00f6ger 2014b2\">{{cite journal|last=R\u00f6ger|first=S.|display-authors=etal|date=Aug 2014|title=Long term impact of Cardiac Contractility Modulation on QRS Duration|journal=J Electrocardiol|volume=47|issue=6|pages=936\u201340|doi=10.1016/j.jelectrocard.2014.08.011|pmid=25201417}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 11, 2014--></ref>\n\n=== Recommendations ===\nThe [[Medical guideline|guidelines]] issued by the [[European Society of Cardiology]] (ESC) in 2016, mention Cardiac Contractility Modulation therapy as a therapy option to be considered in selected group of patients with HF. Mostly these guidelines are endorsed by national cardiac societies in individual countries within the European Union.<ref name=\"ESC Guideline2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.escardio.org/Guidelines-&-Education/Clinical-Practice-Guidelines/Acute-and-Chronic-Heart-Failure|title=Acute and Chronic Heart Failure|website=www.escardio.org|access-date=2017-11-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Efficacy ===\nCardiac Contractility Modulation has proven to be effective and safe in randomized controlled trials involving several hundred patients.<ref name=\"Neelagaru 20062\">{{cite journal|last=Neelagaru|first=S.B.|display-authors=etal|date=Oct 2006|title=Nonexcitatory, cardiac contractility modulation electrical impulses: Feasibility study for advanced heart failure in patients with normal QRS duration|journal=Heart Rhythm|volume=3|issue=10|pages=1140\u20131147|doi=10.1016/j.hrthm.2006.06.031|pmid=17018340}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 16, 2014--></ref><ref name=\"Borggrefe 20082\">{{cite journal|last=Borggrefe|first=M.|display-authors=etal|date=Apr 2008|title=Randomized, double blind study of non-excitatory, cardiac contractility modulation electrical impulses for symptomatic heart failure|url=http://eurheartj.oxfordjournals.org/content/ehj/29/8/1019.full.pdf|journal=Eur Heart J|volume=29|issue=8|pages=1019\u20131028|doi=10.1093/eurheartj/ehn020|pmid=18270213|accessdate=Oct 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Kadish 20112\">{{cite journal|last=Kadish|first=A.|display-authors=etal|date=Feb 2011|title=A randomized controlled trial evaluating the safety and efficacy of cardiac contractility modulation in advanced heart failure|journal=Am Heart J|volume=161|issue=2|pages=329\u2013337|doi=10.1016/j.ahj.2010.10.025|pmid=21315216|url=https://touroscholar.touro.edu/president_pubs/44}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 16, 2014--></ref>\n\nThe nature and extent of the effect of Cardiac Contractility Modulation have been the subject of numerous investigations. Although various individual publications, as well as one of two meta-analyses, have presented the efficacy and significant potential of Cardiac Contractility Modulation in the treatment of heart failure, medical evaluation of the therapy efficacy is not yet complete. Scientists point out, however, that this was also the case for CRT therapy when it was first introduced, advocating the provision of Cardiac contractility modulation to suitable patients before further studies are completed.<ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\" /><ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" />\n\nTo date (February 2015), there are at least two meta-analyses studying the efficacy of Cardiac contractility modulation therapy on heart failure,<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /><ref name=\"Kwong 20122\">{{cite journal|last=Kwong|first=J.S.|author2=J.E. Sanderson|author3=C.M. Yu|date=Sep 2012|title=Cardiac contractility modulation for heart failure: a meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials|journal=Pacing Clin Electrophysiol|volume=35|issue=5|pages=1111\u20131118|doi=10.1111/j.1540-8159.2012.03449.x|pmid=22734676}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 16, 2014--></ref> a large number of review articles (e.g.<ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\" /><ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" /><ref name=\"Butter 20112\" /><ref name=\"Kuschyk 2014b2\">{{cite journal|last=Kuschyk|first=J.|author2=S. R\u00f6ger|author3=M. Borggrefe|date=Oct 2014|title=Kardiale Kontraktilit\u00e4tsmodulation zur Behandlung der symptomatischen Herzinsuffizienz|journal=Der Kardiologe|volume=8|issue=5|pages=407\u2013414|doi=10.1007/s12181-014-0595-7|id=}}</ref><ref name=\"Kuschyk 20132\">{{cite journal|last=Kuschyk|first=J.|author2=M. Borggrefe|date=2013|title=Elektrische Therapie der Herzinsuffizienz|journal=Kardio up|volume=9|issue=1|pages=37\u201356|doi=10.1055/s-0032-1326192|id=}}</ref>) and at least two survey articles on device-based treatments of advanced heart failure<ref name=\"Abraham 20132\" /><ref name=\"Kuck 20133\" /> which address cardiac contractility modulation. Furthermore, there are more than 70 individual publications focusing specifically on Cardiac contractility modulation therapy.<ref name=\"PubMed Suche2\">Research of the [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed Pubmed data base] for the search term \"Cardiac Contractility Modulation\" in the title of publications performed on Oct 16, 2014</ref>\n\nFurther randomized controlled trials studying the effect of Cardiac Contractility Modulation on the progression of heart failure have been initiated and are currently (as of Feb 2015) recruiting patients.<ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\" /><ref name=\"clinicaltrials2\" /><ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" />\n\n==== Meta-analyses ====\nGiallauria et al. evaluated the three [[randomized controlled trial]]s (RCTs) currently available on Cardiac contractility modulation as a treatment for heart failure patients.<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /><ref name=\"Neelagaru 20062\" /><ref name=\"Borggrefe 20082\" /> The three trials included a total of 641 patients and assessed the effect of Cardiac contractility modulation either in comparison to a sham treatment<ref name=\"Neelagaru 20062\" /><ref name=\"Borggrefe 20082\" /> or in comparison to the best medical treatment.<ref name=\"Kadish 20112\" /> In contrast to an earlier meta-analysis by Kwong et al.<ref name=\"Kwong 20122\" /> the study did not evaluate the data based on summarized results alone, but on the basis of the individual data sets of the 641 enrolled patients.\n\nThe study concluded that Cardiac contractility modulation significantly improved important markers of cardiac performance. These included the [[maximal oxygen uptake]] (peak VO2 or pVO2 \u2013 measured by ventilatory parameters during a cardiopulmonary exercise test), which is indicative of improved survival,<ref name=\"Pakarinen 20102\">{{cite journal|last=Pakarinen|first=S.|author2=L. Oikarinen|author3=L. Toivonen|date=Jan 2010|title=Short-term implantation-related complications of cardiac rhythm management device therapy: a retrospective single-centre 1-year survey|url=http://europace.oxfordjournals.org/content/europace/12/1/103.full.pdf|journal=Europace|volume=12|issue=1|pages=103\u2013108|doi=10.1093/europace/eup361|pmid=19914920|accessdate=Nov 6, 2014}}</ref> and the [[Cardiovascular & pulmonary physiotherapy#6 Minute Walk Test .286MWT.29|6-minute walk test]]. The quality of life of participating patients, measured by the Minnesota Living with Heart Failure Questionnaire (MLWHFQ), also improved significantly. However, both meta-analyses demanded additional and larger randomized controlled trials in order to evaluate the effect of the therapy more precisely.\n\nGiallauria et al. describe the success of cardiac contractility modulation and the further potential of the therapy. Particular emphasis is given to the possibility that Cardiac contractility modulation therapy may close the [[Cardiac contractility modulation#Therapeutic Gap in Heart Failure Treatment|therapeutic gap]] in heart failure treatment if previous study outcomes are confirmed.\n\n==== Long-Term Survival Studies ====\nAs of February 2015, the effect of Cardiac contractility modulation therapy on the long-term mortality rates of heart failure patients has not been studied in a randomized controlled trial. Some preliminary single-center studies have been reported though.<ref name=\"Kuschyk 20152\" /> Kuschyk et al. evaluated the long-term efficacy and survival of patients with Cardiac contractility modulation.<ref name=\"Kuschyk 20152\" /> Their analysis included 81 patients with a disease severity of NYHA class II, III or IV and a mean follow-up of around 3 years. The analysis compared the observed mortality rate with the prediction of the Meta-analysis Global Group in Chronic Heart Failure (MAGGIC) model<ref name=\"MAGGIC data2\">{{cite journal|last=Pocock|first=S.J.|display-authors=etal|date=May 2013|title=Predicting survival in heart failure: a risk score based on 39 372 patients from 30 studies|url=http://eurheartj.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2012/10/23/eurheartj.ehs337|journal=Eur Heart J|volume=34|issue=19|pages=1404\u20131413|doi=10.1093/eurheartj/ehs337|pmid=23095984|accessdate=Feb 20, 2015|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"MAGGIC2\">[http://www.heartfailurerisk.org/ \"MAGGIC\" Heart Failure Risc Calculator according to Pocock et al. ''Predicting survival in heart failure: a risk score based on 39 372 patients from 30 studies'', Eur Heart J (2013) 34(19) 1404-1413 (linked above)]</ref> which is based on the records of over 39,000 heart failure patients. Unlike a previous long-term outcome study of Cardiac contractility modulation,<ref name=\"Schau 20112\">{{cite journal|last=Schau|first=T.|display-authors=etal|date=Apr 2011|title=Long-term outcome of cardiac contractility modulation in patients with severe congestive heart failure|url=http://europace.oxfordjournals.org/content/13/10/1436.full-text.pdf|journal=Europace|volume=13|issue=10|pages=1436\u20131444|doi=10.1093/europace/eur153|pmid=21712286|accessdate=Feb 20, 2015}}</ref> this study was not limited by a widely heterogeneous group of patients.\n\nFollowing long-term observation, the study concluded that Cardiac contractility modulation improved quality of life, exercise tolerance, NYHA class, left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF) and [[brain natriuretic peptide]] (BNP) levels. Mortality rates were significantly lower than predicted at year 1, and lower than predicted but not statistically significant at year 3.\n\n==== General ====\n\nHeart failure is a chronic disease that usually progresses gradually.<ref name=\"ESC Guideline2\" /> The rate of progression and the degree of symptoms of the disease varies between different patients. Cardiac contractility modulation therapy aims to treat heart failure through a medium- to long-term treatment, over the course of weeks and months.\n\nAccording to large implanting clinics, after the implantation wound is healed, the lifestyle of a patient is not restricted by the implanted device.<ref name=\"Pacemaker life2\">[http://www.heart.org/HEARTORG/Conditions/Arrhythmia/PreventionTreatmentofArrhythmia/Living-With-Your-Pacemaker_UCM_305290_Article.jsp Tips by the American Heart Associuation \"Living With Your Pacemaker\"]</ref> Leisure, travel (by car, train, ship or plane), hobbies and sex life will not be restricted. The patient may perceive an improved capacity for these activities and overall enhanced performance and exercise capacity in response to the actual therapy.\n\n==Contraindications ==\nIn the past, the most important contraindication in Cardiac contractility modulation treatment was permanent and long-standing persistent [[atrial fibrillation]]. The signal application in current Cardiac contractility modulation devices was timed and triggered according to the electrical activity of the [[Atrium (heart)|atrium]]. In atrial fibrillation, electrical activity in the atrium is severely disturbed and is therefore not a reliable basis for the triggering of Cardiac contractility modulation signals. This also applies to other diseases involving severe disturbance in electrical atrial sensing.<ref name=\"R\u00f6ger 2014a2\">{{cite journal|last=R\u00f6ger|first=S.|display-authors=etal|date=Apr 2014|title=Cardiac contractility modulation: first experience in heart failure patients with reduced ejection fraction and permanent atrial fibrillation|journal=Europace|volume=16|issue=8|pages=1205\u20139|doi=10.1093/europace/euu050|pmid=24706089}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 14, 2014--></ref> Requests have been raised in scientific literature for an improved Cardiac contractility modulation algorithm which would allow the therapy to be delivered independently from any atrial signal. A pioneering study had shown that an improved Cardiac contractility modulation algorithm could make the therapy an effective treatment for patients with persistent atrial fibrillation.<ref name=\"R\u00f6ger 2014a2\" /> Following these study results the new generation was developed and can now offer Cardiac contractility modulation therapy also for patients with [[atrial fibrillation]].\n\nOther irregular rhythms, including frequent [[premature ventricular contraction]]s (ventricular extra systoles) or a distinct signal transduction disorder in the heart (untreated [[AV block]] of more than 300 ms), may represent contraindications. CRT treatment should be considered in lieu of Cardiac contractility modulation in patients with left bundle branch block (LBBB) and a QRS duration of over 120 ms, or when the QRS duration is greater than 150 ms and independent of LBBB.<ref name=\"Abraham 20134\" /><ref name=\"ESC Guideline2\" />\n\nAs with conventional pacemaker therapy, the Cardiac contractility modulation device cannot be implanted if the leads cannot be positioned appropriately in the heart. In cases where there is an [[artificial heart valve]] between the right atrium and ventricle (a mechanical prosthetic tricuspid valve), the valve function could be greatly affected by the ventricular leads. In some instances it may be impossible to guide the leads through the main veins in the upper half of the body to the heart due to [[venous thrombosis]], for example [[Artificial cardiac pacemaker#mode|VVI pacemakers]], in the case of 100% stimulation, are also contraindicated.<ref name=\"Abraham 20134\" />\n\n== Side effects ==\nThe most frequently encountered adverse events related to Cardiac contractility modulation therapy are lead fracture or lead dislodgement.<ref name=\"Kadish 20112\" /> Other reported complications include:\n* Infection and bleeding at the IPG implantation site\n* Accumulation of fluid in the pericardium ([[pericardial effusion]])<ref name=\"Borggrefe 20082\" />\n\nThese side effects are similar to those that occur with other electrical stimulation therapies, such as pacemakers, CRT devices or ICD devices.<ref name=\"Pakarinen 20102\" /> Furthermore, recorded complications did not differ between patients with activated or deactivated Cardiac contractility modulation devices.<ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" />\n\nOverall, Cardiac contractility modulation treatment was demonstrated to have no negative impact on health markers.<ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" />\n\n=== Precautions ===\n\n[[File:Flughafenkontrolle.jpg|thumb|Metal detectors used for security screening]]\nSimilarly to patients with other electrical stimulation devices, patients with a Cardiac contractility modulation device must follow certain precautions arising from the device implantation and its function.\n* Electromagnetic fields: Strong electromagnetic fields can interfere with the function of the device. Most interference will lead to inhibition of Cardiac contractility modulation signal delivery. Once away from the field, the device will resume its normal function in most cases. The electromagnetic fields of household appliances are usually considered harmless.<ref name=\"Pacemaker EM-fields2\">[http://www.heart.org/HEARTORG/Conditions/Arrhythmia/PreventionTreatmentofArrhythmia/Implantable-Cardioverter-Defibrillator-ICD_UCM_448478_Article.jsp Safety recommendations of the American Heart Association for patients with artificial pacemakers]</ref><ref name=\"ICD EM-fields2\">[http://www.heart.org/HEARTORG/Conditions/Arrhythmia/PreventionTreatmentofArrhythmia/Implantable-Cardioverter-Defibrillator-ICD_UCM_448478_Article.jsp Safety recommendations of the American Heart Association for patients with implantable cardioverter defibrillators (ICDs)]</ref>\n* Mobile phones: Similarly to other electrical stimulation devices, such as pacemakers, aside from a recommended safety distance of 10\u201315&nbsp;cm (4-6 inches) between the device and mobile phones, there are no restrictions on the use of mobile phones.<ref name=\"Pacemaker EM-fields2\" />\n* Security checks: Full body or hand-held metal detectors, such as those used at airport security controls, do not usually affect the function of the device. However, where such detectors are used there are often signs warning people with cardiac pacemakers and defibrillators, and Cardiac contractility modulation patients are therefore advised to present their device ID. In these cases, the security check will typically continue with the use of a hand-held metal detector or by physical inspection.<ref name=\"Pacemaker EM-fields2\" />\n* Sports: All sports associated with increased stress on the arms or the chest, such as body building, martial arts or tennis, are usually not permitted. Diving is only permitted up to a depth of 5 meters due to the high pressure at greater depths.<ref name=\"Pacemaker life2\" />\n* Sports: All sports associated with increased stress on the arms or the chest, such as body building, martial arts or tennis, are usually not permitted. Diving is only permitted up to a depth of 5 meters due to the high pressure at greater depth.<ref name=\"Dill 2008-MRI2\">{{cite journal|last=Dill|first=T.|date=Jul 2008|title=Contraindications to magnetic resonance imaging|url=http://www.rad.pitt.edu/public/mrrc-docs/ContraindicationsMRI.pdf|journal=Heart|volume=94|issue=7|pages=943\u2013948|doi=10.1136/hrt.2007.125039|pmid=18552230|accessdate=Feb 22, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402105422/http://www.rad.pitt.edu/public/mrrc-docs/ContraindicationsMRI.pdf|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI): Similarly to other electrical stimulation devices, such as pacemakers, Cardiac contractility modulation therapy is a contraindication for MRI, a medical imaging technique.<ref name=\"Dill 2008-MRI2\" />\n\n== Mechanism of action ==\nThe [[mechanism of action]] of Cardiac contractility modulation has been subject to continuous research since its initial discovery. Based on [[animal testing]] and experiments on human myocardial tissue obtained by [[biopsies]], essential parts of the mechanism of action have been identified.<ref name=\"Butter 20082\" /><ref name=\"Lyon 20132\">{{cite journal|last=Lyon|first=A.R.|author2=M.A. Samara|author3=D.S. Feldman|date=Oct 2013|title=Cardiac contractility modulation therapy in advanced systolic heart failure|journal=Nat. Rev. Cardiol.|volume=10|issue=10|pages=584\u2013598|doi=10.1038/nrcardio.2013.114|pmid=23939481}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 23, 2014--></ref> According to current understanding (as of February 2015), the mechanism of action of Cardiac contractility modulation may be summarized in the following manner: The signals applied during the electrical non-excitatory state of the cardiac muscle cells (the absolute refractory period) cause an increase in myocyte calcium in the cytosol during systole. This increases the muscle contraction strength. Additionally, within minutes, cell [[metabolism]] and [[gene expression]], which are typically abnormal in heart failure, improve towards their normal state.<ref name=\"Lyon 20132\" /> This beneficial effect occurs initially only in the area adjacent to the electrodes, but with time also spreads to remote areas of the cardiac muscle.<ref name=\"Lyon 20132\" /> Cardiac contractility modulation therefore restores the structure and function of damaged cells back towards their normal state. In some cases, disease-related changes in the ventricular heart structure can be partially reversed by Cardiac contractility modulation through a process known as reverse remodeling of the heart.<ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\" /><ref name=\"Butter 20082\" /><ref name=\"Yu 20092\" /><ref name=\"Butter 20112\" /><ref name=\"Imai 20072\">{{cite journal|last=Imai|first=M.|display-authors=etal|date=May 2007|title=Therapy with cardiac contractility modulation electrical signals improves left ventricular function and remodeling in dogs with chronic heart failure|journal=J Am Coll Cardiol|volume=49|issue=21|pages=2120\u20132128|doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2006.10.082|pmid=17531662}}</ref><ref name=\"Gupta 20082\">{{cite journal|last=Gupta|first=R.C.|display-authors=etal|date=Feb 2009|title=Cardiac Contractility Modulation Electrical Signals Normalize Activity, Expression, and Phosphorylation of the Na+-Ca2+ Exchanger in Heart Failure|journal=Journal of Cardiac Failure|volume=15|issue=1|pages=48\u201356|doi=10.1016/j.cardfail.2008.08.011|pmid=19181294}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nDevelopment of cardiac contractility modulation began in the late 1990s.<ref name=\"patent2\">[https://archive.is/20150308200716/http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect2=PTO1&Sect2=HITOFF&p=1&u=/netahtml/PTO/search-bool.html&r=1&f=G&l=50&d=PALL&RefSrch=yes&Query=PN/6360126 Patent for CCM: ''Apparatus and method for controlling the delivery of contractility modulating non-excitatory signals to the heart'']</ref><ref name=\"Mohri2\">{{cite journal|last=Mohri|first=S.|display-authors=etal|date=May 2002|title=Cardiac contractility modulation by electric currents applied during the refractory period|journal=Am J Physiol Heart Circ Physiol|volume=282|issue=5|pages=H1642\u2013H1647|doi=10.1152/ajpheart.00959.2001|pmid=11959626|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/7d14951c1e80e58bbddaf946231f7a709cf5a952}}</ref> Studies on individual cardiac muscle cells using a patch-clamp technique had already shown, in 1969, that a voltage applied during the absolute refractory period through leads between the interior of the cell and its outside environment increased the calcium influx through the cell membrane and improved the contraction of cardiac muscle cells.<ref name=\"Antoni2\">{{cite journal|last=Antoni|first=H.|author2=R. Jacob|author3=R. Kaufmann|date=1969|title=Mechanical response of the frog and mammalian myocardium to changes in the action potential duration by constant current pulses|journal=Pfl\u00fcgers Arch|volume=306|issue=1|pages=33\u201357|pmid=4975967|doi=10.1007/bf00586610}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 9, 2014--></ref><ref name=\"Wood2\">{{cite journal|last=Wood|first=E.H.|author2=R.L. Heppner|author3=S. Weidmann|date=Mar 1969|title=Inotropic effects of electric currents. I. Positive and negative effects of constant electric currents or current pulses applied during cardiac action potentials. II. Hypotheses: calcium movements, excitation-contraction coupling and inotropic effects.|journal=Circ Res|volume=24|issue=3|pages=409\u2013445|doi=10.1161/01.RES.24.3.409|pmid=5766519|doi-access=free}}</ref> In 2001, scientists observed that a similar effect occurs even if the voltage is applied exclusively outside the cardiac muscle cells.[[Cardiac contractility modulation#cite note-Burkhoff 2001-48|<sup>[48]</sup>]] Additionally, it was observed that therapeutically useful effects on the cardiac muscle were achieved if the electrical signals were applied not only to single cells but to large areas using larger leads, as used in conventional cardiac pacemakers. The contractility of both a healthy heart and a damaged heart could be increased through application of appropriate signals during the absolute refractory period of the cardiac muscle cells.<ref name=\"Burkhoff 20012\">{{cite journal|last=Burkhoff|first=D.|display-authors=etal|date=Jan 2001|title=Electric currents applied during the refractory period can modulate cardiac contractility in vitro and in vivo|journal=Heart Fail Rev|volume=6|issue=1|pages=27\u201334|pmid=11248765|doi=10.1023/A:1009851107189}}</ref><ref name=\"Sabbah2\">{{cite journal|last=Sabbah|first=H.N.|display-authors=etal|date=Jan 2001|title=Cardiac contractility modulation with the impulse dynamics signal: studies in dogs with chronic heart failure|journal=Heart Fail Rev|volume=6|issue=1|pages=45\u201353|pmid=11248767|doi=10.1023/A:1009855208097}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 9, 2014--></ref>\n\nAn implantable Cardiac contractility modulation device was received by a patient for the first time in 2001.<ref name=\"Pappone 20012\">{{cite journal|last=Pappone|first=C.|display-authors=etal|date=Jan 2001|title=Electrical modulation of cardiac contractility: clinical aspects in congestive heart failure|journal=Heart Fail Rev|volume=6|issue=1|pages=55\u201360|pmid=11248768|doi=10.1023/A:1009807309006}}<!--| accessdate = Nov 6, 2014--></ref><ref name=\"Pappone 20022\">{{cite journal|last=Pappone|first=C.|display-authors=etal|date=Dec 2002|title=Cardiac contractility modulation by electric currents applied during the refractory period in patients with heart failure secondary to ischemic or idiopathic dilated cardiomyopathy|journal=Am J Cardiol|volume=90|issue=12|pages=1307\u20131313|doi=10.1016/s0002-9149(02)02868-0|pmid=12480039}}<!--| accessdate = Nov 6, 2014--></ref> The first study on the therapeutic effects of in humans was presented in 2004.<ref name=\"Stix 20042\">{{cite journal|last=Stix|first=G.|display-authors=etal|date=Apr 2014|title=Chronic electrical stimulation during the absolute refractory period of the myocardium improves severe heart failure|url=http://eurheartj.oxfordjournals.org/content/ehj/25/8/650.full.pdf|journal=Eur Heart J|volume=25|issue=8|pages=650\u2013655|doi=10.1016/j.ehj.2004.02.027|pmid=15084369|accessdate=Oct 10, 2014}}</ref> To date, more than 3,000 heart failure patients have been treated with Cardiac contractility modulation worldwide,<ref name=\"Kuschyk 2014a2\" /> including 641 patients under the study conditions recommended by the [[Cochrane Collaboration]] as being necessary for inclusion in a meta-analysis.<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /> Cardiac contractility modulation device implant was first successfully done in India in Royal Hospital,Trivandrum,Kerala,under the leadership of the Chief Cardiologist Dr. C. Bharath Chandran. Advocate Harishankar is the first person in India to get the CCM device implanted.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Heart]]\n* [[Cardiac cycle]]\n* [[Heart failure]]\n* [[Artificial cardiac pacemaker]]\n* [[Implantable cardioverter-defibrillator]]\n* [[NYHA classification]]\n* [[Cardiac resynchronization therapy]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n== External links ==\n* [http://europace.oxfordjournals.org/content/europace/16/1/109.full.pdf Current assessment of new device therapies for heart failure by the European Heart Rhythm Association (EHRA) \u2013 includes Cardiac contractility modulation]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cardiac contractility modulation}}\n[[Category:Cardiac procedures]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical intervention\n| name         = Cardiac Contractility Modulation\n| synonym      =\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| alt          = \n| pronounce    = \n| specialty    = Heart Failure, Electrophysiology, Cardiology\n| synonyms     = \n| ICD10        = \n| ICD9         = \n| ICD9unlinked = \n| CPT          = \n| MeshID       = \n| LOINC        = \n| other_codes  = \n| MedlinePlus  = \n| eMedicine    = \n}}\n\n'''Cardiac Contractility Modulation''' is a [[therapy]] which is intended for the treatment of patients with moderate to severe [[heart failure]] ([[New York Heart Association Functional Classification|NYHA class II\u2013IV]]) with symptoms despite optimal medical therapy who can benefit from an improvement in cardiac output. The short- and long-term use of this therapy enhances the strength of ventricular [[Muscle contraction|contraction]] and therefore the heart's pumping capacity by modulating (adjusting) the [[myocardial contractility]]. This is provided by a [[Artificial cardiac pacemaker|pacemaker]]-like device that applies [[Action potential#Refractory period|non-excitatory electrical signals]] adjusted to and synchronized with the electrical action in the [[Heart#Cardiac cycle|cardiac cycle]].<ref name=\"Abraham 20132\">{{cite journal|last=Abraham|first=W.T.|author2=S.A. Smith|date=Feb 2013|title=Devices in the management of advanced, chronic heart failure|journal=Nat Rev Cardiol|volume=10|issue=2|pages=98\u2013110|doi=10.1038/nrcardio.2012.178|pmc=3753073|pmid=23229137}}</ref><ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\">{{cite journal|last=Giallauria|first=F.|display-authors=etal|date=Aug 2014|title=Effects of cardiac contractility modulation by non-excitatory electrical stimulation on exercise capacity and quality of life: an individual patient's data meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials|journal=Int J Cardiol|volume=175|issue=2|pages=352\u2013357|doi=10.1016/j.ijcard.2014.06.005|pmid=24975782}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 10, 2014--></ref><ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\">{{cite journal|last=Borggrefe|first=M.|author2=D. Burkhoff|date=Jul 2012|title=Clinical effects of cardiac contractility modulation (CCM) as a treatment for chronic heart failure|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/d6c70f07e57473d9ad72ea30318a41f74ac2bd57|journal=Eur J Heart Fail|volume=14|issue=7|pages=703\u2013712|doi=10.1093/eurjhf/hfs078|pmid=22696514}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 11, 2014--></ref>\n\nIn Cardiac Contractility Modulation therapy, electrical stimulation is applied to the cardiac muscle during the absolute [[Action potential#Refractory period|refractory period]]. In this phase of the cardiac cycle, electrical signals cannot trigger new [[cardiac muscle]] contractions, hence this type of stimulation is known as a non-excitatory stimulation. However, the electrical signals increase the influx of [[calcium]] [[ion]]s into the cardiac muscle cells ([[cardiomyocytes]]).<ref name=\"Butter 20082\">{{cite journal|last=Butter|first=C.|display-authors=etal|date=May 2008|title=Cardiac Contractility Modulation Electrical Signals Improve Myocardial Gene Expression in Patients With Heart Failure|journal=J Am Coll Cardiol|volume=51|issue=18|pages=1784\u20131789|doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2008.01.036|pmid=18452785}}</ref><ref name=\"Yu 20092\">{{cite journal|last=Yu|first=C.M.|display-authors=etal|date=Dec 2009|title=Impact of cardiac contractility modulation on left ventricular global and regional function and remodeling|journal=JACC Cardiovasc Imaging|volume=2|issue=12|pages=1341\u20131349|doi=10.1016/j.jcmg.2009.07.011|pmid=20083066}}</ref>&nbsp;In contrast to other electrical stimulation treatments for heart failure, such as [[pacemaker]] therapy or [[implantable cardioverter defibrillator]]s (ICD), Cardiac Contractility Modulation does not directly affect cardiac rhythm. Rather, the aim is to enhance the heart's natural contraction (the native cardiac contractility) sustainably over long periods of time. Furthermore, unlike most interventions that increase cardiac contractility, Cardiac Contractility Modulation is not associated with an unfavorable increase in oxygen demand by the heart (measured in terms of Myocardial Oxygen Consumption or MVO<sub>2</sub>). This may be explained by the beneficial effect the therapy has in improving cardiac efficiency.<ref name=\"Marcus 19832\">{{cite book|title=The Coronary Circulation in Health and Disease|last=Marcus|first=Melvin L.|date=1983|publisher=McGraw Hill|isbn=978-0070402935|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/coronarycirculat0000marc}}</ref><ref name=\"Butter 20073\">{{cite journal|last=Butter|first=C.|display-authors=etal|date=Mar 2007|title=Enhanced inotropic state of the failing left ventricle by cardiac contractility modulation electrical signals is not associated with increased myocardial oxygen consumption|journal=J Card Fail|volume=13|issue=2|pages=137\u2013142|doi=10.1016/j.cardfail.2006.11.004|pmid=17395055}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 11, 2014--></ref><ref name=\"Goliasch 20123\">{{cite journal|last=Goliasch|first=G.|display-authors=etal|date=Mar 2012|title=The effect of device-based cardiac contractility modulation therapy on myocardial efficiency and oxidative metabolism in patients with heart failure|journal=Eur J Nucl Med Mol Imaging|volume=39|issue=3|pages=408\u2013415|doi=10.1007/s00259-011-1977-8|pmid=22083298}}</ref>&nbsp;A meta-analysis in 2014<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" />&nbsp;and an overview of device-based treatment options in heart failure in 2013<ref name=\"Abraham 20134\">{{cite journal|last=Abraham|first=W.T.|author2=S.A. Smith|date=Feb 2013|title=Devices in the management of advanced, chronic heart failure|journal=Nat Rev Cardiol|volume=10|issue=2|pages=98\u2013110|doi=10.1038/nrcardio.2012.178|pmc=3753073|pmid=23229137}}</ref> concluded that Cardiac contractility modulation treatment is safe,<ref name=\"Abraham 20132\" /><ref name=\"Abraham 20134\" /> that it is generally beneficial to patients<ref name=\"Abraham 20132\" /><ref name=\"Abraham 20134\" /> and that the treatment increases the [[Cardiac stress test|exercise tolerance]] (ET) and [[quality of life]] (QoL) of patients.<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /> Furthermore, preliminary long-term [[Survival analysis|survival data]] shows that Cardiac contractility modulation is associated with lower long-term [[Cause of death|mortality]] in heart failure patients when compared with expected rates among similar patients not treated with Cardiac contractility modulation.<ref name=\"Kuschyk 20152\">{{cite journal|last=Kuschyk|first=J.|display-authors=etal|date=Jan 2015|title=Efficacy and survival in patients with cardiac contractility modulation: Long-term single center experience in 81 patients|journal=Int J Cardiol|volume=183|issue=|pages=76\u201381|doi=10.1016/j.ijcard.2014.12.178|pmid=25662055}}</ref>\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n== Medical uses ==\n\n===FDA Approval===\nBased on the results of the pivotal FIX-HF-5C trial <ref>{{cite journal|last=Abraham|first=W.|display-authors=etal|date=Oct 2018|title=A Randomized Controlled Trial to Evaluate the Safety and Efficacy of Cardiac Contractility Modulation|journal=JACC Heart Failure|volume=6|issue=10|pages=874-883| doi: 10.1016/j.jchf.2018.04.010. Epub 2018 May 10.></ref>\nThe FDA approved Cardiac Contractility Modulation therapy for use in the United States on March 21, 2019.\n\n=== FDA Indication ===\nThe FDA approved the OPTIMIZER Smart System, which delivers Cardiac Contractility Modulation therapy, as indicated to improve 6-minute hall walk distance, quality of life, and functional status of NYHA Class III heart failure patients who remain symptomatic despite guideline directed medical therapy, who are in normal sinus rhythm, are not indicated for Cardiac Resynchronization Therapy, and have a left ventricular ejection fraction ranging from 25% to 45%.\n\n=== CE Mark ===\nBased on the results of clinical trials,<ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\" /><ref name=\"Kuschyk 2014a2\">{{cite journal|last=Kuschyk|first=J.|date=2014|title=Der Besondere Stellenwert der Kardialen Kontraktilit\u00e4tsmodulation in der Devicetherapie|url=http://cme.medlearning.de/herzmedizin/kardialen_kontraktilitaetsmodulation/cme.htm|journal=Herzmedizin|accessdate=Jun 6, 2014}}</ref>  Cardiac contractility modulation devices are approved and available for clinical use in all [[European Union]] countries and in [[Australia]], [[Turkey]], [[India]] and [[Hong Kong]], as well as in other countries that recognize [[CE marking]] for [[medical device]]s.\n\n=== CE Indication ===\n[[Image:SinusRhythmLabels.svg|thumb|Schematic representation of normal [[sinus rhythm]] as seen on an ECG. The QRS complex is shown in the center.]]Based on the approval of Cardiac Contractility Modulation devices, the therapy is a treatment option for patients that are at least 18 years old who suffer from [[Heart failure#Left-sided failure|heart failure symptoms]] due to left ventricular systolic dysfunction (LVSD) despite adequate medical treatment. Further clinical research are under way to identify which patient group within the scope of the device approval benefits most from Cardiac Contractility Modulation treatment.<ref name=\"Abraham 20132\" /><ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /><ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\" /><ref name=\"clinicaltrials2\">[http://clinicaltrials.gov/show/NCT01381172 clinicaltrials.gov Announcement of a study that will further investigate safety and efficacy of CCM devices]</ref>\n\nCriteria for the classification of patients with left ventricular systolic heart failure include the severity of the disease based on functional parameters (NYHA classification), the average percentage of blood volume ejected by the left ventricle with each heart beat (left ventricular [[ejection fraction]] or LVEF) and the duration of the QRS complex seen in the electrocardiogram (ECG). Most clinical studies on Cardiac Contractility Modulation therapy have involved heart failure patients who were classified initially as NYHA Class II, III or IV and had a normal QRS duration (QRS duration \u2264 120 ms). The efficacy of Cardiac Contractility Modulation on patients in an earlier stage of heart failure has not yet been studied.<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /><ref name=\"Kuck 20133\">{{cite journal|last=Kuck|first=K.-H.|display-authors=etal|date=Jan 2014|title=New devices in heart failure: an European Heart Rhythm Association report: developed by the European Heart Rhythm Association; endorsed by the Heart Failure Association|url=http://europace.oxfordjournals.org/content/europace/16/1/109.full.pdf|journal=Europace|volume=16|issue=1|pages=109\u2013128|doi=10.1093/europace/eut311|pmid=24265466|accessdate=Oct 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nA subsequent evaluation study (subgroup analysis) has already suggested a particular patient group that responds exceptionally well to Cardiac Contractility Modulation therapy. The patients were characterized by a disease severity of NYHA class III and a left ventricular ejection fraction of \u2265 25%.<ref name=\"Abraham 20132\" /><ref name=\"Abraham 20112\">{{cite journal|last=Abraham|first=W.T.|display-authors=etal|date=Sep 2011|title=Subgroup Analysis of a Randomized Controlled Trial Evaluating the Safety and Efficacy of Cardiac Contractility Modulation in Advanced Heart Failure|journal=J Card Fail|volume=17|issue=9|pages=710\u2013717|doi=10.1016/j.cardfail.2011.05.006|pmid=21872139}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 13, 2014--></ref>\n\nAlthough studies on Cardiac Contractility Modulation therapy have focused on patients with a normal QRS duration (i.e. \u2264 120 ms), it is possible to use the therapy in patients who meet the treatment indication but who do not have a normal QRS duration.<ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\" /><ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\">{{cite journal|last=Burkhoff|first=D.|date=Dec 2011|title=Does Contractility Modulation Have a Role in the Treatment of Heart Failure?|journal=Curr Heart Fail Rep|volume=8|issue=4|pages=260\u2013265|doi=10.1007/s11897-011-0067-3|pmid=21656201}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 11, 2014--></ref><ref name=\"Butter 20112\">{{cite journal|last=Butter|first=C.|date=Mar 2011|title=Verbesserung der linksventrikul\u00e4ren Kontraktilit\u00e4t durch Stimulation in der absoluten Refrakt\u00e4rperiode. Kardiale Kontraktilit\u00e4tsmodulation.|journal=Herzschr Elektrophys|volume=22|issue=1|pages=27\u201333|doi=10.1007/s00399-011-0120-7|pmid=21365468}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 15, 2014--></ref>\n\nA preliminary study has previously shown that Cardiac Contractility Modulation may be safe and effective in such patients who have not responded to [[cardiac resynchronization therapy]] (CRT).<ref name=\"Nagele 20082\">{{cite journal|last=Nagele|first=H.|author2=S. Behrens|author3=C. Eisermann|date=Dec 2008|title=Cardiac Contractility Modulation in Non-responders to Cardiac Resynchronization Therapy|url=http://europace.oxfordjournals.org/content/europace/10/12/1375.full.pdf|journal=Europace|volume=10|issue=12|pages=1375\u20131380|doi=10.1093/europace/eun257|pmid=18776196|accessdate=Oct 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Therapeutic gap ===\nCardiac resynchronization therapy (CRT; also known as biventricular pacing) has proven to be an effective treatment in heart failure.<ref name=\"ESC Guideline2\">{{cite journal|last=McMurray|first=J.J.V.|display-authors=etal|date=2012|title=ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of acute and chronic heart failure 2012|url=http://eurheartj.oxfordjournals.org/content/ehj/33/14/1787.full.pdf|journal=European Heart Journal|volume=33|issue=14|pages=1787\u20131847|doi=10.1093/eurheartj/ehs104|pmid=22611136|accessdate=Oct 10, 2014}}</ref> However, CRT is generally recommended exclusively for patients with a preserved sinus rhythm and a prolonged QRS complex (\u2265 120 ms) who also suffer from [[left bundle branch block]] (LBBB), or for patients without left bundle branch block but who have a preserved sinus rhythm and a QRS complex with a width of \u2265 150 ms.<ref name=\"ESC Guideline2\" /> However, only 30-40% of all heart failure patients show such a prolonged QRS complex, and therefore the 60-70% of patients who have a normal QRS complex cannot be treated with CRT. In addition, around 30% of the patients eligible for CRT treatment do not respond to CRT.<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /><ref name=\"Kuck 20133\" /><ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" />\n\nUntil recently, the only other available device-based treatment was the [[left ventricular assist device]] (LVAD). LVAD therapy is indicated in patients with severe illness and is associated with several hours of surgery (involving a [[cardiopulmonary bypass]]). It is usually considered as a therapy providing a \u201cbridge to transplant\u201d for heart failure patients classified as NYHA class IV, and is intended to support heart function until a [[Heart transplantation|heart transplant]] is received.<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /><ref name=\"Kuck 20133\" /><ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" /> Current research results suggest that the therapeutic gap described above could now be closed by the Cardiac contractility modulation therapy.<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /><ref name=\"Kuck 20133\" /><ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" /> Additionally, a long-term study showed that the Cardiac Contractility Modulation was able to stop the common and prognostically unfavorable long-term prolongation of QRS duration in heart failure patients. This result was interpreted as signaling the safety of the treatment and as an indicator that patients could benefit from Cardiac contractility modulation therapy in the long term. If the QRS-stabilizing effect were to be confirmed in further studies, the Cardiac Contractility Modulation would become the first device-based treatment for heart failure with the potential to halt QRS prolongation, a factor associated with a poor prognosis.<ref name=\"R\u00f6ger 2014b2\">{{cite journal|last=R\u00f6ger|first=S.|display-authors=etal|date=Aug 2014|title=Long term impact of Cardiac Contractility Modulation on QRS Duration|journal=J Electrocardiol|volume=47|issue=6|pages=936\u201340|doi=10.1016/j.jelectrocard.2014.08.011|pmid=25201417}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 11, 2014--></ref>\n\n=== Recommendations ===\nThe [[Medical guideline|guidelines]] issued by the [[European Society of Cardiology]] (ESC) in 2016, mention Cardiac Contractility Modulation therapy as a therapy option to be considered in selected group of patients with HF. Mostly these guidelines are endorsed by national cardiac societies in individual countries within the European Union.<ref name=\"ESC Guideline2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.escardio.org/Guidelines-&-Education/Clinical-Practice-Guidelines/Acute-and-Chronic-Heart-Failure|title=Acute and Chronic Heart Failure|website=www.escardio.org|access-date=2017-11-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Efficacy ===\nCardiac Contractility Modulation has proven to be effective and safe in randomized controlled trials involving several hundred patients.<ref name=\"Neelagaru 20062\">{{cite journal|last=Neelagaru|first=S.B.|display-authors=etal|date=Oct 2006|title=Nonexcitatory, cardiac contractility modulation electrical impulses: Feasibility study for advanced heart failure in patients with normal QRS duration|journal=Heart Rhythm|volume=3|issue=10|pages=1140\u20131147|doi=10.1016/j.hrthm.2006.06.031|pmid=17018340}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 16, 2014--></ref><ref name=\"Borggrefe 20082\">{{cite journal|last=Borggrefe|first=M.|display-authors=etal|date=Apr 2008|title=Randomized, double blind study of non-excitatory, cardiac contractility modulation electrical impulses for symptomatic heart failure|url=http://eurheartj.oxfordjournals.org/content/ehj/29/8/1019.full.pdf|journal=Eur Heart J|volume=29|issue=8|pages=1019\u20131028|doi=10.1093/eurheartj/ehn020|pmid=18270213|accessdate=Oct 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Kadish 20112\">{{cite journal|last=Kadish|first=A.|display-authors=etal|date=Feb 2011|title=A randomized controlled trial evaluating the safety and efficacy of cardiac contractility modulation in advanced heart failure|journal=Am Heart J|volume=161|issue=2|pages=329\u2013337|doi=10.1016/j.ahj.2010.10.025|pmid=21315216|url=https://touroscholar.touro.edu/president_pubs/44}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 16, 2014--></ref>\n\nThe nature and extent of the effect of Cardiac Contractility Modulation have been the subject of numerous investigations. Although various individual publications, as well as one of two meta-analyses, have presented the efficacy and significant potential of Cardiac Contractility Modulation in the treatment of heart failure, medical evaluation of the therapy efficacy is not yet complete. Scientists point out, however, that this was also the case for CRT therapy when it was first introduced, advocating the provision of Cardiac contractility modulation to suitable patients before further studies are completed.<ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\" /><ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" />\n\nTo date (February 2015), there are at least two meta-analyses studying the efficacy of Cardiac contractility modulation therapy on heart failure,<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /><ref name=\"Kwong 20122\">{{cite journal|last=Kwong|first=J.S.|author2=J.E. Sanderson|author3=C.M. Yu|date=Sep 2012|title=Cardiac contractility modulation for heart failure: a meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials|journal=Pacing Clin Electrophysiol|volume=35|issue=5|pages=1111\u20131118|doi=10.1111/j.1540-8159.2012.03449.x|pmid=22734676}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 16, 2014--></ref> a large number of review articles (e.g.<ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\" /><ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" /><ref name=\"Butter 20112\" /><ref name=\"Kuschyk 2014b2\">{{cite journal|last=Kuschyk|first=J.|author2=S. R\u00f6ger|author3=M. Borggrefe|date=Oct 2014|title=Kardiale Kontraktilit\u00e4tsmodulation zur Behandlung der symptomatischen Herzinsuffizienz|journal=Der Kardiologe|volume=8|issue=5|pages=407\u2013414|doi=10.1007/s12181-014-0595-7|id=}}</ref><ref name=\"Kuschyk 20132\">{{cite journal|last=Kuschyk|first=J.|author2=M. Borggrefe|date=2013|title=Elektrische Therapie der Herzinsuffizienz|journal=Kardio up|volume=9|issue=1|pages=37\u201356|doi=10.1055/s-0032-1326192|id=}}</ref>) and at least two survey articles on device-based treatments of advanced heart failure<ref name=\"Abraham 20132\" /><ref name=\"Kuck 20133\" /> which address cardiac contractility modulation. Furthermore, there are more than 70 individual publications focusing specifically on Cardiac contractility modulation therapy.<ref name=\"PubMed Suche2\">Research of the [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed Pubmed data base] for the search term \"Cardiac Contractility Modulation\" in the title of publications performed on Oct 16, 2014</ref>\n\nFurther randomized controlled trials studying the effect of Cardiac Contractility Modulation on the progression of heart failure have been initiated and are currently (as of Feb 2015) recruiting patients.<ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\" /><ref name=\"clinicaltrials2\" /><ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" />\n\n==== Meta-analyses ====\nGiallauria et al. evaluated the three [[randomized controlled trial]]s (RCTs) currently available on Cardiac contractility modulation as a treatment for heart failure patients.<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /><ref name=\"Neelagaru 20062\" /><ref name=\"Borggrefe 20082\" /> The three trials included a total of 641 patients and assessed the effect of Cardiac contractility modulation either in comparison to a sham treatment<ref name=\"Neelagaru 20062\" /><ref name=\"Borggrefe 20082\" /> or in comparison to the best medical treatment.<ref name=\"Kadish 20112\" /> In contrast to an earlier meta-analysis by Kwong et al.<ref name=\"Kwong 20122\" /> the study did not evaluate the data based on summarized results alone, but on the basis of the individual data sets of the 641 enrolled patients.\n\nThe study concluded that Cardiac contractility modulation significantly improved important markers of cardiac performance. These included the [[maximal oxygen uptake]] (peak VO2 or pVO2 \u2013 measured by ventilatory parameters during a cardiopulmonary exercise test), which is indicative of improved survival,<ref name=\"Pakarinen 20102\">{{cite journal|last=Pakarinen|first=S.|author2=L. Oikarinen|author3=L. Toivonen|date=Jan 2010|title=Short-term implantation-related complications of cardiac rhythm management device therapy: a retrospective single-centre 1-year survey|url=http://europace.oxfordjournals.org/content/europace/12/1/103.full.pdf|journal=Europace|volume=12|issue=1|pages=103\u2013108|doi=10.1093/europace/eup361|pmid=19914920|accessdate=Nov 6, 2014}}</ref> and the [[Cardiovascular & pulmonary physiotherapy#6 Minute Walk Test .286MWT.29|6-minute walk test]]. The quality of life of participating patients, measured by the Minnesota Living with Heart Failure Questionnaire (MLWHFQ), also improved significantly. However, both meta-analyses demanded additional and larger randomized controlled trials in order to evaluate the effect of the therapy more precisely.\n\nGiallauria et al. describe the success of cardiac contractility modulation and the further potential of the therapy. Particular emphasis is given to the possibility that Cardiac contractility modulation therapy may close the [[Cardiac contractility modulation#Therapeutic Gap in Heart Failure Treatment|therapeutic gap]] in heart failure treatment if previous study outcomes are confirmed.\n\n==== Long-Term Survival Studies ====\nAs of February 2015, the effect of Cardiac contractility modulation therapy on the long-term mortality rates of heart failure patients has not been studied in a randomized controlled trial. Some preliminary single-center studies have been reported though.<ref name=\"Kuschyk 20152\" /> Kuschyk et al. evaluated the long-term efficacy and survival of patients with Cardiac contractility modulation.<ref name=\"Kuschyk 20152\" /> Their analysis included 81 patients with a disease severity of NYHA class II, III or IV and a mean follow-up of around 3 years. The analysis compared the observed mortality rate with the prediction of the Meta-analysis Global Group in Chronic Heart Failure (MAGGIC) model<ref name=\"MAGGIC data2\">{{cite journal|last=Pocock|first=S.J.|display-authors=etal|date=May 2013|title=Predicting survival in heart failure: a risk score based on 39 372 patients from 30 studies|url=http://eurheartj.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2012/10/23/eurheartj.ehs337|journal=Eur Heart J|volume=34|issue=19|pages=1404\u20131413|doi=10.1093/eurheartj/ehs337|pmid=23095984|accessdate=Feb 20, 2015|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\"MAGGIC2\">[http://www.heartfailurerisk.org/ \"MAGGIC\" Heart Failure Risc Calculator according to Pocock et al. ''Predicting survival in heart failure: a risk score based on 39 372 patients from 30 studies'', Eur Heart J (2013) 34(19) 1404-1413 (linked above)]</ref> which is based on the records of over 39,000 heart failure patients. Unlike a previous long-term outcome study of Cardiac contractility modulation,<ref name=\"Schau 20112\">{{cite journal|last=Schau|first=T.|display-authors=etal|date=Apr 2011|title=Long-term outcome of cardiac contractility modulation in patients with severe congestive heart failure|url=http://europace.oxfordjournals.org/content/13/10/1436.full-text.pdf|journal=Europace|volume=13|issue=10|pages=1436\u20131444|doi=10.1093/europace/eur153|pmid=21712286|accessdate=Feb 20, 2015}}</ref> this study was not limited by a widely heterogeneous group of patients.\n\nFollowing long-term observation, the study concluded that Cardiac contractility modulation improved quality of life, exercise tolerance, NYHA class, left ventricular ejection fraction (LVEF) and [[brain natriuretic peptide]] (BNP) levels. Mortality rates were significantly lower than predicted at year 1, and lower than predicted but not statistically significant at year 3.\n\n==== General ====\n\nHeart failure is a chronic disease that usually progresses gradually.<ref name=\"ESC Guideline2\" /> The rate of progression and the degree of symptoms of the disease varies between different patients. Cardiac contractility modulation therapy aims to treat heart failure through a medium- to long-term treatment, over the course of weeks and months.\n\nAccording to large implanting clinics, after the implantation wound is healed, the lifestyle of a patient is not restricted by the implanted device.<ref name=\"Pacemaker life2\">[http://www.heart.org/HEARTORG/Conditions/Arrhythmia/PreventionTreatmentofArrhythmia/Living-With-Your-Pacemaker_UCM_305290_Article.jsp Tips by the American Heart Associuation \"Living With Your Pacemaker\"]</ref> Leisure, travel (by car, train, ship or plane), hobbies and sex life will not be restricted. The patient may perceive an improved capacity for these activities and overall enhanced performance and exercise capacity in response to the actual therapy.\n\n==Contraindications ==\nIn the past, the most important contraindication in Cardiac contractility modulation treatment was permanent and long-standing persistent [[atrial fibrillation]]. The signal application in current Cardiac contractility modulation devices was timed and triggered according to the electrical activity of the [[Atrium (heart)|atrium]]. In atrial fibrillation, electrical activity in the atrium is severely disturbed and is therefore not a reliable basis for the triggering of Cardiac contractility modulation signals. This also applies to other diseases involving severe disturbance in electrical atrial sensing.<ref name=\"R\u00f6ger 2014a2\">{{cite journal|last=R\u00f6ger|first=S.|display-authors=etal|date=Apr 2014|title=Cardiac contractility modulation: first experience in heart failure patients with reduced ejection fraction and permanent atrial fibrillation|journal=Europace|volume=16|issue=8|pages=1205\u20139|doi=10.1093/europace/euu050|pmid=24706089}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 14, 2014--></ref> Requests have been raised in scientific literature for an improved Cardiac contractility modulation algorithm which would allow the therapy to be delivered independently from any atrial signal. A pioneering study had shown that an improved Cardiac contractility modulation algorithm could make the therapy an effective treatment for patients with persistent atrial fibrillation.<ref name=\"R\u00f6ger 2014a2\" /> Following these study results the new generation was developed and can now offer Cardiac contractility modulation therapy also for patients with [[atrial fibrillation]].\n\nOther irregular rhythms, including frequent [[premature ventricular contraction]]s (ventricular extra systoles) or a distinct signal transduction disorder in the heart (untreated [[AV block]] of more than 300 ms), may represent contraindications. CRT treatment should be considered in lieu of Cardiac contractility modulation in patients with left bundle branch block (LBBB) and a QRS duration of over 120 ms, or when the QRS duration is greater than 150 ms and independent of LBBB.<ref name=\"Abraham 20134\" /><ref name=\"ESC Guideline2\" />\n\nAs with conventional pacemaker therapy, the Cardiac contractility modulation device cannot be implanted if the leads cannot be positioned appropriately in the heart. In cases where there is an [[artificial heart valve]] between the right atrium and ventricle (a mechanical prosthetic tricuspid valve), the valve function could be greatly affected by the ventricular leads. In some instances it may be impossible to guide the leads through the main veins in the upper half of the body to the heart due to [[venous thrombosis]], for example [[Artificial cardiac pacemaker#mode|VVI pacemakers]], in the case of 100% stimulation, are also contraindicated.<ref name=\"Abraham 20134\" />\n\n== Side effects ==\nThe most frequently encountered adverse events related to Cardiac contractility modulation therapy are lead fracture or lead dislodgement.<ref name=\"Kadish 20112\" /> Other reported complications include:\n* Infection and bleeding at the IPG implantation site\n* Accumulation of fluid in the pericardium ([[pericardial effusion]])<ref name=\"Borggrefe 20082\" />\n\nThese side effects are similar to those that occur with other electrical stimulation therapies, such as pacemakers, CRT devices or ICD devices.<ref name=\"Pakarinen 20102\" /> Furthermore, recorded complications did not differ between patients with activated or deactivated Cardiac contractility modulation devices.<ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" />\n\nOverall, Cardiac contractility modulation treatment was demonstrated to have no negative impact on health markers.<ref name=\"Burkhoff 20112\" />\n\n=== Precautions ===\n\n[[File:Flughafenkontrolle.jpg|thumb|Metal detectors used for security screening]]\nSimilarly to patients with other electrical stimulation devices, patients with a Cardiac contractility modulation device must follow certain precautions arising from the device implantation and its function.\n* Electromagnetic fields: Strong electromagnetic fields can interfere with the function of the device. Most interference will lead to inhibition of Cardiac contractility modulation signal delivery. Once away from the field, the device will resume its normal function in most cases. The electromagnetic fields of household appliances are usually considered harmless.<ref name=\"Pacemaker EM-fields2\">[http://www.heart.org/HEARTORG/Conditions/Arrhythmia/PreventionTreatmentofArrhythmia/Implantable-Cardioverter-Defibrillator-ICD_UCM_448478_Article.jsp Safety recommendations of the American Heart Association for patients with artificial pacemakers]</ref><ref name=\"ICD EM-fields2\">[http://www.heart.org/HEARTORG/Conditions/Arrhythmia/PreventionTreatmentofArrhythmia/Implantable-Cardioverter-Defibrillator-ICD_UCM_448478_Article.jsp Safety recommendations of the American Heart Association for patients with implantable cardioverter defibrillators (ICDs)]</ref>\n* Mobile phones: Similarly to other electrical stimulation devices, such as pacemakers, aside from a recommended safety distance of 10\u201315&nbsp;cm (4-6 inches) between the device and mobile phones, there are no restrictions on the use of mobile phones.<ref name=\"Pacemaker EM-fields2\" />\n* Security checks: Full body or hand-held metal detectors, such as those used at airport security controls, do not usually affect the function of the device. However, where such detectors are used there are often signs warning people with cardiac pacemakers and defibrillators, and Cardiac contractility modulation patients are therefore advised to present their device ID. In these cases, the security check will typically continue with the use of a hand-held metal detector or by physical inspection.<ref name=\"Pacemaker EM-fields2\" />\n* Sports: All sports associated with increased stress on the arms or the chest, such as body building, martial arts or tennis, are usually not permitted. Diving is only permitted up to a depth of 5 meters due to the high pressure at greater depths.<ref name=\"Pacemaker life2\" />\n* Sports: All sports associated with increased stress on the arms or the chest, such as body building, martial arts or tennis, are usually not permitted. Diving is only permitted up to a depth of 5 meters due to the high pressure at greater depth.<ref name=\"Dill 2008-MRI2\">{{cite journal|last=Dill|first=T.|date=Jul 2008|title=Contraindications to magnetic resonance imaging|url=http://www.rad.pitt.edu/public/mrrc-docs/ContraindicationsMRI.pdf|journal=Heart|volume=94|issue=7|pages=943\u2013948|doi=10.1136/hrt.2007.125039|pmid=18552230|accessdate=Feb 22, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402105422/http://www.rad.pitt.edu/public/mrrc-docs/ContraindicationsMRI.pdf|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI): Similarly to other electrical stimulation devices, such as pacemakers, Cardiac contractility modulation therapy is a contraindication for MRI, a medical imaging technique.<ref name=\"Dill 2008-MRI2\" />\n\n== Mechanism of action ==\nThe [[mechanism of action]] of Cardiac contractility modulation has been subject to continuous research since its initial discovery. Based on [[animal testing]] and experiments on human myocardial tissue obtained by [[biopsies]], essential parts of the mechanism of action have been identified.<ref name=\"Butter 20082\" /><ref name=\"Lyon 20132\">{{cite journal|last=Lyon|first=A.R.|author2=M.A. Samara|author3=D.S. Feldman|date=Oct 2013|title=Cardiac contractility modulation therapy in advanced systolic heart failure|journal=Nat. Rev. Cardiol.|volume=10|issue=10|pages=584\u2013598|doi=10.1038/nrcardio.2013.114|pmid=23939481}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 23, 2014--></ref> According to current understanding (as of February 2015), the mechanism of action of Cardiac contractility modulation may be summarized in the following manner: The signals applied during the electrical non-excitatory state of the cardiac muscle cells (the absolute refractory period) cause an increase in myocyte calcium in the cytosol during systole. This increases the muscle contraction strength. Additionally, within minutes, cell [[metabolism]] and [[gene expression]], which are typically abnormal in heart failure, improve towards their normal state.<ref name=\"Lyon 20132\" /> This beneficial effect occurs initially only in the area adjacent to the electrodes, but with time also spreads to remote areas of the cardiac muscle.<ref name=\"Lyon 20132\" /> Cardiac contractility modulation therefore restores the structure and function of damaged cells back towards their normal state. In some cases, disease-related changes in the ventricular heart structure can be partially reversed by Cardiac contractility modulation through a process known as reverse remodeling of the heart.<ref name=\"Borggrefe 20122\" /><ref name=\"Butter 20082\" /><ref name=\"Yu 20092\" /><ref name=\"Butter 20112\" /><ref name=\"Imai 20072\">{{cite journal|last=Imai|first=M.|display-authors=etal|date=May 2007|title=Therapy with cardiac contractility modulation electrical signals improves left ventricular function and remodeling in dogs with chronic heart failure|journal=J Am Coll Cardiol|volume=49|issue=21|pages=2120\u20132128|doi=10.1016/j.jacc.2006.10.082|pmid=17531662}}</ref><ref name=\"Gupta 20082\">{{cite journal|last=Gupta|first=R.C.|display-authors=etal|date=Feb 2009|title=Cardiac Contractility Modulation Electrical Signals Normalize Activity, Expression, and Phosphorylation of the Na+-Ca2+ Exchanger in Heart Failure|journal=Journal of Cardiac Failure|volume=15|issue=1|pages=48\u201356|doi=10.1016/j.cardfail.2008.08.011|pmid=19181294}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nDevelopment of cardiac contractility modulation began in the late 1990s.<ref name=\"patent2\">[https://archive.is/20150308200716/http://patft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-Parser?Sect2=PTO1&Sect2=HITOFF&p=1&u=/netahtml/PTO/search-bool.html&r=1&f=G&l=50&d=PALL&RefSrch=yes&Query=PN/6360126 Patent for CCM: ''Apparatus and method for controlling the delivery of contractility modulating non-excitatory signals to the heart'']</ref><ref name=\"Mohri2\">{{cite journal|last=Mohri|first=S.|display-authors=etal|date=May 2002|title=Cardiac contractility modulation by electric currents applied during the refractory period|journal=Am J Physiol Heart Circ Physiol|volume=282|issue=5|pages=H1642\u2013H1647|doi=10.1152/ajpheart.00959.2001|pmid=11959626|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/7d14951c1e80e58bbddaf946231f7a709cf5a952}}</ref> Studies on individual cardiac muscle cells using a patch-clamp technique had already shown, in 1969, that a voltage applied during the absolute refractory period through leads between the interior of the cell and its outside environment increased the calcium influx through the cell membrane and improved the contraction of cardiac muscle cells.<ref name=\"Antoni2\">{{cite journal|last=Antoni|first=H.|author2=R. Jacob|author3=R. Kaufmann|date=1969|title=Mechanical response of the frog and mammalian myocardium to changes in the action potential duration by constant current pulses|journal=Pfl\u00fcgers Arch|volume=306|issue=1|pages=33\u201357|pmid=4975967|doi=10.1007/bf00586610}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 9, 2014--></ref><ref name=\"Wood2\">{{cite journal|last=Wood|first=E.H.|author2=R.L. Heppner|author3=S. Weidmann|date=Mar 1969|title=Inotropic effects of electric currents. I. Positive and negative effects of constant electric currents or current pulses applied during cardiac action potentials. II. Hypotheses: calcium movements, excitation-contraction coupling and inotropic effects.|journal=Circ Res|volume=24|issue=3|pages=409\u2013445|doi=10.1161/01.RES.24.3.409|pmid=5766519|doi-access=free}}</ref> In 2001, scientists observed that a similar effect occurs even if the voltage is applied exclusively outside the cardiac muscle cells.[[Cardiac contractility modulation#cite note-Burkhoff 2001-48|<sup>[48]</sup>]] Additionally, it was observed that therapeutically useful effects on the cardiac muscle were achieved if the electrical signals were applied not only to single cells but to large areas using larger leads, as used in conventional cardiac pacemakers. The contractility of both a healthy heart and a damaged heart could be increased through application of appropriate signals during the absolute refractory period of the cardiac muscle cells.<ref name=\"Burkhoff 20012\">{{cite journal|last=Burkhoff|first=D.|display-authors=etal|date=Jan 2001|title=Electric currents applied during the refractory period can modulate cardiac contractility in vitro and in vivo|journal=Heart Fail Rev|volume=6|issue=1|pages=27\u201334|pmid=11248765|doi=10.1023/A:1009851107189}}</ref><ref name=\"Sabbah2\">{{cite journal|last=Sabbah|first=H.N.|display-authors=etal|date=Jan 2001|title=Cardiac contractility modulation with the impulse dynamics signal: studies in dogs with chronic heart failure|journal=Heart Fail Rev|volume=6|issue=1|pages=45\u201353|pmid=11248767|doi=10.1023/A:1009855208097}}<!--| accessdate = Oct 9, 2014--></ref>\n\nAn implantable Cardiac contractility modulation device was received by a patient for the first time in 2001.<ref name=\"Pappone 20012\">{{cite journal|last=Pappone|first=C.|display-authors=etal|date=Jan 2001|title=Electrical modulation of cardiac contractility: clinical aspects in congestive heart failure|journal=Heart Fail Rev|volume=6|issue=1|pages=55\u201360|pmid=11248768|doi=10.1023/A:1009807309006}}<!--| accessdate = Nov 6, 2014--></ref><ref name=\"Pappone 20022\">{{cite journal|last=Pappone|first=C.|display-authors=etal|date=Dec 2002|title=Cardiac contractility modulation by electric currents applied during the refractory period in patients with heart failure secondary to ischemic or idiopathic dilated cardiomyopathy|journal=Am J Cardiol|volume=90|issue=12|pages=1307\u20131313|doi=10.1016/s0002-9149(02)02868-0|pmid=12480039}}<!--| accessdate = Nov 6, 2014--></ref> The first study on the therapeutic effects of in humans was presented in 2004.<ref name=\"Stix 20042\">{{cite journal|last=Stix|first=G.|display-authors=etal|date=Apr 2014|title=Chronic electrical stimulation during the absolute refractory period of the myocardium improves severe heart failure|url=http://eurheartj.oxfordjournals.org/content/ehj/25/8/650.full.pdf|journal=Eur Heart J|volume=25|issue=8|pages=650\u2013655|doi=10.1016/j.ehj.2004.02.027|pmid=15084369|accessdate=Oct 10, 2014}}</ref> To date, more than 3,000 heart failure patients have been treated with Cardiac contractility modulation worldwide,<ref name=\"Kuschyk 2014a2\" /> including 641 patients under the study conditions recommended by the [[Cochrane Collaboration]] as being necessary for inclusion in a meta-analysis.<ref name=\"Giallauria 20142\" /> Cardiac contractility modulation device implant was first successfully done in India in Royal Hospital,Trivandrum,Kerala,under the leadership of the Chief Cardiologist Dr. C. Bharath Chandran. Advocate Harishankar is the first person in India to get the CCM device implanted.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Heart]]\n* [[Cardiac cycle]]\n* [[Heart failure]]\n* [[Artificial cardiac pacemaker]]\n* [[Implantable cardioverter-defibrillator]]\n* [[NYHA classification]]\n* [[Cardiac resynchronization therapy]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n== External links ==\n* [http://europace.oxfordjournals.org/content/europace/16/1/109.full.pdf Current assessment of new device therapies for heart failure by the European Heart Rhythm Association (EHRA) \u2013 includes Cardiac contractility modulation]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cardiac contractility modulation}}\n[[Category:Cardiac procedures]]\n", "name_user": "Grimes2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFDA Approval:format cite template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cardiac_contractility_modulation"}
{"title_page": "Transplastomic plant", "text_new": "A '''transplastomic plant''' is a [[genetically modified plant]] in which [[Gene|genes]] are inactivated, modified or new foreign genes are inserted into the [[DNA]] of [[Chloroplast|chloroplasts]] instead of nuclear DNA.\n\n==Transformation technology==\nThe most common method to transform plastids is particle bombardment: Small gold or tungsten particles are coated with DNA and shot into young plant cells or plant embryos. Some genetic material will stay in the cells and transform them. The [[Transformation (genetics)|transformation]] efficiency is lower than in [[Agrobacterium tumefaciens|agrobacterial]] mediated transformation, which is also common in plant genetic engineering, but particle bombardment is especially suitable for plastid transformation.\n\nIn order to persist and be stably maintained in the cell, a plasmid DNA molecule must contain an [[origin of replication]], which allows it to be replicated in the cell independently of the [[chromosome]]. Because transformation usually produces a mixture of rare transformed cells and abundant non-transformed cells, a method is needed to identify the cells that have acquired the plasmid. Plasmids used in transformation experiments will usually also contain a gene giving resistance to an antibiotic (or, more recently developed resistance against a herbicide) that the intended recipient strain of bacteria is sensitive to. Selection for cells able to grow on media containing this antibiotic can then select the cells that have acquired the plasmid by transformation, as cells lacking the plasmid will be unable to grow.\n\n==Biological containment and agricultural coexistence==\nGenetically modified plants must be safe for the environment and suitable for [[Co-existence of genetically modified and conventional crops and derived food and feed|coexistence with conventional and organic crops]]. Towards such safety, a major hurdle is posed by the potential [[outcrossing]] of the [[transgene]] via pollen movement. Plastid transformation, which yields transplastomic plants in which the pollen does not contain the transgene, not only increases biosafety, but also facilitates the coexistence of genetically modified, conventional and organic agriculture. Therefore, developing such crops is a major goal of research projects such as [[Co-Extra]] and Transcontainer.\n\n==Transplastomic tobacco==\nHowever, plastid transformation is suitable only for certain crop species, and the reliability of this method has only been proven for tobacco. Led by Ralph Bock from the Max Planck Institute of Molecular Plant Physiology in Germany, researchers studied genetically modified tobacco in which the transgene was integrated in chloroplasts.<ref>{{Citation | last = Bock | first = Ralph |  title = Determining the transgene containment level provided by chloroplast transformation | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | volume = 104 | issue = 17 | pages = 6998\u20137002 | year = 2007 | url = http://www.pnas.org/cgi/content/abstract/104/17/6998 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0700008104 | pmid = 17420459 | last2 = Karcher | first2 = D | last3 = Bock | first3 = R | pmc = 1849964}}</ref> Since past literature reported contradicting figures on the reliability of this process, the Co-Extra researchers analysed more than two million seedlings and found that less than 20 in 1,000,000 inherited the transgene. In the pollen of adult plants, the rate was even lower, remaining below 3 in 1,000,000. This reduction is because some parts of the seedlings are lost during their development into mature plants.\n\nBecause tobacco has a strong tendency towards self-fertilisation, the reliability of transplastomic plants is assumed to be even higher under field conditions. Therefore, the researchers believe that only one in 100,000,000 GM tobacco plants actually would transmit the transgene via pollen. Such values are more than satisfactory to ensure coexistence. However, for GM crops used in the production of pharmaceuticals, or in other cases in which absolutely no outcrossing is permitted, the researchers recommend the combination of chloroplast transformation with other [[biological containment]] methods, such as [[cytoplasmic male sterility]] or transgene mitigation strategies.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.co-extra.eu Co-Extra] Research on the co-existence and traceability of genetically modified plants\n*[http://www.transcontainer.org/UK/ Transcontainer] Developing biological containment systems for genetically modified plants\n\n[[Category:Genetic engineering]]\n[[Category:Genetically modified organisms in agriculture]]\n", "text_old": "A '''transplastomic plant''' is a [[genetically modified plant]] in which the new [[gene]]s have not been inserted in the nuclear [[DNA]] but in the DNA of the [[chloroplast]]s. The major advantage of this technology is that in many plant species [[plastid]] DNA is not transmitted through pollen, which prevents [[gene flow]] from the genetically modified plant to other plants.\n\n==Transformation technology==\nThe most common method to transform plastids is particle bombardment: Small gold or tungsten particles are coated with DNA and shot into young plant cells or plant embryos. Some genetic material will stay in the cells and transform them. The [[Transformation (genetics)|transformation]] efficiency is lower than in [[Agrobacterium tumefaciens|agrobacterial]] mediated transformation, which is also common in plant genetic engineering, but particle bombardment is especially suitable for plastid transformation.\n\nIn order to persist and be stably maintained in the cell, a plasmid DNA molecule must contain an [[origin of replication]], which allows it to be replicated in the cell independently of the [[chromosome]]. Because transformation usually produces a mixture of rare transformed cells and abundant non-transformed cells, a method is needed to identify the cells that have acquired the plasmid. Plasmids used in transformation experiments will usually also contain a gene giving resistance to an antibiotic (or, more recently developed resistance against a herbicide) that the intended recipient strain of bacteria is sensitive to. Selection for cells able to grow on media containing this antibiotic can then select the cells that have acquired the plasmid by transformation, as cells lacking the plasmid will be unable to grow.\n\n==Biological containment and agricultural coexistence==\nGenetically modified plants must be safe for the environment and suitable for [[Co-existence of genetically modified and conventional crops and derived food and feed|coexistence with conventional and organic crops]]. Towards such safety, a major hurdle is posed by the potential [[outcrossing]] of the [[transgene]] via pollen movement. Plastid transformation, which yields transplastomic plants in which the pollen does not contain the transgene, not only increases biosafety, but also facilitates the coexistence of genetically modified, conventional and organic agriculture. Therefore, developing such crops is a major goal of research projects such as [[Co-Extra]] and Transcontainer.\n\n==Transplastomic tobacco==\nHowever, plastid transformation is suitable only for certain crop species, and the reliability of this method has only been proven for tobacco. Led by Ralph Bock from the Max Planck Institute of Molecular Plant Physiology in Germany, researchers studied genetically modified tobacco in which the transgene was integrated in chloroplasts.<ref>{{Citation | last = Bock | first = Ralph |  title = Determining the transgene containment level provided by chloroplast transformation | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences | volume = 104 | issue = 17 | pages = 6998\u20137002 | year = 2007 | url = http://www.pnas.org/cgi/content/abstract/104/17/6998 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0700008104 | pmid = 17420459 | last2 = Karcher | first2 = D | last3 = Bock | first3 = R | pmc = 1849964}}</ref> Since past literature reported contradicting figures on the reliability of this process, the Co-Extra researchers analysed more than two million seedlings and found that less than 20 in 1,000,000 inherited the transgene. In the pollen of adult plants, the rate was even lower, remaining below 3 in 1,000,000. This reduction is because some parts of the seedlings are lost during their development into mature plants.\n\nBecause tobacco has a strong tendency towards self-fertilisation, the reliability of transplastomic plants is assumed to be even higher under field conditions. Therefore, the researchers believe that only one in 100,000,000 GM tobacco plants actually would transmit the transgene via pollen. Such values are more than satisfactory to ensure coexistence. However, for GM crops used in the production of pharmaceuticals, or in other cases in which absolutely no outcrossing is permitted, the researchers recommend the combination of chloroplast transformation with other [[biological containment]] methods, such as [[cytoplasmic male sterility]] or transgene mitigation strategies.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.co-extra.eu Co-Extra] Research on the co-existence and traceability of genetically modified plants\n*[http://www.transcontainer.org/UK/ Transcontainer] Developing biological containment systems for genetically modified plants\n\n[[Category:Genetic engineering]]\n[[Category:Genetically modified organisms in agriculture]]\n", "name_user": "Asteroidz19", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transplastomic_plant"}
{"title_page": "Han Sorya", "text_new": "{{Good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Korean name|Han}}\n{{Infobox writer  <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].-->\n| name = Han Sorya\n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = Han S\u014frya portrait.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = Portrait of Han Sorya\n| caption = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = Han Py\u014fngdo\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1900|08|03|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Hamhung]], [[Korean Empire]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1976|04|06|1900|08|03}}\n| death_place = [[Pyongyang]], [[North Korea|Democratic People's Republic of Korea]]\n| resting_place = [[Patriotic Martyrs' Cemetery]]\n| occupation = novelist, short story writer, literary administrator, politician\n| language = Korean\n| nationality = Korean\n| citizenship = North Korean\n| education = \n| alma_mater = [[Nippon University]]\n| period = 20th century\n| genre =         <!-- or: | genres =      -->\n| subject =       <!-- or: | subjects =    -->\n| movement = [[Proletarian literature]]<ref name=\"Lee2007\">{{cite book|author=Namhee Lee|title=The Making of Minjung: Democracy and the Politics of Representation in South Korea|url=https://archive.org/details/makingofminjungd00leen_0|url-access=registration|year=2007|location=Ithaca|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0-8014-4566-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/makingofminjungd00leen_0/page/270 270]}}</ref>\n| notableworks = ''[[Jackals (Han Sorya novel)|Jackals]]'', ''[[History (Han Sorya novel)|History]]'' <!-- or: | notablework = -->\n| spouse =        <!-- or: | spouses =     -->\n| partner =       <!-- or: | partners =    -->\n| children = \n| relatives = \n| awards = [[Order of the National Flag]] (second class, 1951),{{sfn|Wit|2015|p=44}} [[People's Prize]] (''History'', 1958), title of [[People's Artist]] (1958){{sfn|Myers|1994|p=191}}\n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| years_active = \n| module =\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| title          =\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| context        =north\n| hangul         ={{linktext|\ud55c|\uc124|\uc57c}}\n| hanja          ={{linktext|\u97d3|\u96ea|\u91ce}}<ref>{{cite journal|publisher=\ud55c\uad6d\ubb38\ud559\uc774\ub860\uacfc \ube44\ud3c9 \uc81c16\uc9d1|date=September 2002|pages=342\u2013368|script-title=ko:\ud55c\uc77c \uc804\ud5a5\uc18c\uc124\uc758 \ubb38\ud559\uc0ac\uc801 \uc131\uaca9-\ud55c\uc124\uc57c(\u97d3\u96ea\u91ce)\uc640 \ub098\uce74\ub178 \uc2dc\uac8c\ud558\ub8e8(\u4e2d\u91ce\u91cd\u6cbb)\ub97c \uc911\uc2ec\uc73c\ub85c The Characteristics of the Novel of Conversion in Korea and Japan|author=\ud669\uce58\ubcf5|url=http://www.dbpia.co.kr/Journal/ArticleDetail/425374|access-date=27 June 2015}}</ref>\n| rr             =Han Seol-ya\n| mr             =Han S\u014frya\n| koreanipa      =\n| hangulborn     = {{linktext|\ud55c|\ubcd1|\ub3c4}}\n| hanjaborn      = {{linktext|\u97d3|\u79c9|\u9053}}\n| rrborn         = Han Byeongdo\n| mrborn         =Han Py\u014fngdo\n| koreanipaborn  =\n| text           =\n| child=yes\n}}\n| website = \n| portaldisp = on<!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n| ethnicity = \n}}\n\n'''Han Sorya''' ({{lang-ko|\ud55c\uc124\uc57c}}, born '''Han Py\u014fngdo''';{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}} 3 August 1900 \u2013 6 April 1976) was a Korean writer, literary administrator and politician who spent much of his career in [[North Korea]]. Regarded as one of the most important fiction writers in North Korean history, Han also ran the entire North Korean literary scene as the head of the [[Korean Writers' Union]] and [[Ministry of Education (North Korea)|minister of education]].\n\nDuring his career, Han survived a number of purges that were caused by [[Workers' Party of North Korea#Factionalism|factional strife]] within the [[Workers' Party of North Korea]], to become a member of  the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea]]. Han, motivated by personal grievances against his rival writers, sometimes acted as the force behind the purges within the cultural establishment as well. Han himself was purged in 1962. In his works, Han offered some of the earliest known contributions to the [[cult of personality of Kim Il-sung]]. His influence is felt in North Korea even today, though his name has been forgotten from official histories. Han's best-known work, the [[anti-American]] novella ''[[Jackals (Han Sorya novel)|Jackals]]'', however, has been invoked in the 2000s.\n\n==Early life==\nHan was born on 3 August 1900 in [[Hamhung]], in the north of [[Korea under Japanese rule|Korea]]. His father was a county magistrate. He graduated from middle school in 1919 and attended [[Nippon University]] in Tokyo from 1921 to 1924,{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}} studying [[sociology]].{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=20}} He emigrated to [[Manchuria]] in 1925 but returned to [[Seoul]] in the south in 1927.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}} In 1944, he returned to his native Hamhung. After the [[liberation of Korea]] he settled in [[Pyongyang]].{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}}\n\n==Career==\nHan was one of the most prominent fiction writers in the history of [[North Korean literature]].<ref name=\"Yearn1995\"/> During his career, Han earned the official title of \"the greatest writer of modern Korean literature\", which he shared with [[Yi Kiy\u014fng]], and was called a \"living classic\".{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} Han's career was at its height from 1955 to 1957.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} Han, along with [[Kim Tu-bong]], shaped North Korea's cultural policies.<ref>{{cite book|last=Howard|first=Keith|chapter=Music across the DMZ|editor-first1=John Morgan|editor-last1=O'Connell|editor-first2=Salwa El-Shawan|editor-last2=Castelo-Branco|title=Music and Conflict|location=Champaign|publisher=University of Illinois Press|date=September 2010|via=ProQuest ebrary|url=http://site.ebrary.com/lib/alltitles/docDetail.action?docID=10603913|page=82|isbn=978-0-252-09025-7}}</ref>\n\n===In pre-liberation Korea===\nBefore the liberation of Korea, Han was an insignificant author. His subsequent fame would only be due to his association with the {{Interlanguage link multi|Korean Artist Proletarian Federation|ko|3=\uc870\uc120\ud504\ub864\ub808\ud0c0\ub9ac\uc544\uc608\uc220\uac00\ub3d9\ub9f9}} (KAPF),<ref name=\"Gabroussenko2013\">{{Cite web | title = Benoit Symposium: Writers in the DPRK: The Invisible Stars | last = Gabroussenko|first=Tatiana  | work = Sino-NK | date =  27 September 2013 | accessdate = 21 August 2016 | url = http://sinonk.com/2013/09/27/writers-in-the-dprk-the-invisible-stars/}}</ref> which he joined in [[Seoul]] in 1927. The organization had been founded in 1925 during his emigration in Manchuria,{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}} and after the liberation it would have been the only left-leaning Korean literary organization. For this reason, [[Kim Il-sung]] would promote writers like Han who had belonged to it and exaggerated their achievements.<ref name=\"Gabroussenko2013\"/>\n\nDuring the early 1930s, Han did briefly associate himself with leftist ideas, but later, during the [[Pacific War]], he became a [[Chinilpa|pro-Japanese]] writer.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} He also joined pro-Japanese writers' organizations.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}} After the war, he reinvented his image abruptly. Besides the Japanese, he also distanced himself from the [[Domestic faction]] of the [[Workers' Party of North Korea|Workers' Party]],{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} though some scholars like {{Interlanguage link multi|Wada Haruki|ja|3=\u548c\u7530\u6625\u6a39}} explicitly include him in the faction.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=70}} From this position, he played an important role in opposing the [[Soviet Koreans faction]] during the late 1950s.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}}\n\n===Emigration===\nAfter the liberation of Korea, writers were faced with the task of establishing a [[national literature]]. Some, like {{Interlanguage link multi|Kim Namch'\u014fn|ko|3=\uae40\ub0a8\ucc9c}}, sought to gather a wide range of both moderate and progressive writers to write \"democratic national literature\".{{sfn|Ryu|2013|p=182}} A writers' association called the {{Interlanguage link multi|Headquarters for the Construction of Korean Literature|ko|3=\uc870\uc120\ubb38\ud559\uac74\uc124\ubcf8\ubd80}} ([[McCune\u2013Reischauer|MR]]: ''Chos\u014fn Munhak K\u014fns\u014fl Ponbu'') was founded in 1945 immediately after the liberation by Kim and others. Han, however, disagreed with this approach, accusing it of forgetting class questions.{{sfn|Ryu|2013|p=195}} Since the 1930s, Han had already had bad personal relations with these writers originally hailing from the south of Korea. The struggle for dominance in the North Korean literary bureaucracy made them worse.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=35}} In retaliation Han, together with other writers including Yi Kiy\u014fng, founded the [[Korean Proletarian Literature Alliance]] ([[McCune\u2013Reischauer|MR]]: ''Chos\u014fn P'\u016drollet'aria Munhak Tongmaeng'').{{sfn|Ryu|2013|p=195}} For Han's purposes his fellow writer Yi Kiy\u014fng, though respected, was not particularly interested in political matters and thus posed no threat to Han's own aspirations.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} The two organizations became merged to form {{Interlanguage link multi|Korean Writers' Alliance|ko|3=\uc870\uc120\ubb38\ud559\ub3d9\ub9f9}} ([[McCune\u2013Reischauer|MR]]: ''Chos\u014fn munhakka tongmaeng'') in late 1945.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=182}} Disapproving of this, Han moved to the north of the country, and was one of the first writers to do so.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|pp=181\u2013182}}\n\n===In North Korea===\nSoon after starting his career in North Korea, Han had become one of the earliest and most enthusiastic admirers of [[Kim Il-sung]],{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} with whom he had met in February 1946.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=37}} Han acted in his writing as a \"curator of the personality cult\" [[Personality cult of Kim Il-sung|of Kim Il-sung]]{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=148}} and was, in effect, the official [[hagiographer]] of Kim.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=43}} Indeed, the cult's beginnings can be traced as far back as 1946{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=171}} when Han coined the appellation \"our Sun\" to describe Kim.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=223}} Han was also the first to employ the phrase \"Sun of the Nation\" in referring to Kim.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=44}} Considered proteg\u00e9 of Kim,<ref name=\"Jospehson2009\">{{cite book|last=Josephson|first=Paul R.|title=Would Trotsky Wear a Bluetooth? : Technological Utopianism under Socialism, 1917\u20131989|location=Baltimore|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|year=2009|url=http://site.ebrary.com/lib/alltitles/docDetail.action?docID=10375804|via=ProQuest ebrary|page=153|isbn=978-0-8018-9841-9}}</ref> Han survived the purge of the Domestic faction.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} The [[August faction]] criticized Han for his close ties with Kim Il-sung.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=97}}\n\nWriters opposing Han, such as {{Interlanguage link multi|Yim Hwa|ko|3=\uc784\ud654}}, were purged because of their connections with South Korean communists. When the Domestic faction, including its leader [[Pak Hon-yong]], were purged,{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} Han attacked their associates in the literary circles from 1953 onwards.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=35}} Later, between 1955 and 1957, Han attacked the Soviet Koreans faction,{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} accusing them of \"factional, splitting activity\"{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=37}} and \"not allow[ing] the party and the people to demonstrate their good feeling and love toward their leader\".{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=44}} It is possible that Han influenced Kim Il-sung to wage his campaign against the Soviet Koreans' faction specifically on the literary front, culminating in Kim's famous \"''[[Juche]]'' speech\" of 1955: [[On Eliminating Dogmatism and Formalism and Establishing Juche in Ideological Work|''On Eliminating Dogmatism and Formalism and Establishing ''Juche'' in Ideological Work'']].{{sfn|Lankov|2007|pp=39\u201340}} The speech credits Han for uncovering{{sfn|Myers|2006|pp=94\u201395}} \"serious ideological errors on the literary front\"<ref name=\"marx_Onel\">{{Cite web | title = On eliminating dogmatism and formalism and establishing Juche in ideological work | author = Kim Il-sung | work = Marxists Internet Archive | orig-year = 28 December 1955 | date = 2008| accessdate = 2 July 2015 | url = https://www.marxists.org/archive/kim-il-sung/1955/12/28.htm | others = Transcription: Victor Barraza, HTML Markup: Salil Sen}}</ref> and can be considered an expression of public support for Han.{{sfn|Myers|2006|p=111}} In editions after Han's purge in 1962, his name is omitted or replaced with the expression \"prominent proletarian writers\".{{sfn|Myers|2015|pp=231\u2013232, 236}}\n\n[[File:1952-10 1952\u5e7410\u67082\u65e5\u4e9a\u6d32\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u533a\u57df\u548c\u5e73\u4f1a\u8bae\u7f8e\u56fd\u4ee3\u8868\u56e2\u957f\u4e0e\u671d\u9c9c\u4ee3\u8868\u97e9\u96ea\u91ce.png|thumb|Han Sorya meeting Americans in 1952. Han's best known work, ''[[Jackals (Han Sorya novel)|Jackals]]'', and his legacy is known for anti-Americanism.]]\nDuring his career, Han held multiple posts in the literature administration as well as politics in general. Since 1946, Han edited {{Interlanguage link multi|North Korean Federation of Literature and Arts|ko|3=\ubd81\uc870\uc120\ubb38\ud559\uc608\uc220\ucd1d\ub3d9\ub9f9}} (NKFLA) organ ''[[Munhwa chons\u014fn]]''{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}} ({{Langnf||Korean|\"The Cultural Front\"|links=no}}){{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=43}} and was the chairman of the organization since January 1948.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}} During the [[Korean War]], he was the chairman of the united [[Korean Federation of Literature and Arts]] (KFLA){{sfn|Myers|1994|p=75}} and a member in its Literature Organization.{{sfn|Wit|2015|p=43}} Since 1953, Han was the chairman of the [[Korean Writers' Union]].{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=86}} This position made him the most powerful cultural administrator of the country and he effectively ran the whole system of publishing literature and providing for the writers.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} Han also wrote for the ''[[Rodong Sinmun]]'' in the 1950s.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=51}}\n\nIn 1946, Han became a member of the [[1st Central Committee of the Workers' Party of North Korea|first Central Committee]] of the [[Workers' Party of North Korea]].{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=46}} He maintained the post in the party and its successor, the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]], until 1969.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=191}} Han became the [[Minister of education (North Korea)|minister of education]] in May 1956{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=58}} and retained his post as the chairman of the Writers' Union.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}} During his ministerial career, Han initiated a campaign to diminish the importance of Russian language teaching in North Korean colleges in the spring of 1956.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=59}} He also started to enlist [[proletarian writer|writers with a proletarian background]].{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=191}}\n\n====Purge====\nIn 1962, Han was accused of \"parochialism\" and \"bourgeois decadence\" by the NKFLA. He was consequentially expelled from the party and stripped of his offices.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=191}} His purge coincided with the election of the [[1962 North Korean parliamentary election|third]] [[Supreme People's Assembly]].<ref name=\"Pratt2007\">{{cite book|last=Pratt|first=Keith|title=Everlasting Flower: A History of Korea|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Gui8CdUfVoC&pg=PA270|date=2007|location=London|publisher=Reaktion Books|isbn=978-1-86189-450-2|page=270}}</ref> The following year, he was exiled to a village in [[Chagang Province]].{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=147}} Han was likely pardoned later, in 1969,{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} when his name reappear as a member of the party Central Committee. Han was never reassigned to any other post he had held. He was absent from the [[5th Congress of the Workers' Party of Korea]] in November 1970, leading [[B. R. Myers]] to conclude that it is likely \"though by no means certain, that Han died sometime between late 1969 and late 1970\",{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=150}} with some preference for the year 1970.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=1}} Han's gravestone at the [[Patriotic Martyrs' Cemetery]] in Pyongyang,<ref name=\"Prometheus\">{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224114520/http://www.prometheus.co.kr/articles/120/20060813/20060813190300.html|url=http://www.prometheus.co.kr/articles/120/20060813/20060813190300.html|url-status=dead|script-title=ko:\ubd81\ud55c\uc758 \uc5f4\uc0ac\ub989, \uadf8 \uc0c1\uc9d5\uacfc \ud3ed\ub825: \ud601\uba85\uc5f4\uc0ac\ub989\uacfc \uc560\uad6d\uc5f4\uc0ac\ub989|language=Korean|date=13 August 2006|access-date=7 July 2015|archive-date=24 December 2013 |publisher=Prometheus}}</ref> however, gives the date of his death as 6 April 1976.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Grave of Han Sol Ya (Han S\u014frya) | author = Moravius | work = Flickr | date = 9 February 2008 | accessdate = 5 October 2016 | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/kernbeisser/2469709564/}}</ref> Ultimately, the secrecy practiced by North Korea precludes any certain knowledge about \"when (or even if) Han died\".{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=6}}\n\nIn Han's wake, other cultural figures, like [[Ch'oe S\u016dngh\u016di]] and [[Sim Y\u014fng]], were purged also.<ref name=\"Pratt2007\"/> The regime faced a problem in Han's work being politically useful in nature but his name tarnished. His name began to be disconnected from his work, which was still widely disseminated. For the future, North Korean publishing authorities would employ a policy of publishing collective works of creative teams and withhold names of individual authors, a practice that was observed particularly in the 1970s and started to wane only in the 1980s.<ref name=\"Gabroussenko2013\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThough Han Sorya's name has been since been all but forgotten in official North Korean accounts, his influence on contemporary North Korean literature has been significant.<ref name=Yearn1995>{{cite journal|title=World literature in review: Korea|last=Choi|first=Yearn Hong|journal=World Literature Today|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/book-reviews/9512211137/world-literature-review-korea|date=1995|volume=69|issue=1}}</ref>\n\nLiterately, Han's style of writing has been described as experimental in his employment of various narrative structures.<ref name=\"Lee2007\"/> [[Andrei Lankov]] considers Han mediocre as a writer{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} and assess his rivals Kim Namch'\u014fn and {{Interlanguage link multi|Yi T'ae-jun|ko|3=\uc774\ud0dc\uc900}} \"marginally more gifted\", however considering North Korean literature of the period \"boring and highly politicized propaganda\" across the board.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=35}} Lankov describes Han \"unscrupulous\" as an opportunist and careerist.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} The literary style and ideologies of Han and some of his adversaries are very similar, and Han's prevailing is due to factional strife. Some aspects of the struggles are baseless, too, as some works by Han include rather sympathetic depictions of Japanese soldiers, while it was many of his rivals who were purged because of their \"pro-Japanese\" tendencies. Thus, Lankov concludes, the struggle within the literary establishment can be attributed to conflicting personal ambitions more than anything else.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=35}}\n\nYearn Hong Choi assess that \"Han is not a typical North Korean writer\" but an extremely political one in his attempt at pleasing Kim Il-sung.<ref name=Yearn1995/> B. R. Myers contrasts Han's legacy with that of North Korean poet [[Cho Ki-chon]]. While in Han's works Kim Il-sung embodies traditional Korean virtues of innocence and naivety having \"mastered Marxism\u2013Leninism with his heart, not his brain\",{{sfn|Myers|2011|p=36}} in Cho's he exemplifies particular traits of the rather early cult of personality built upon Soviet [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] and bloc conformity.{{sfn|Myers|2015|p=28, 40n36}} The style of Han based on [[Korean ethnic nationalism]] ultimately established itself as the standard of propaganda over Cho's.{{sfn|Myers|2011|p=36}} According to Myers, Han is not a writer of fiction in the official literary doctrine of [[socialist realism]] at all, but \"his own man, not a socialist realist\". Yearn Hong Choi disagrees, and points to Han's one-time praise of the Soviets and Kim Il-sung as well as his employment of propaganda in praise of a \"utopian\" North Korea as proof of him being a socialist realist. According to Yearn, Myers simply has a different idea of what socialist realism is from North Korean writers.<ref name=Yearn1995/>\n\nAn exception to Han's forgotten legacy in North Korea exists. The multi-part film ''[[Nation and Destiny]]'' not only features him, but allows Han to be a hero of the film. This was the first time that an anti-establishment figure has been the hero on North Korean screen.<ref name=\"Seoul2002\">{{cite book|title=North Korea Handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JIlh9nNeadMC&pg=PA469|year=2002|publisher=Yonhap News Agency|isbn=978-0-7656-3523-5|page=469}}</ref> In [[South Korea]], Han's works were banned by the [[Ministry of Culture and Information (South Korea)|Ministry of Culture and Information]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Wells|first=Kenneth M.|date=1995|editor=University of Hawaii at Manoa|title=South Korea's Minjung Movement : The Culture and Politics of Dissidence|location=Honolulu|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|via=ProQuest ebrary|url=http://site.ebrary.com/lib/alltitles/docDetail.action?docID=5004871|isbn=978-0-8248-6439-2|page=195}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n''[[History (Han Sorya novel)|History]]'' ([[McCune\u2013Reischauer|MR]]: ''Ry\u014fksa'') was the first long North Korean work to deal with Kim Il-sung during the [[Anti-Japanese struggle]].<ref>{{cite journal |ref=harv |last=Epstein |first=Stephen |date=January 2002 |title=On Reading North Korean Short Stories on the Cusp of the New Millennium |url=http://actakoreana.org/events/download_issue.php?ctl=acta_back_issue&No=51&num=1#.pdf|journal=Acta Koreana|volume=5|issue=1|page=37}}</ref> [[Yan'an faction]] member [[Yi P'il-gyu]] expressed harsh criticism of ''History'',{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=79}} aimed at Han's close relationship with Kim Il-sung: \"Han S\u014fl-ya&nbsp;\u2014 he should be killed. He deserves it even only for just one book&nbsp;\u2014 ''History''. He is a very bad and harmful man; he is Kim Il Song's sycophant, a bootlicker\".{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=83}}\n\n===''Jackals''===\n{{quote box| align = right| width = 25em|quote=All in all, there were a lot of poor people living around here. The missionaries had purchased the area for twenty w\u014fn upon arriving in Korea twenty years ago. Since then they had turned it into a scenic summer retreat, on which Reverend Yi and one or two newly-rich families had recently erected neat brick houses. But far from benefiting from this, those who had always lived there in their rock huts just became more inextricably enmired in poverty as time went on.|source=''[[Jackals (Han Sorya novel)|Jackals]]''<ref>Translation in {{harvnb|Myers|1994|pp=158\u2013159}}</ref>| salign = right}}\n''[[Jackals (Han Sorya novel)|Jackals]]'',{{efn|The Korean name of the novella is {{Lang|ko|\uc2b9\ub0e5\uc774}} (''S\u016dngnyangi''), which literally means [[dhole]]s. In English, the work is often known as ''Jackals'' following Myers' translation.<ref name=\"sino\"/> Sometimes ''Wolves'' is used,{{sfn|David-West|2012|p=1}} whereas North Korean sources use ''Wolf''.<ref name=\"sino\"/><ref name=\"kcna_Dram\"/>}} is a 1951 novella by Han, noted for its [[anti-American]] and [[anti-Christian]] tendencies.<ref name=\"sino\">{{Cite web | title = Collapsist Narratives and State Strength: Reading The Interview through Han Sorya's Jackals | last = Fields | first = David | work = Sino-NK | date = 18 February 2015 | access-date=26 June 2015 | url = http://sinonk.com/2015/02/18/collapsist-narratives-and-state-strength-reading-the-interview-through-han-soryas-jackals/ }}</ref>{{sfn|Myers|2011|p=152}}\n''Jackals'' tells the story of a Korean boy murdered by American missionaries with an injection.{{sfn|Myers|2011|p=40}} In North Korea, the story is taken to be based on fact,{{sfn|Myers|2011|p=138}} and B. R. Myers assesses that it is possible that it gave impetus to [[allegations of biological warfare in the Korean War]] by North Korea.{{sfn|Myers|2011|p=40}} Called \"the country's most enduring work of fiction\",<ref name=\"nyti_TheO\">{{Cite web | title = The Obsessions of Kim Jong Il | last = Myers |first = Brian Reynolds | work = The New York Times | date = 19 May 2003 | accessdate = 2 July 2015 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2003/05/19/opinion/the-obsessions-of-kim-jong-il.html}}</ref> it is still influential in North Korea where the word \"jackals\" has become a synonym for \"Americans\", and papers like ''Rodong Sinmun'' regularly invoke the language of the novella.<ref name=\"sino\"/>\n\nThe emotional story is inspired by [[Maxim Gorky]]'s sentimental novel ''[[The Mother (Gorky novel)|Mother]]'',{{sfn|David-West|2012|p=2}} which is considered the first socialist realist novel,{{sfn|Wit|2015|p=110}} and a story that Han was familiar with.{{sfn|David-West|2012|p=2}} Myers traces the story's foundation back to anti-Christian stories in rural [[colonial Korea]] as well as in [[fascist Japan]].{{sfn|Myers|2011|p=152}} The metaphor of the villain as a beast, too, is more readily associated with wartime [[Japanese propaganda]] than socialist realism.{{sfn|Myers|1994|pp=95\u201396}} It had, however, featured in the works of early Soviet writers as whose work Han knew, as well as in textual genres not bound by the official socialist realist dogma, such as journalism.{{sfn|David-West|2012|pp=3\u20134}}\n\n''Jackals'' was republished in ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Chos\u014fn munhak|ko|3=\uc870\uc120\ubb38\ud559}}'', ''[[Ch'\u014fngny\u014fn munhak]]'' and ''[[Chollima (magazine)|Chollima]]'' in August 2003, one year after the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]] designated North Korea as part of the \"[[Axis of evil]]\".{{sfn|David-West|2012|p=1}} After the [[Sony Pictures Entertainment hack]] of 2014, [[North Korean media]] employed similar rhetoric against [[Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]]. One article compared Kerry with a jackal no fewer than eleven times.<ref name=\"sino\"/> ''Jackals'' was adapted on stage and performed in Pyongyang in 2015.<ref name=\"kcna_Dram\">{{Cite web | title = Drama 'Wolf' Re-created in DPRK | agency = KCNA | date = 31 August 2015 | accessdate = 21 August 2016 | url = http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2015/201508/news31/20150831-20ee.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191124075159/http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2015/201508/news31/20150831-20ee.html | archive-date = 24 November 2019 | url-status = dead }}</ref> The novel remains one of the very few North Korean works of fiction that have been translated into English.<ref name=\"japa_Writ\">{{Cite web| title = Writers From the Other Asia: the two Koreas| publisher = The Asia-Pacific Journal| last = Feffer |first = John| work = JapanFocus| date = 6 September 2006|access-date=23 June 2015| url = http://www.japanfocus.org/-John-Feffer/2215/article.html|page=4}}</ref>\n\n===List of works===\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|trans-title=Transition Period|title=Kwadogi|date=1929}}<ref name=\"Lee2003\">{{cite book|last=Lee|first=Peter H.|title=A History of Korean Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pfb2QHJtw54C&pg=PA398|date=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-44086-8|page=398}}</ref> Short story.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|trans-title=Wrestling Match|title=Ssir\u016dm|date=1929}}<ref name=\"Lee2003\"/> Short story.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|trans-title=Erosion Work|date=1932|title=Sabang Kongsa}}<ref name=\"Lee2003\"/>\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|trans-title=Dusk|title=Hwanghon|date=1936}}<ref name=\"Lee2003\"/> Novel.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|trans-title=Pagoda|title=T'ap|date=1940}} Autobiographical novel.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}}{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=35}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Ch'oso-es\u014f|trans-title=At a Guard Post|date=1950}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|trans-title=Path of Blood|title=Hy\u014flla|date=1946}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=37}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Mining Settlement|date=1946}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|trans-title=The Hat|date=1946|title=Moja}}{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=43}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Growing Village|date=1949}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Brother and Sister|date=1949}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|editor=Brian Myers|chapter=Jackals|title=Han S\u014frya and North Korean Literature: The Failure of Socialist Realism in DPRK|year=1994|orig-year=1951|publisher=East Asia Program, Cornell University|location=Ithca|isbn=978-0-939657-84-1|pages=157\u2013188}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|trans-title=The Taedong River|date=1955|title=Taedonggang}} Trilogy.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=33}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Man'gy\u014fngdae|date=1955}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Ry\u014fksa|trans-title=History|date=1958}} [[People's Prize]] (1958).{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=191}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Love|date=1960}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=191}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Emulate the Leader|date=1960}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=191}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|North Korea|Biography}}\n* [[Cho Ki-chon]]\n* [[Korean literature]]\n* [[North Korean literature]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Works cited===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Armstrong|first=Charles K.|title=The North Korean Revolution, 1945\u20131950|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eUf-_XACg3UC|date=15 April 2013|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0-8014-6879-5}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=David-West|first=Alzo|title=Savage Nature and Noble Spirit in Han S\u014frya's Wolves : A North Korean Morality Tale|journal=Transnational Literature|volume=4|number=2|date=May 2012|url=http://dspace.flinders.edu.au/jspui/bitstream/2328/25882/1/Savage_Nature.pdf|pages=1\u201318}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Lankov|first=Andrei|date=2007|title=Crisis in North Korea: The Failure of De-Stalinization, 1956|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cRDhhzwB2hYC|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|isbn=978-0-8248-3207-0}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Myers|first=B. R.|title=Han S\u014frya and North Korean Literature: The Failure of Socialist Realism in DPRK|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1yhwAAAAMAAJ|date=1994|location=Ithca|publisher=East Asia Program, Cornell University|isbn=978-0-939657-84-1}}\n* {{cite journal|author-mask=1|ref=harv|last=Myers|first=Brian|date=2006|title=The Watershead that Wasn't: Re-evalutaing Kim Il Sung's 'Juche Speech' of 1955 |url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/19756057/watershed-that-wasnt-re-evaluating-kim-il-sungs-juche-speech-1955|journal=Acta Koreana|volume=9|issue=1}}\n* {{cite book|author-mask=1|last=Myers|first=B. R.|title=The Cleanest Race: How North Koreans See Themselves and Why It Matters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KWQEAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT36|year=2011|publisher=Melville House|location=New York|isbn=978-1-935554-97-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author-mask=1|last=Myers|first=B. R.|title=North Korea's Juche Myth|year=2015|location=Busan|publisher=Sthele Press|isbn=978-1-5087-9993-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Ryu|first=Youngju|date=June 2013|editor-last1=Hanscom|editor-first1=Christopher P.|editor-last2=Lew|editor-first2=Walter K.|editor-last3=Ryu|editor-first3=Youngju|chapter=10. Kim Namch'\u014fn|pages=181\u2013196|title=Korean Classics Library : Historical Materials : Imperatives of Culture : Selected Essays on Korean History, Literature, and Society from the Japanese Colonial Era|location=Honolulu|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|via=ProQuest ebrary|access-date=23 June 2015|url=http://site.ebrary.com/lib/alltitles/docDetail.action?docID=10745589|isbn=978-0-8248-3904-8}}\n* {{cite thesis|ref=harv|last=Wit|first=Jer\u00f4me de|title=Writing under wartime conditions : North and South Korean writers during the Korean war (1950\u20131953)|type=Doctoral thesis|url=https://openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/handle/1887/31445/Writing%20under%20Wartime%20Conditions%20Jerome%20de%20WitNIEUW.pdf?sequence=3|date=15 January 2015|publisher=Leiden University}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite thesis|last=Kim|first=Ellie Sue|title=Rituals of Decolonization: The Role of Inner-Migrant Intellectuals in North Korea, 1948\u20131967|type=Doctoral thesis|publisher=University of California Los Angeles|date=2014|url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/04176993#page-1|oclc=904783158}}\n* {{cite book|editor=Kw\u014fn Y\u014fgngmin|trans-title=Studies of Writers Who Went North|title=W\u014flbuk munin y\u014fn'gu|location=Seoul|publisher=Munhak sasangsa|year=1989|oclc=22847934}}\n* {{cite book|author=Se-p'yong Yun|date=30 November 1960|title=Han Sol-ya and His Literature: North Korea|location=Washington D.C., U.S.|publisher=Joint Publications Research Service|url=http://handle.dtic.mil/100.2/ADA376834#.pdf|oclc=227922016}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Flickr image inline link|kernbeisser/2469709564/|Grave of Han Sorya}}\n* [http://encykorea.aks.ac.kr/Contents/Index?contents_id=E0061717 Han Sorya] at the ''[[Encyclopedia of Korean Culture]]'' {{in lang|ko}}\n* [http://www.cybernk.net/infoText/InfoHumanDetail.aspx?mc=EJ0702&hid=EH010300012354&rightType=3&direct=1 Han Sorya] at ''[[North Korean Human Geography]]'' {{in lang|ko}}\n* {{YouTube|pjJeuAIMebc|\"American Wolf\" dance performance loosely based on ''Jackals''}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Han, Sorya}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:Education ministers]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of North Korea]]\n[[Category:North Korean novelists]]\n[[Category:People from Hamhung]]\n[[Category:Socialist realism writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century novelists]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n", "text_old": "{{Good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Korean name|Han}}\n{{Infobox writer  <!--For more information, see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]].-->\n| name = Han Sorya\n| honorific_prefix = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = Han S\u014frya portrait.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = Portrait of Han Sorya\n| caption = \n| pseudonym = \n| birth_name = Han Py\u014fngdo\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1900|08|03|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Hamhung]], [[Korean Empire]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1976|04|06|1900|08|03}}\n| death_place = [[Pyongyang]], [[North Korea|Democratic People's Republic of Korea]]\n| resting_place = [[Patriotic Martyrs' Cemetery]]\n| occupation = novelist, short story writer, literary administrator, politician\n| language = Korean\n| nationality = Korean\n| citizenship = North Korean\n| education = \n| alma_mater = [[Nippon University]]\n| period = 20th century\n| genre =         <!-- or: | genres =      -->\n| subject =       <!-- or: | subjects =    -->\n| movement = [[Proletarian literature]]<ref name=\"Lee2007\">{{cite book|author=Namhee Lee|title=The Making of Minjung: Democracy and the Politics of Representation in South Korea|url=https://archive.org/details/makingofminjungd00leen_0|url-access=registration|year=2007|location=Ithaca|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0-8014-4566-3|page=[https://archive.org/details/makingofminjungd00leen_0/page/270 270]}}</ref>\n| notableworks = ''[[Jackals (Han Sorya novel)|Jackals]]'', ''[[History (Han Sorya novel)|History]]'' <!-- or: | notablework = -->\n| spouse =        <!-- or: | spouses =     -->\n| partner =       <!-- or: | partners =    -->\n| children = \n| relatives = \n| awards = [[Order of the National Flag]] (second class, 1951),{{sfn|Wit|2015|p=44}} [[People's Prize]] (''History'', 1958), title of [[People's Artist]] (1958){{sfn|Myers|1994|p=191}}\n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| years_active = \n| module =\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| title          =\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| context        =north\n| hangul         ={{linktext|\ud55c|\uc124|\uc57c}}\n| hanja          ={{linktext|\u97d3|\u96ea|\u91ce}}<ref>{{cite journal|publisher=\ud55c\uad6d\ubb38\ud559\uc774\ub860\uacfc \ube44\ud3c9 \uc81c16\uc9d1|date=September 2002|pages=342\u2013368|script-title=ko:\ud55c\uc77c \uc804\ud5a5\uc18c\uc124\uc758 \ubb38\ud559\uc0ac\uc801 \uc131\uaca9-\ud55c\uc124\uc57c(\u97d3\u96ea\u91ce)\uc640 \ub098\uce74\ub178 \uc2dc\uac8c\ud558\ub8e8(\u4e2d\u91ce\u91cd\u6cbb)\ub97c \uc911\uc2ec\uc73c\ub85c The Characteristics of the Novel of Conversion in Korea and Japan|author=\ud669\uce58\ubcf5|url=http://www.dbpia.co.kr/Journal/ArticleDetail/425374|access-date=27 June 2015}}</ref>\n| rr             =Han Seol-ya\n| mr             =Han S\u014frya\n| koreanipa      =\n| hangulborn     = {{linktext|\ud55c|\ubcd1|\ub3c4}}\n| hanjaborn      = {{linktext|\u97d3|\u79c9|\u9053}}\n| rrborn         = Han Byeongdo\n| mrborn         =Han Py\u014fngdo\n| koreanipaborn  =\n| text           =\n| child=yes\n}}\n| website = \n| portaldisp = on<!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc; or omit -->\n| ethnicity = \n}}\n\n'''Han Sorya''' ({{lang-ko|\ud55c\uc124\uc57c}}, born '''Han Py\u014fngdo''';{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}} 3 August 1900 \u2013 6 April 1976) was a Korean writer, literary administrator and politician who spent much of his career in [[North Korea]]. Regarded as one of the most important fiction writers in North Korean history, Han also ran the entire North Korean literary scene as the head of the [[Korean Writers' Union]] and [[Minister of education (North Korea)|minister of education]].\n\nDuring his career, Han survived a number of purges that were caused by [[Workers' Party of North Korea#Factionalism|factional strife]] within the [[Workers' Party of North Korea]], to become a member of  the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea]]. Han, motivated by personal grievances against his rival writers, sometimes acted as the force behind the purges within the cultural establishment as well. Han himself was purged in 1962. In his works, Han offered some of the earliest known contributions to the [[cult of personality of Kim Il-sung]]. His influence is felt in North Korea even today, though his name has been forgotten from official histories. Han's best-known work, the [[anti-American]] novella ''[[Jackals (Han Sorya novel)|Jackals]]'', however, has been invoked in the 2000s.\n\n==Early life==\nHan was born on 3 August 1900 in [[Hamhung]], in the north of [[Korea under Japanese rule|Korea]]. His father was a county magistrate. He graduated from middle school in 1919 and attended [[Nippon University]] in Tokyo from 1921 to 1924,{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}} studying [[sociology]].{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=20}} He emigrated to [[Manchuria]] in 1925 but returned to [[Seoul]] in the south in 1927.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}} In 1944, he returned to his native Hamhung. After the [[liberation of Korea]] he settled in [[Pyongyang]].{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}}\n\n==Career==\nHan was one of the most prominent fiction writers in the history of [[North Korean literature]].<ref name=\"Yearn1995\"/> During his career, Han earned the official title of \"the greatest writer of modern Korean literature\", which he shared with [[Yi Kiy\u014fng]], and was called a \"living classic\".{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} Han's career was at its height from 1955 to 1957.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} Han, along with [[Kim Tu-bong]], shaped North Korea's cultural policies.<ref>{{cite book|last=Howard|first=Keith|chapter=Music across the DMZ|editor-first1=John Morgan|editor-last1=O'Connell|editor-first2=Salwa El-Shawan|editor-last2=Castelo-Branco|title=Music and Conflict|location=Champaign|publisher=University of Illinois Press|date=September 2010|via=ProQuest ebrary|url=http://site.ebrary.com/lib/alltitles/docDetail.action?docID=10603913|page=82|isbn=978-0-252-09025-7}}</ref>\n\n===In pre-liberation Korea===\nBefore the liberation of Korea, Han was an insignificant author. His subsequent fame would only be due to his association with the {{Interlanguage link multi|Korean Artist Proletarian Federation|ko|3=\uc870\uc120\ud504\ub864\ub808\ud0c0\ub9ac\uc544\uc608\uc220\uac00\ub3d9\ub9f9}} (KAPF),<ref name=\"Gabroussenko2013\">{{Cite web | title = Benoit Symposium: Writers in the DPRK: The Invisible Stars | last = Gabroussenko|first=Tatiana  | work = Sino-NK | date =  27 September 2013 | accessdate = 21 August 2016 | url = http://sinonk.com/2013/09/27/writers-in-the-dprk-the-invisible-stars/}}</ref> which he joined in [[Seoul]] in 1927. The organization had been founded in 1925 during his emigration in Manchuria,{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}} and after the liberation it would have been the only left-leaning Korean literary organization. For this reason, [[Kim Il-sung]] would promote writers like Han who had belonged to it and exaggerated their achievements.<ref name=\"Gabroussenko2013\"/>\n\nDuring the early 1930s, Han did briefly associate himself with leftist ideas, but later, during the [[Pacific War]], he became a [[Chinilpa|pro-Japanese]] writer.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} He also joined pro-Japanese writers' organizations.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}} After the war, he reinvented his image abruptly. Besides the Japanese, he also distanced himself from the [[Domestic faction]] of the [[Workers' Party of North Korea|Workers' Party]],{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} though some scholars like {{Interlanguage link multi|Wada Haruki|ja|3=\u548c\u7530\u6625\u6a39}} explicitly include him in the faction.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=70}} From this position, he played an important role in opposing the [[Soviet Koreans faction]] during the late 1950s.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}}\n\n===Emigration===\nAfter the liberation of Korea, writers were faced with the task of establishing a [[national literature]]. Some, like {{Interlanguage link multi|Kim Namch'\u014fn|ko|3=\uae40\ub0a8\ucc9c}}, sought to gather a wide range of both moderate and progressive writers to write \"democratic national literature\".{{sfn|Ryu|2013|p=182}} A writers' association called the {{Interlanguage link multi|Headquarters for the Construction of Korean Literature|ko|3=\uc870\uc120\ubb38\ud559\uac74\uc124\ubcf8\ubd80}} ([[McCune\u2013Reischauer|MR]]: ''Chos\u014fn Munhak K\u014fns\u014fl Ponbu'') was founded in 1945 immediately after the liberation by Kim and others. Han, however, disagreed with this approach, accusing it of forgetting class questions.{{sfn|Ryu|2013|p=195}} Since the 1930s, Han had already had bad personal relations with these writers originally hailing from the south of Korea. The struggle for dominance in the North Korean literary bureaucracy made them worse.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=35}} In retaliation Han, together with other writers including Yi Kiy\u014fng, founded the [[Korean Proletarian Literature Alliance]] ([[McCune\u2013Reischauer|MR]]: ''Chos\u014fn P'\u016drollet'aria Munhak Tongmaeng'').{{sfn|Ryu|2013|p=195}} For Han's purposes his fellow writer Yi Kiy\u014fng, though respected, was not particularly interested in political matters and thus posed no threat to Han's own aspirations.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} The two organizations became merged to form {{Interlanguage link multi|Korean Writers' Alliance|ko|3=\uc870\uc120\ubb38\ud559\ub3d9\ub9f9}} ([[McCune\u2013Reischauer|MR]]: ''Chos\u014fn munhakka tongmaeng'') in late 1945.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=182}} Disapproving of this, Han moved to the north of the country, and was one of the first writers to do so.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|pp=181\u2013182}}\n\n===In North Korea===\nSoon after starting his career in North Korea, Han had become one of the earliest and most enthusiastic admirers of [[Kim Il-sung]],{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} with whom he had met in February 1946.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=37}} Han acted in his writing as a \"curator of the personality cult\" [[Personality cult of Kim Il-sung|of Kim Il-sung]]{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=148}} and was, in effect, the official [[hagiographer]] of Kim.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=43}} Indeed, the cult's beginnings can be traced as far back as 1946{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=171}} when Han coined the appellation \"our Sun\" to describe Kim.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=223}} Han was also the first to employ the phrase \"Sun of the Nation\" in referring to Kim.{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=44}} Considered proteg\u00e9 of Kim,<ref name=\"Jospehson2009\">{{cite book|last=Josephson|first=Paul R.|title=Would Trotsky Wear a Bluetooth? : Technological Utopianism under Socialism, 1917\u20131989|location=Baltimore|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|year=2009|url=http://site.ebrary.com/lib/alltitles/docDetail.action?docID=10375804|via=ProQuest ebrary|page=153|isbn=978-0-8018-9841-9}}</ref> Han survived the purge of the Domestic faction.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} The [[August faction]] criticized Han for his close ties with Kim Il-sung.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=97}}\n\nWriters opposing Han, such as {{Interlanguage link multi|Yim Hwa|ko|3=\uc784\ud654}}, were purged because of their connections with South Korean communists. When the Domestic faction, including its leader [[Pak Hon-yong]], were purged,{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} Han attacked their associates in the literary circles from 1953 onwards.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=35}} Later, between 1955 and 1957, Han attacked the Soviet Koreans faction,{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} accusing them of \"factional, splitting activity\"{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=37}} and \"not allow[ing] the party and the people to demonstrate their good feeling and love toward their leader\".{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=44}} It is possible that Han influenced Kim Il-sung to wage his campaign against the Soviet Koreans' faction specifically on the literary front, culminating in Kim's famous \"''[[Juche]]'' speech\" of 1955: [[On Eliminating Dogmatism and Formalism and Establishing Juche in Ideological Work|''On Eliminating Dogmatism and Formalism and Establishing ''Juche'' in Ideological Work'']].{{sfn|Lankov|2007|pp=39\u201340}} The speech credits Han for uncovering{{sfn|Myers|2006|pp=94\u201395}} \"serious ideological errors on the literary front\"<ref name=\"marx_Onel\">{{Cite web | title = On eliminating dogmatism and formalism and establishing Juche in ideological work | author = Kim Il-sung | work = Marxists Internet Archive | orig-year = 28 December 1955 | date = 2008| accessdate = 2 July 2015 | url = https://www.marxists.org/archive/kim-il-sung/1955/12/28.htm | others = Transcription: Victor Barraza, HTML Markup: Salil Sen}}</ref> and can be considered an expression of public support for Han.{{sfn|Myers|2006|p=111}} In editions after Han's purge in 1962, his name is omitted or replaced with the expression \"prominent proletarian writers\".{{sfn|Myers|2015|pp=231\u2013232, 236}}\n\n[[File:1952-10 1952\u5e7410\u67082\u65e5\u4e9a\u6d32\u592a\u5e73\u6d0b\u533a\u57df\u548c\u5e73\u4f1a\u8bae\u7f8e\u56fd\u4ee3\u8868\u56e2\u957f\u4e0e\u671d\u9c9c\u4ee3\u8868\u97e9\u96ea\u91ce.png|thumb|Han Sorya meeting Americans in 1952. Han's best known work, ''[[Jackals (Han Sorya novel)|Jackals]]'', and his legacy is known for anti-Americanism.]]\nDuring his career, Han held multiple posts in the literature administration as well as politics in general. Since 1946, Han edited {{Interlanguage link multi|North Korean Federation of Literature and Arts|ko|3=\ubd81\uc870\uc120\ubb38\ud559\uc608\uc220\ucd1d\ub3d9\ub9f9}} (NKFLA) organ ''[[Munhwa chons\u014fn]]''{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}} ({{Langnf||Korean|\"The Cultural Front\"|links=no}}){{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=43}} and was the chairman of the organization since January 1948.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}} During the [[Korean War]], he was the chairman of the united [[Korean Federation of Literature and Arts]] (KFLA){{sfn|Myers|1994|p=75}} and a member in its Literature Organization.{{sfn|Wit|2015|p=43}} Since 1953, Han was the chairman of the [[Korean Writers' Union]].{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=86}} This position made him the most powerful cultural administrator of the country and he effectively ran the whole system of publishing literature and providing for the writers.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} Han also wrote for the ''[[Rodong Sinmun]]'' in the 1950s.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=51}}\n\nIn 1946, Han became a member of the [[1st Central Committee of the Workers' Party of North Korea|first Central Committee]] of the [[Workers' Party of North Korea]].{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=46}} He maintained the post in the party and its successor, the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]], until 1969.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=191}} Han became the [[Minister of education (North Korea)|minister of education]] in May 1956{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=58}} and retained his post as the chairman of the Writers' Union.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}} During his ministerial career, Han initiated a campaign to diminish the importance of Russian language teaching in North Korean colleges in the spring of 1956.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=59}} He also started to enlist [[proletarian writer|writers with a proletarian background]].{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=191}}\n\n====Purge====\nIn 1962, Han was accused of \"parochialism\" and \"bourgeois decadence\" by the NKFLA. He was consequentially expelled from the party and stripped of his offices.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=191}} His purge coincided with the election of the [[1962 North Korean parliamentary election|third]] [[Supreme People's Assembly]].<ref name=\"Pratt2007\">{{cite book|last=Pratt|first=Keith|title=Everlasting Flower: A History of Korea|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Gui8CdUfVoC&pg=PA270|date=2007|location=London|publisher=Reaktion Books|isbn=978-1-86189-450-2|page=270}}</ref> The following year, he was exiled to a village in [[Chagang Province]].{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=147}} Han was likely pardoned later, in 1969,{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} when his name reappear as a member of the party Central Committee. Han was never reassigned to any other post he had held. He was absent from the [[5th Congress of the Workers' Party of Korea]] in November 1970, leading [[B. R. Myers]] to conclude that it is likely \"though by no means certain, that Han died sometime between late 1969 and late 1970\",{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=150}} with some preference for the year 1970.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=1}} Han's gravestone at the [[Patriotic Martyrs' Cemetery]] in Pyongyang,<ref name=\"Prometheus\">{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224114520/http://www.prometheus.co.kr/articles/120/20060813/20060813190300.html|url=http://www.prometheus.co.kr/articles/120/20060813/20060813190300.html|url-status=dead|script-title=ko:\ubd81\ud55c\uc758 \uc5f4\uc0ac\ub989, \uadf8 \uc0c1\uc9d5\uacfc \ud3ed\ub825: \ud601\uba85\uc5f4\uc0ac\ub989\uacfc \uc560\uad6d\uc5f4\uc0ac\ub989|language=Korean|date=13 August 2006|access-date=7 July 2015|archive-date=24 December 2013 |publisher=Prometheus}}</ref> however, gives the date of his death as 6 April 1976.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Grave of Han Sol Ya (Han S\u014frya) | author = Moravius | work = Flickr | date = 9 February 2008 | accessdate = 5 October 2016 | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/kernbeisser/2469709564/}}</ref> Ultimately, the secrecy practiced by North Korea precludes any certain knowledge about \"when (or even if) Han died\".{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=6}}\n\nIn Han's wake, other cultural figures, like [[Ch'oe S\u016dngh\u016di]] and [[Sim Y\u014fng]], were purged also.<ref name=\"Pratt2007\"/> The regime faced a problem in Han's work being politically useful in nature but his name tarnished. His name began to be disconnected from his work, which was still widely disseminated. For the future, North Korean publishing authorities would employ a policy of publishing collective works of creative teams and withhold names of individual authors, a practice that was observed particularly in the 1970s and started to wane only in the 1980s.<ref name=\"Gabroussenko2013\"/>\n\n==Legacy==\nThough Han Sorya's name has been since been all but forgotten in official North Korean accounts, his influence on contemporary North Korean literature has been significant.<ref name=Yearn1995>{{cite journal|title=World literature in review: Korea|last=Choi|first=Yearn Hong|journal=World Literature Today|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/book-reviews/9512211137/world-literature-review-korea|date=1995|volume=69|issue=1}}</ref>\n\nLiterately, Han's style of writing has been described as experimental in his employment of various narrative structures.<ref name=\"Lee2007\"/> [[Andrei Lankov]] considers Han mediocre as a writer{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} and assess his rivals Kim Namch'\u014fn and {{Interlanguage link multi|Yi T'ae-jun|ko|3=\uc774\ud0dc\uc900}} \"marginally more gifted\", however considering North Korean literature of the period \"boring and highly politicized propaganda\" across the board.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=35}} Lankov describes Han \"unscrupulous\" as an opportunist and careerist.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=34}} The literary style and ideologies of Han and some of his adversaries are very similar, and Han's prevailing is due to factional strife. Some aspects of the struggles are baseless, too, as some works by Han include rather sympathetic depictions of Japanese soldiers, while it was many of his rivals who were purged because of their \"pro-Japanese\" tendencies. Thus, Lankov concludes, the struggle within the literary establishment can be attributed to conflicting personal ambitions more than anything else.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=35}}\n\nYearn Hong Choi assess that \"Han is not a typical North Korean writer\" but an extremely political one in his attempt at pleasing Kim Il-sung.<ref name=Yearn1995/> B. R. Myers contrasts Han's legacy with that of North Korean poet [[Cho Ki-chon]]. While in Han's works Kim Il-sung embodies traditional Korean virtues of innocence and naivety having \"mastered Marxism\u2013Leninism with his heart, not his brain\",{{sfn|Myers|2011|p=36}} in Cho's he exemplifies particular traits of the rather early cult of personality built upon Soviet [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] and bloc conformity.{{sfn|Myers|2015|p=28, 40n36}} The style of Han based on [[Korean ethnic nationalism]] ultimately established itself as the standard of propaganda over Cho's.{{sfn|Myers|2011|p=36}} According to Myers, Han is not a writer of fiction in the official literary doctrine of [[socialist realism]] at all, but \"his own man, not a socialist realist\". Yearn Hong Choi disagrees, and points to Han's one-time praise of the Soviets and Kim Il-sung as well as his employment of propaganda in praise of a \"utopian\" North Korea as proof of him being a socialist realist. According to Yearn, Myers simply has a different idea of what socialist realism is from North Korean writers.<ref name=Yearn1995/>\n\nAn exception to Han's forgotten legacy in North Korea exists. The multi-part film ''[[Nation and Destiny]]'' not only features him, but allows Han to be a hero of the film. This was the first time that an anti-establishment figure has been the hero on North Korean screen.<ref name=\"Seoul2002\">{{cite book|title=North Korea Handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JIlh9nNeadMC&pg=PA469|year=2002|publisher=Yonhap News Agency|isbn=978-0-7656-3523-5|page=469}}</ref> In [[South Korea]], Han's works were banned by the [[Ministry of Culture and Information (South Korea)|Ministry of Culture and Information]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Wells|first=Kenneth M.|date=1995|editor=University of Hawaii at Manoa|title=South Korea's Minjung Movement : The Culture and Politics of Dissidence|location=Honolulu|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|via=ProQuest ebrary|url=http://site.ebrary.com/lib/alltitles/docDetail.action?docID=5004871|isbn=978-0-8248-6439-2|page=195}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n''[[History (Han Sorya novel)|History]]'' ([[McCune\u2013Reischauer|MR]]: ''Ry\u014fksa'') was the first long North Korean work to deal with Kim Il-sung during the [[Anti-Japanese struggle]].<ref>{{cite journal |ref=harv |last=Epstein |first=Stephen |date=January 2002 |title=On Reading North Korean Short Stories on the Cusp of the New Millennium |url=http://actakoreana.org/events/download_issue.php?ctl=acta_back_issue&No=51&num=1#.pdf|journal=Acta Koreana|volume=5|issue=1|page=37}}</ref> [[Yan'an faction]] member [[Yi P'il-gyu]] expressed harsh criticism of ''History'',{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=79}} aimed at Han's close relationship with Kim Il-sung: \"Han S\u014fl-ya&nbsp;\u2014 he should be killed. He deserves it even only for just one book&nbsp;\u2014 ''History''. He is a very bad and harmful man; he is Kim Il Song's sycophant, a bootlicker\".{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=83}}\n\n===''Jackals''===\n{{quote box| align = right| width = 25em|quote=All in all, there were a lot of poor people living around here. The missionaries had purchased the area for twenty w\u014fn upon arriving in Korea twenty years ago. Since then they had turned it into a scenic summer retreat, on which Reverend Yi and one or two newly-rich families had recently erected neat brick houses. But far from benefiting from this, those who had always lived there in their rock huts just became more inextricably enmired in poverty as time went on.|source=''[[Jackals (Han Sorya novel)|Jackals]]''<ref>Translation in {{harvnb|Myers|1994|pp=158\u2013159}}</ref>| salign = right}}\n''[[Jackals (Han Sorya novel)|Jackals]]'',{{efn|The Korean name of the novella is {{Lang|ko|\uc2b9\ub0e5\uc774}} (''S\u016dngnyangi''), which literally means [[dhole]]s. In English, the work is often known as ''Jackals'' following Myers' translation.<ref name=\"sino\"/> Sometimes ''Wolves'' is used,{{sfn|David-West|2012|p=1}} whereas North Korean sources use ''Wolf''.<ref name=\"sino\"/><ref name=\"kcna_Dram\"/>}} is a 1951 novella by Han, noted for its [[anti-American]] and [[anti-Christian]] tendencies.<ref name=\"sino\">{{Cite web | title = Collapsist Narratives and State Strength: Reading The Interview through Han Sorya's Jackals | last = Fields | first = David | work = Sino-NK | date = 18 February 2015 | access-date=26 June 2015 | url = http://sinonk.com/2015/02/18/collapsist-narratives-and-state-strength-reading-the-interview-through-han-soryas-jackals/ }}</ref>{{sfn|Myers|2011|p=152}}\n''Jackals'' tells the story of a Korean boy murdered by American missionaries with an injection.{{sfn|Myers|2011|p=40}} In North Korea, the story is taken to be based on fact,{{sfn|Myers|2011|p=138}} and B. R. Myers assesses that it is possible that it gave impetus to [[allegations of biological warfare in the Korean War]] by North Korea.{{sfn|Myers|2011|p=40}} Called \"the country's most enduring work of fiction\",<ref name=\"nyti_TheO\">{{Cite web | title = The Obsessions of Kim Jong Il | last = Myers |first = Brian Reynolds | work = The New York Times | date = 19 May 2003 | accessdate = 2 July 2015 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2003/05/19/opinion/the-obsessions-of-kim-jong-il.html}}</ref> it is still influential in North Korea where the word \"jackals\" has become a synonym for \"Americans\", and papers like ''Rodong Sinmun'' regularly invoke the language of the novella.<ref name=\"sino\"/>\n\nThe emotional story is inspired by [[Maxim Gorky]]'s sentimental novel ''[[The Mother (Gorky novel)|Mother]]'',{{sfn|David-West|2012|p=2}} which is considered the first socialist realist novel,{{sfn|Wit|2015|p=110}} and a story that Han was familiar with.{{sfn|David-West|2012|p=2}} Myers traces the story's foundation back to anti-Christian stories in rural [[colonial Korea]] as well as in [[fascist Japan]].{{sfn|Myers|2011|p=152}} The metaphor of the villain as a beast, too, is more readily associated with wartime [[Japanese propaganda]] than socialist realism.{{sfn|Myers|1994|pp=95\u201396}} It had, however, featured in the works of early Soviet writers as whose work Han knew, as well as in textual genres not bound by the official socialist realist dogma, such as journalism.{{sfn|David-West|2012|pp=3\u20134}}\n\n''Jackals'' was republished in ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Chos\u014fn munhak|ko|3=\uc870\uc120\ubb38\ud559}}'', ''[[Ch'\u014fngny\u014fn munhak]]'' and ''[[Chollima (magazine)|Chollima]]'' in August 2003, one year after the [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]] designated North Korea as part of the \"[[Axis of evil]]\".{{sfn|David-West|2012|p=1}} After the [[Sony Pictures Entertainment hack]] of 2014, [[North Korean media]] employed similar rhetoric against [[Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]]. One article compared Kerry with a jackal no fewer than eleven times.<ref name=\"sino\"/> ''Jackals'' was adapted on stage and performed in Pyongyang in 2015.<ref name=\"kcna_Dram\">{{Cite web | title = Drama 'Wolf' Re-created in DPRK | agency = KCNA | date = 31 August 2015 | accessdate = 21 August 2016 | url = http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2015/201508/news31/20150831-20ee.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20191124075159/http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2015/201508/news31/20150831-20ee.html | archive-date = 24 November 2019 | url-status = dead }}</ref> The novel remains one of the very few North Korean works of fiction that have been translated into English.<ref name=\"japa_Writ\">{{Cite web| title = Writers From the Other Asia: the two Koreas| publisher = The Asia-Pacific Journal| last = Feffer |first = John| work = JapanFocus| date = 6 September 2006|access-date=23 June 2015| url = http://www.japanfocus.org/-John-Feffer/2215/article.html|page=4}}</ref>\n\n===List of works===\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|trans-title=Transition Period|title=Kwadogi|date=1929}}<ref name=\"Lee2003\">{{cite book|last=Lee|first=Peter H.|title=A History of Korean Literature|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pfb2QHJtw54C&pg=PA398|date=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-44086-8|page=398}}</ref> Short story.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|trans-title=Wrestling Match|title=Ssir\u016dm|date=1929}}<ref name=\"Lee2003\"/> Short story.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|trans-title=Erosion Work|date=1932|title=Sabang Kongsa}}<ref name=\"Lee2003\"/>\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|trans-title=Dusk|title=Hwanghon|date=1936}}<ref name=\"Lee2003\"/> Novel.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|trans-title=Pagoda|title=T'ap|date=1940}} Autobiographical novel.{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=189}}{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=35}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Ch'oso-es\u014f|trans-title=At a Guard Post|date=1950}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|trans-title=Path of Blood|title=Hy\u014flla|date=1946}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=37}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Mining Settlement|date=1946}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|trans-title=The Hat|date=1946|title=Moja}}{{sfn|Armstrong|2013|p=43}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Growing Village|date=1949}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Brother and Sister|date=1949}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|editor=Brian Myers|chapter=Jackals|title=Han S\u014frya and North Korean Literature: The Failure of Socialist Realism in DPRK|year=1994|orig-year=1951|publisher=East Asia Program, Cornell University|location=Ithca|isbn=978-0-939657-84-1|pages=157\u2013188}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|trans-title=The Taedong River|date=1955|title=Taedonggang}} Trilogy.{{sfn|Lankov|2007|p=33}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Man'gy\u014fngdae|date=1955}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=190}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Ry\u014fksa|trans-title=History|date=1958}} [[People's Prize]] (1958).{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=191}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Love|date=1960}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=191}}\n* {{cite book|author=Han Sorya|author-mask=1|title=Emulate the Leader|date=1960}}{{sfn|Myers|1994|p=191}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|North Korea|Biography}}\n* [[Cho Ki-chon]]\n* [[Korean literature]]\n* [[North Korean literature]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Works cited===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Armstrong|first=Charles K.|title=The North Korean Revolution, 1945\u20131950|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eUf-_XACg3UC|date=15 April 2013|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=0-8014-6879-5}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=David-West|first=Alzo|title=Savage Nature and Noble Spirit in Han S\u014frya's Wolves : A North Korean Morality Tale|journal=Transnational Literature|volume=4|number=2|date=May 2012|url=http://dspace.flinders.edu.au/jspui/bitstream/2328/25882/1/Savage_Nature.pdf|pages=1\u201318}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Lankov|first=Andrei|date=2007|title=Crisis in North Korea: The Failure of De-Stalinization, 1956|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cRDhhzwB2hYC|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|isbn=978-0-8248-3207-0}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Myers|first=B. R.|title=Han S\u014frya and North Korean Literature: The Failure of Socialist Realism in DPRK|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1yhwAAAAMAAJ|date=1994|location=Ithca|publisher=East Asia Program, Cornell University|isbn=978-0-939657-84-1}}\n* {{cite journal|author-mask=1|ref=harv|last=Myers|first=Brian|date=2006|title=The Watershead that Wasn't: Re-evalutaing Kim Il Sung's 'Juche Speech' of 1955 |url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/19756057/watershed-that-wasnt-re-evaluating-kim-il-sungs-juche-speech-1955|journal=Acta Koreana|volume=9|issue=1}}\n* {{cite book|author-mask=1|last=Myers|first=B. R.|title=The Cleanest Race: How North Koreans See Themselves and Why It Matters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KWQEAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT36|year=2011|publisher=Melville House|location=New York|isbn=978-1-935554-97-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|author-mask=1|last=Myers|first=B. R.|title=North Korea's Juche Myth|year=2015|location=Busan|publisher=Sthele Press|isbn=978-1-5087-9993-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|last=Ryu|first=Youngju|date=June 2013|editor-last1=Hanscom|editor-first1=Christopher P.|editor-last2=Lew|editor-first2=Walter K.|editor-last3=Ryu|editor-first3=Youngju|chapter=10. Kim Namch'\u014fn|pages=181\u2013196|title=Korean Classics Library : Historical Materials : Imperatives of Culture : Selected Essays on Korean History, Literature, and Society from the Japanese Colonial Era|location=Honolulu|publisher=University of Hawaii Press|via=ProQuest ebrary|access-date=23 June 2015|url=http://site.ebrary.com/lib/alltitles/docDetail.action?docID=10745589|isbn=978-0-8248-3904-8}}\n* {{cite thesis|ref=harv|last=Wit|first=Jer\u00f4me de|title=Writing under wartime conditions : North and South Korean writers during the Korean war (1950\u20131953)|type=Doctoral thesis|url=https://openaccess.leidenuniv.nl/bitstream/handle/1887/31445/Writing%20under%20Wartime%20Conditions%20Jerome%20de%20WitNIEUW.pdf?sequence=3|date=15 January 2015|publisher=Leiden University}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite thesis|last=Kim|first=Ellie Sue|title=Rituals of Decolonization: The Role of Inner-Migrant Intellectuals in North Korea, 1948\u20131967|type=Doctoral thesis|publisher=University of California Los Angeles|date=2014|url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/04176993#page-1|oclc=904783158}}\n* {{cite book|editor=Kw\u014fn Y\u014fgngmin|trans-title=Studies of Writers Who Went North|title=W\u014flbuk munin y\u014fn'gu|location=Seoul|publisher=Munhak sasangsa|year=1989|oclc=22847934}}\n* {{cite book|author=Se-p'yong Yun|date=30 November 1960|title=Han Sol-ya and His Literature: North Korea|location=Washington D.C., U.S.|publisher=Joint Publications Research Service|url=http://handle.dtic.mil/100.2/ADA376834#.pdf|oclc=227922016}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Flickr image inline link|kernbeisser/2469709564/|Grave of Han Sorya}}\n* [http://encykorea.aks.ac.kr/Contents/Index?contents_id=E0061717 Han Sorya] at the ''[[Encyclopedia of Korean Culture]]'' {{in lang|ko}}\n* [http://www.cybernk.net/infoText/InfoHumanDetail.aspx?mc=EJ0702&hid=EH010300012354&rightType=3&direct=1 Han Sorya] at ''[[North Korean Human Geography]]'' {{in lang|ko}}\n* {{YouTube|pjJeuAIMebc|\"American Wolf\" dance performance loosely based on ''Jackals''}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Han, Sorya}}\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:Education ministers]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of North Korea]]\n[[Category:North Korean novelists]]\n[[Category:People from Hamhung]]\n[[Category:Socialist realism writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century novelists]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n", "name_user": "Rakoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Han_Sorya"}
{"title_page": "Bob Tuke", "text_new": "{{Infobox Congressional Candidate\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Bob Tuke\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image =\n| state = Illinois\n| nominee=[[United States Senate election in Tennessee, 2008|U.S. Senator from Tennessee]]\n| opponent = [[Lamar Alexander]] (R)\n| incumbent = [[Lamar Alexander]]\n| election_date = November 4, 2008\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|birth_name=Robert Dudley Tuke\n| birth_date={{birth date and age|1947|12|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Rochester, New York]]\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| alma_mater = [[University of Virginia]], [[Vanderbilt University]]\n| profession = [[Attorney at law (United States)|attorney]]\n| spouse = Susan\n| residence =\n| religion =\n\n}}\n\n'''Robert Dudley Tuke''' (born December 5, 1947, Rochester, New York) was the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for the [[United States Senate election in Tennessee, 2008|2008 United States Senate election in Tennessee]], having won the Democratic primary in August. He faced incumbent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Lamar Alexander]] in the general election in November, losing by approximately 33% of the final vote.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.tennessean.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081104/NEWS0206/81104163| title=Alexander wins re-election in landslide| publisher=The Tennessean| date=2008-11-04| accessdate=2008-11-18}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nTuke served in the [[United States Marine]] and led a combined force in [[Vietnam]] during the [[Vietnam War]]. He led the Veterans for [[John Kerry|Kerry]] campaign for Tennessee in 2004. Tuke was elected chairman of the Democratic Party of [[Tennessee]] on June 18, 2005, serving for two years.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mielczarek|first=Natalia|title=Lawyer Tuke is Democrats' new chairman|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/303999676/|newspaper=The Tennessean|date=June 19, 2005|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|p=B2|accessdate=August 22, 2018}}</ref> He also served as [[Barack Obama]]'s Presidential campaign chair in Tennessee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Three major candidates put Tenn. in travel plans|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/278902046/|newspaper=The Tennessean|date=March 5, 2008|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|p=A14|accessdate=August 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nTuke earned his bachelor's degree from the [[University of Virginia]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]]. He is also a graduate of [[Vanderbilt University]], where he received his [[juris doctorate]].<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=104715 Robert D. 'Bob' Tuke] ''Project Vote Smart''</ref>  {{As of|2008}}, Tuke is a partner at the [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] law firm of Trauger and Tuke.<ref>{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=Bonna|title=Attorney Tuke hopes to unseat Alexander|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/278997769|newspaper=The Tennessean|date=February 24, 2008|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|p=B1|accessdate=August 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"TribuneProfile\">{{cite news |title=Chairman Bob Tuke Begins His First Week of Work as the Chairman of the Tennessee Democratic Party |publisher=Tennessee Tribune |date=21 July 2005|id={{ProQuest|368969451}} }}</ref>  Tuke is married to Susan Cummins Tuke; the couple have two grown children, Andrew and Sarah.<ref name=\"TribuneProfile\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[United States Senate election in Tennessee, 2008]]\n\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite news | title=Clement Names Bob Tuke As State Finance Chairman | work=The Chattanoogan | date=8 May 2002 | url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/2002/5/8/21597/Clement-Names-Bob-Tuke-As-State-Finance.aspx| access-date=29 August 2018}}\n* {{cite news |title=How this law came about |work=Tennessee Bar Journal |url=http://www.tba.org/journal/how-this-law-came-about }}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* {{cite news |last=Wade |first=Paula |work=The Commercial Appeal |location=Memphis, Tenn. |date=22 May 1995 |p=A.1}}\n* {{cite news |last=Wiley |first=Henry |date=10 January 2008 |title=Battle brewing in tennessee |work=Tri-State Defender |id={{ProQuest|367737846}} }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{CongLinks | congbio= | votesmart=104715 | fec=S8TN00238 | congress= }}<!-- Links formerly displayed via the {{CongLinks}} template:\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/Senate/Bob_Tuke.htm Issue positions and quotes] at [[On the Issues]]\n* -->\n* [http://www.opensecrets.org/races/summary.php?cycle=2008&id=TNS2 Campaign contributions] at [[OpenSecrets.org]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tuke, Bob}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2008 United States elections]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:State political party chairs of Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Democrats]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Democratic Party chairs]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps officers]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia alumni]]\n\n\n{{Tennessee-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Congressional Candidate\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Bob Tuke\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image =\n| state = Illinois\n| nominee=[[United States Senate election in Tennessee, 2008|U.S. Senator from Tennessee]]\n| opponent = [[Lamar Alexander]] (R)\n| incumbent = [[Lamar Alexander]]\n| election_date = November 4, 2008\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|birth_name=Robert Dudley Tuke\n| birth_date={{birth date and age|1947|12|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Rochester, New York]]\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| alma_mater = [[University of Virginia]], [[Vanderbilt University]]\n| profession = [[Attorney at law (United States)|attorney]]\n| spouse = Susan\n| residence =\n| religion =\n\n}}\n\n'''Robert Dudley Tuke''' (born December 5, 1947, Rochester, New York) was the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for the [[United States Senate election in Tennessee, 2008|2008 United States Senate election in Tennessee]], having won the Democratic primary in August. He faced incumbent [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Lamar Alexander]] in the general election in November, losing by approximately 33% of the final vote.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.tennessean.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081104/NEWS0206/81104163| title=Alexander wins re-election in landslide| publisher=The Tennesseean| date=2008-11-04| accessdate=2008-11-18}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nTuke served in the [[United States Marine]] and led a combined force in [[Vietnam]] during the [[Vietnam War]]. He led the Veterans for [[John Kerry|Kerry]] campaign for Tennessee in 2004. Tuke was elected chairman of the Democratic Party of [[Tennessee]] on June 18, 2005, serving for two years.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mielczarek|first=Natalia|title=Lawyer Tuke is Democrats' new chairman|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/303999676/|newspaper=The Tennessean|date=June 19, 2005|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|p=B2|accessdate=August 22, 2018}}</ref> He also served as [[Barack Obama]]'s Presidential campaign chair in Tennessee.<ref>{{cite news|title=Three major candidates put Tenn. in travel plans|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/278902046/|newspaper=The Tennessean|date=March 5, 2008|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|p=A14|accessdate=August 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nTuke earned his bachelor's degree from the [[University of Virginia]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]]. He is also a graduate of [[Vanderbilt University]], where he received his [[juris doctorate]].<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=104715 Robert D. 'Bob' Tuke] ''Project Vote Smart''</ref>  {{As of|2008}}, Tuke is a partner at the [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] law firm of Trauger and Tuke.<ref>{{cite news|last=Johnson|first=Bonna|title=Attorney Tuke hopes to unseat Alexander|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/278997769|newspaper=The Tennessean|date=February 24, 2008|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|p=B1|accessdate=August 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"TribuneProfile\">{{cite news |title=Chairman Bob Tuke Begins His First Week of Work as the Chairman of the Tennessee Democratic Party |publisher=Tennessee Tribune |date=21 July 2005|id={{ProQuest|368969451}} }}</ref>  Tuke is married to Susan Cummins Tuke; the couple have two grown children, Andrew and Sarah.<ref name=\"TribuneProfile\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[United States Senate election in Tennessee, 2008]]\n\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite news | title=Clement Names Bob Tuke As State Finance Chairman | work=The Chattanoogan | date=8 May 2002 | url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/2002/5/8/21597/Clement-Names-Bob-Tuke-As-State-Finance.aspx| access-date=29 August 2018}}\n* {{cite news |title=How this law came about |work=Tennessee Bar Journal |url=http://www.tba.org/journal/how-this-law-came-about }}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n* {{cite news |last=Wade |first=Paula |work=The Commercial Appeal |location=Memphis, Tenn. |date=22 May 1995 |p=A.1}}\n* {{cite news |last=Wiley |first=Henry |date=10 January 2008 |title=Battle brewing in tennessee |work=Tri-State Defender |id={{ProQuest|367737846}} }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{CongLinks | congbio= | votesmart=104715 | fec=S8TN00238 | congress= }}<!-- Links formerly displayed via the {{CongLinks}} template:\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/Senate/Bob_Tuke.htm Issue positions and quotes] at [[On the Issues]]\n* -->\n* [http://www.opensecrets.org/races/summary.php?cycle=2008&id=TNS2 Campaign contributions] at [[OpenSecrets.org]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tuke, Bob}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2008 United States elections]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:State political party chairs of Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Democrats]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Democratic Party chairs]]\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps officers]]\n[[Category:University of Virginia alumni]]\n\n\n{{Tennessee-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo fixing, replaced: Tennesseean \u2192 Tennessean", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Tuke"}
{"title_page": "HCT Group", "text_new": "{{Short description|Group of community transport operators in Britain}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date = July 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox Bus transit\n|name            = HCT Group\n|logo            = HCTGroup.svg\n|logo_size       = 200\n|image           = Au Morandarte Flickr CT Plus EO1 on Route 388, Trowbridge Estate (Hackney Wick) (11381089715).jpg\n|image_size      = \n|image_caption   = [[Optare Olympus|Darwen Olympus]] bodied [[Alexander Dennis Enviro400]] in [[Hackney Wick]] in 2013\n|company_slogan  = Social justice and equality for all\n|parent          =   \n|founded         = 1982\n|headquarters    = [[Old Street]], [[London]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Contacting HCT Group |url=http://hctgroup.org/hct_corporate/contact_us |website=HCT Group |accessdate=4 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704131917/http://hctgroup.org/hct_corporate/contact_us |archivedate=4 July 2019}}</ref>\n|locale          = \n|service_area    = {{hlist|[[Bristol]]|[[Guernsey]]|[[Jersey]]|[[London]]|[[Yorkshire]]|[[Manchester]]|[[Derbyshire]]}}\n|service_type    = Bus services\n|routes          = \n|hubs            = \n|stations        =\n|lounge          = \n|fleet           = \n|ridership       = \n|fuel_type       = \n|operator        = \n|ceo             = Dai Powell\n|website         = [http://www.hctgroup.org/ www.hctgroup.org]}}\n\n'''HCT Group'''<ref>[http://data.companieshouse.gov.uk/doc/company/01747483 Companies House extract company no 1747483] HCT Group</ref> is a [[social enterprise]] providing transport services and community services in [[Bristol]], [[Guernsey]], [[Jersey]], [[London]], and [[Yorkshire]]. It was founded in 1982 as ''Hackney Community Transport'' in the [[London Borough of Hackney]] to provide transport services for local voluntary organisations, charities, and community groups. HCT Group is registered as a [[company limited by guarantee]] (and has therefore no [[shareholders]]). The company is also a registered [[Charitable organization|charity]].<ref>[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=28 Our structure] on HCT Group website, retrieved 1 October 2009</ref>\n\nFounded in 1982, the HCT Group has a fleet of 500 vehicles and a turnover of \u00a343.7m (as of 2014)<ref>'[http://www.thenews.coop/92351/news/community/the-phone-co-op-invests-in-public-transport-social-enterprise/ The Phone Co-op invests in public transport social enterprise]' on ''[[Co-operative News]]'' website, dated 2014-12-09, viewed 17 December 2014</ref> and employs over 700 people. In June 2011 it reinvested 37% of annual profits into local community services, its best performance to date. Its chief executive, Dai Powell, joined the social enterprise as a bus cleaner.<ref>''[https://www.theguardian.com/social-enterprise-network/2011/sep/02/start-ups-growth-social-enterprises Research shows 'start-up explosion' in deprived communities]'' on ''[[The Guardian]]'' website, viewed 10 September 2011</ref>\n{{TOClimit}}\n\n==London==\n'''CT Plus''' was founded as a wholly owned trading arm of HCT in 2001, and became a [[community interest company]] in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ctplus.org/about_ct_plus|title=About CT Plus|website=CT Plus|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/04137890|title=CT PLUS COMMUNITY INTEREST COMPANY|website=Companies House|language=en|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref> The company competes for contracts in the marketplace, and its profits are used by HCT to support community transport or other objectives such as training for the long-term unemployed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/how_we_work|title=How we work|website=HCT Group|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref> In August 2019 the CT Plus brand was dropped with operations brought under the HCT Group banner.\n\n===History===\nIn 2001, CT Plus began operating its [[Transport for London]] contracted service, [[London Buses route 153|route 153]].<ref>[http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/the_hct_group_story The HCT Group story] HCT Group</ref> In 2003, it began operating routes [[London Buses route 388|388]] and [[London Buses route 394|394]].\n\n===Public services in London===\n[[File:CT Plus HTL10 PF52 TFX 2.JPG|thumb|[[East Lancs Myllennium Lolyne]] bodied [[Dennis Trident 2]] on [[London Buses route 388|route 388]] in June 2009]]\n[[File:YJ10EYK Optare OS7 of CT Plus, Coppermill Lane, E17 - Flickr - sludgegulper.jpg|thumb|[[Optare Solo]] on [[London Buses route W12|route W12]] in March 2010]]\n====Ash Grove (HK)====\n[[Ash Grove bus garage]] was CT Plus' first London garage, and is shared with [[Arriva London]]. This garage operates 10 routes, including [[London Buses route 26|route 26]] and [[London Buses route 394|route 394]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Our routes |url=http://ctplus.org/ct_plus/red_bus_routes_20 |website=CT plus |accessdate=4 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704132129/http://ctplus.org/ct_plus/red_bus_routes_20 |archivedate=4 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Walthamstow Avenue (AW)====\nIn November 2016, CT Plus opened a second garage in [[Walthamstow]].<ref>[https://cbwmagazine.com/ct-plus-opens-new-walthamstow-garage/ CT Plus opens new Walthamstow garage] ''[[Coach & Bus Week]]'' 2 December 2016</ref> As of March 2019, Walthamstow Avenue operates routes 20, 385, 397, W11, W12, W16, and W19.\n\n===Other London services===\n*Special Educational Needs Transport and coach and bus hire, in [[Waltham Forest]]\n*Social services transport, in [[Royal Borough of Kensington & Chelsea|Kensington & Chelsea]]\n*Day Centre & Special Educational Needs Transport, in [[London Borough of Lambeth|Lambeth]]\n*Special Educational Needs Transport, in [[London Borough of Southwark|Southwark]]\n*Impact Group, purchased from [[Tower Transit]] in August 2018<ref>\"Impact acquired by HCT Group\" ''Coach & Bus Week'' issue 1355 15 August 2018 page 7</ref><ref>[http://www.route-one.net/articles/Business_deals/HCT_Group_purchases_Impact_as_it_grows_again HCT Group purchases Impact as it grows again] ''Route One'' 15 August 2018</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hctgroup.org/1417/HCT+Group+acquires+west+London+operator+Impact+Group/about_us/hct_group_news?page=2|title=HCT Group - All the latest news from HCT Group|website=www.hctgroup.org|access-date=2019-07-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Fleet ===\nAs at March 2017, the Transport for London fleet consisted of 120 buses.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Carr|first1=Ken|title=The London Bus Guide|date=May 2015|publisher=Visions International Entertainment|location=Boreham|isbn=978-0-9931735-3-0|page=24|edition=5}}</ref>\n\n==Outside London==\n[[Image:AccessBus in Leeds9.JPG|thumb|AccessBus in [[Leeds]]]]\nHCT also operates a number of community and mainstream bus services outside London.\n\n=== West Yorkshire ===\n'''CT Plus''' ([[Yorkshire]]) operates from depots in [[Wakefield]] and [[Leeds]],<ref>{{cite web |title=CT PLUS (YORKSHIRE) COMMUNITY INTEREST COMPANY |url=https://www.vehicle-operator-licensing.service.gov.uk/view-details/licence/316558 |website=Vehicle Operator Licensing |accessdate=1 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101094759/https://www.vehicle-operator-licensing.service.gov.uk/view-details/licence/316558 |archivedate=1 January 2019}}</ref> with a fleet of around 110 vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nebula.wsimg.com/34b18440c0c950ff708d657bc2804731?AccessKeyId=8B7A174C4DD908996CD8&disposition=0&alloworigin=1|title=CT Plus Yorkshire|website=Sheffield Omnibus Enthusiasts Society|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101095125/http://nebula.wsimg.com/34b18440c0c950ff708d657bc2804731?AccessKeyId=8B7A174C4DD908996CD8&disposition=0&alloworigin=1|archivedate=1 January 2019|accessdate=1 January 2019}}</ref> The services in Yorkshire consist mostly of [[West Yorkshire Metro]] tendered services: AccessBus, a [[demand responsive transport]] service providing local transport for those unable to use regular transport,<ref>{{cite web |title=AccessBus: The flexible alternative to regular bus services |url=https://www.wymetro.com/buses/rural-services/accessbus/ |website=Metro |accessdate=1 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101100736/https://www.wymetro.com/buses/rural-services/accessbus/ |archivedate=1 January 2019}}</ref> and school buses, including some '[[My bus]]' [[School bus yellow|yellow]] [[school bus]] contracts.<ref>{{cite web |title=My Bus: School buses in Leeds and Wakefield |url=http://www.ctplusyorks.org/my_bus |website=CT plus Yorkshire |accessdate=15 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215121548/http://www.ctplusyorks.org/my_bus |archivedate=15 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A few public routes are operated, around Wakefield, [[Pontefract]], and [[South Elmsall]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Bus services |url=http://www.ctplusyorks.org/bus_services_7 |website=CT Plus Yorkshire |accessdate=1 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101095733/http://www.ctplusyorks.org/bus_services_7 |archivedate=1 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=CT Plus (Yorkshire) |url=https://bustimes.org/operators/ct-plus-yorkshire |website=Bus Times |accessdate=15 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215121249/https://bustimes.org/operators/ct-plus-yorkshire |archivedate=15 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, some private contracts are operated, including two shuttle services for the [[NHS England|NHS]].<ref>{{cite web |title=CT Plus Yorkshire wins Doncaster NHS Shuttle |url=http://www.hctgroup.org/the_hct_group/ct_plus_yorkshire/yorskshire_news/645/CT%20Plus%20Yorkshire%20wins%20Doncaster%20NHS%20Shuttle |website=CT Plus Yorkshire |accessdate=1 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101100055/http://www.hctgroup.org/the_hct_group/ct_plus_yorkshire/yorskshire_news/645/CT%20Plus%20Yorkshire%20wins%20Doncaster%20NHS%20Shuttle |archivedate=1 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Elsewhere ===\n*[[Manchester Community Transport]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester Community Transport joins HCT Group |url=http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/609/Manchester%20Community%20Transport%20joins%20HCT%20Group |website=HCT group news |accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n*Powells Bus, [[South Yorkshire]], acquired July 2018<ref>[http://www.route-one.net/articles/Bus_routes/Debut_purchase__HCT_Group_buys_South_Yorks_Powells_Bus Debut purchase: HCT Group buys South Yorks Powells Bus] ''Route One'' 25 July 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.busandcoachbuyer.com/hct-group-acquires-powells-bus/ HCT Group acquires Powells Bus] ''Bus & Coach Buyer'' 1 August 2018</ref>\n*Routes 505, 506, 511, and 512, branded Bristol Community Transport, under contract to [[Bristol City Council]], from 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bristolcommunitytransport.org.uk/bus_services_5|title=Bus services|website=Bristol Community Transport|language=en|access-date=21 July 2018}}</ref> Since January 2019 Bristol Community Transport operate route m1 of [[MetroBus (Bristol)|Bristol Metrobus]], using 21 [[biogas]]-powered buses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/630/Bristol%20Community%20Transport%20unveiled%20as%20Metrobus%20m1%20operator|title=Bristol Community Transport unveiled as Metrobus m1 operator|website=HCT Group|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214062728/http://hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/630/Bristol%20Community%20Transport%20unveiled%20as%20Metrobus%20m1%20operator|archivedate=14 December 2018|accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Guernsey]] public bus services, branded as buses.gg<ref>[http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/247/CT%20Plus%20begins%20Guernsey%20operations%20 HCT Group \u00a6 Social Enterprise bus operator \u00a6 - All the latest news from HCT Group<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n*[[Jersey]] public bus services, branded as [[LibertyBus]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://libertybus.je/about/social_enterprise|title=Who are LibertyBus|website=Liberty Bus|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n*Derbyshire Community Transport<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.derbyshirect.org/|title=Derbyshire Community Transport - Derbyshire Community Transport|website=www.derbyshirect.org|access-date=2019-07-14}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Former operations ===\n* [[Park and ride]] bus service in [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], 2010 to 2014<ref>[http://www.thisishullandeastriding.co.uk/news/London-based-group-wins-Hull-park-ride-deal/article-1340517-detail/article.html London group wins Hull park and ride deal] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120913181616/http://www.thisishullandeastriding.co.uk/news/London-based-group-wins-Hull-park-ride-deal/article-1340517-detail/article.html |date=13 September 2012 }} on thisishullandeastriding.co.uk news website, retrieved 1 October 2009</ref><ref name=CB_Hull_Withdrawal>{{Cite web|url=https://cbwmagazine.com/stagecoach-improve-hull-park-ride/|title=Stagecoach improve Hull Park & Ride|date=6 October 2014|website=Coach & Bus Week|language=en-GB|access-date=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Community transport services==\n[[Image:Special needs education transport services in Waltham Forest0.JPG|thumb|[[Special needs]] education transport services in [[Waltham Forest]]]]\nHCT operates:<ref>[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=42 Community transport services] on HCT Group website, retrieved 1 October 2009</ref>\n*[[accessible]] [[minibus]]es for community and voluntary groups\n*'Capital Call' - a door-to-door service provided by [[Minicab|private hire vehicle]]s for users with mobility difficulties\n*'ScootAbility' - a [[mobility scooter]] home delivery service\n*'PlusBus' - a bus service for those who have difficulty accessing mainstream transport\n*'Door 2 Door' - a transport service provided by volunteers for [[London Borough of Hackney|Hackney]] residents\n*'Integrated Transport Solutions' - a transport [[contract management]] service\n*'YourCar' - a door-to-door service for registered users with mobility difficulties in the London Boroughs of [[London Borough of Lambeth|Lambeth]] and [[London Borough of Southwark|Southwark]]\n\n==Education and training==\nHCT provides [[education]] services supported by the [[Learning and Skills Council]] and the [[London Development Agency]]. The courses include [[bus driver]] training, particularly for [[women]], [[social care]], and [[management]].<ref>''[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=5 Our Learning Centre]'' on company website, retrieved 4 January 2011</ref>\n\n==Social enterprise and transport==\n[[Image:My bus at Bingley.jpg|thumb|[[West Yorkshire Metro]] [[My bus]] school bus service operated by CT Plus in [[Bingley]]]]\n[[File:CT Plus Guernsey Bus.jpg|thumb|An [[East Lancashire Coachbuilders|ELC bodied]] bus on [[Guernsey]] in November 2015]]\nThe British government has promoted the delivery of public services by [[not for profit]] organisations (the [[Voluntary sector|third sector]]).<ref name=\"AGENDA ITEM NO 16\">[https://www.wypta.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/D92FD985-A09D-4FE4-A764-6ABFFC930E2A/0/PTA21NOVEMBER2008ITEM16.pdf AGENDA ITEM NO: 16. SUBJECT: COMMUNITY TRANSPORT] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002082239/https://www.wypta.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/D92FD985-A09D-4FE4-A764-6ABFFC930E2A/0/PTA21NOVEMBER2008ITEM16.pdf |date=2 October 2011 }} on [[West Yorkshire Metro]] website, retrieved 9 October 2009</ref> British prime minister [[David Cameron]] has stated that he wants more social enterprises running public services as part of his \"[[Big Society]]\".<ref name=\"socialist\"/>\n\nCharitable legal website ''Get Legal'' described HCT's [[corporate structure]] as allowing HCT Group to \"separate the risks associated with its business in different [[limited liability]] [[Legal personality|vehicle]]s. The social mission of each of those vehicles is protected (either through [[charitable status]] or through being [[community interest company|CIC]]s) which sends a clear message to the public that the organisation is a social enterprise''.<ref>''[http://www.getlegal.org.uk/resources/case-studies/hackney-community-transport.html HCT Group case study] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100802222603/http://www.getlegal.org.uk/resources/case-studies/hackney-community-transport.html |date=2 August 2010 }} on ''Get Legal'' website, retrieved 4 January 2011</ref>\n\nHCT says it aims to \"demonstrate and promote the social enterprise [[business model]] as a highly effective and [[socially responsible]] mechanism\", and that it maintains [[Environmental policy|environmental]], [[health and safety]], and [[social policy|social policies]], and regularly measures its performance against these.<ref>''[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=7 Corporate responsibility]'' on Group website, retrieved 4 January 2011</ref> Profit is seen by company CEO Dai Powell as enabling its social goals: \"You have to be an enterprise first, because if you don't make a profit, you can't fulfil that social mission.\"<ref name=\"ambassadors\">{{cite web|url=http://socialenterpriseambassadors.org.uk/ambassador/dai-powell |title=Profile of Dai Powell on socialenterpriseambassadors.org website |date=4 January 2011 |archivedate=1 August 2011 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110801000436/http://socialenterpriseambassadors.org.uk/ambassador/dai-powell }}</ref> HCT's commercial services allowed it to invest 18 per cent of its annual profits into non-commercial [[community transport]] in 2007/08. Its mission was to increase this to 30 per cent in the subsequent five years.<ref name=\"ambassadors\"/>\n\nHCT only competes for contracts that have high levels of [[accessibility]] and quality in the specification.<ref name=\"action plan\"/> \"HCT sees the provision of high-quality [[public services]] as a goal in itself...and actively seeks user input into the design and delivery of all its services.\"<ref name=\"action plan\">''[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20101213144151/http:/www.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/media/cabinetoffice/third_sector/assets/se_action_plan_2006.pdf Social enterprise action plan: Scaling New Heights]'', British cabinet paper, retrieved 8 October 2009</ref> The CEO claims \"we don't provide poor services for poor people \u2013 the quality has to be there.\u201d<ref name=\"ambassadors\"/> HCT recruits [[Volunteering|volunteers]] to train people with [[learning disabilities|learning difficulties]] and [[physical disabilities]] to use public transport independently.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719103731/http://www.bassac.org.uk/members/work-of-members/working-with-volunteers|url=http://www.bassac.org.uk/members/work-of-members/working-with-volunteers|title= Engaging the unemployed in a volunteer led community service - HCT Group|author=British Association of Settlements and Social Action Centres website|date=4 January 2011|archivedate=19 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[West Yorkshire Metro]] noted that a community transport provider \"...spends its surpluses on transport services in the community which are not commissioned from public bodies\" but that \"commissioning from the sector can however carry risks...organisations can lack capability and professionalism and be over reliant on individuals leading to instability.\"<ref name=\"AGENDA ITEM NO 16\"/>\n\nHCT Group is no more immune to [[labour relations]] problems than any other bus operator.<ref>see for example [http://www.wrp.org.uk/news/3227 40 BUS WORKERS PICKET ASH GROVE] on [[Workers Revolutionary Party (UK)|Workers Revolutionary Party]] news website, and [http://archive.unitetheunion.org/news__events/archived_news_releases/2008_archived_press_releases/london_bus_workers_at_hackney.aspx London bus workers at Hackney to strike over dismissal of shop steward] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217221331/http://archive.unitetheunion.org/news__events/archived_news_releases/2008_archived_press_releases/london_bus_workers_at_hackney.aspx |date=17 December 2013 }} on [[Unite the union]] news website; both retrieved 10 October 2009</ref> The ''[[Socialist Worker]]'' described HCT as \"no friend of workers\" and its workers as \"some of the lowest paid drivers in London\".<ref name=\"socialist\">'[http://www.socialistworker.co.uk/art.php?id=22694 East London bus drivers picket bosses over pay]' on ''[[Socialist Worker]]'' website, retrieved 6 January 2011</ref>\n\nHCT Group prefers social enterprises and [[Cooperative|co-ops]] as [[business partner]]s and suppliers;<ref>'[https://www.theguardian.com/social-enterprise-network/2011/oct/17/social-enterprises-co-ops-business-partners?newsfeed=true Why we prefer social enterprises and co-ops as business partners]' on ''[[The Guardian]]'' website, viewed 19 October 2011</ref> when they raised \u00a3500k [[impact investing|impact investment]] from [[The Phone Co-op|The Phone Co-Op]] in 2014, their CEO explained with investors as well as suppliers they want to \"buy social\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anca|first1=Voinea|title=The Phone Co-op invests in public transport social enterprise|url=http://www.thenews.coop/92351/news/community/the-phone-co-op-invests-in-public-transport-social-enterprise/|website=The News Co-Op|accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, HCT Group secured \u00a317.8 million in funding to tackle social isolation, with the help of the investment bank ClearlySo. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukbaa.org.uk/news/clearlyso-helps-hct-group-secure-17-8-million-in-funding-to-tackle-social-isolation/|title=ClearlySo helps HCT Group secure \u00a317.8 million in funding to tackle social isolation {{!}} UK Business Angels Association (UKBAA)|last=|first=|date=|website=UK Business Angels Association|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Dai Powell.jpg|thumb|150px|Dai Powel, the [[CEO]] of HCT Group, formerly a coal miner in [[Wales]],<ref name=\"ft\"/> joined as a bus cleaner in 1990<ref name=\"origins\"/>]]\n\n''Hackney Community Transport'' was established in 1982 when 30 community groups in the [[London Borough of Hackney]] formed a pool of six vehicles with a grant from [[Hackney Borough Council]] to provide low cost [[van]] and [[minibus]] [[rental car|hire]] for local community groups, and a [[door to door]] alternative to [[public transport]] for [[people with disabilities]].<ref name=\"origins\"/> The company's services were staffed by [[Volunteering|volunteers]],<ref name=\"origins\">[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=12 Origins] on HCT Group website, retrieved 18 October 2009</ref> but over the next decade a small group of [[employee|paid staff]] built up to assist the volunteer workforce.<ref>[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=13 1986 - 1996] on HCT Group website, retrieved 18 October 2009</ref>\n\nHCT Group received loans from London Rebuilding Society to finance its entry to the bus industry.<ref name=\"rebuilding\">[http://www.londonrebuilding.com/information/89713/90262/91013/90539/hct_group/ HCT Group] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908055447/http://www.londonrebuilding.com/information/89713/90262/91013/90539/hct_group/ |date=8 September 2008 }} on http://www.londonrebuilding.com website, retrieved 8 October 2009</ref>\n\nIn 2004, HCT was contracted by EduAction to deliver 500 local [[special needs]] children to school and back each day for [[London Borough of Waltham Forest]] from a new depot in [[Leyton]].<ref name=\"2004 - 2005\">[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=18 2004 - 2005] on HCT Group website, retrieved 19 October 2009</ref>\n\nIn March 2006, HCT expanded outside London to run eight yellow ''[[My bus]]'' school transport routes in and around [[City of Wakefield|Wakefield]] for [[West Yorkshire Metro]]. A further seven runs were added in September<ref name=\"2006 page\">[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=82 2006] on HCT Group website, retrieved 19 October 2009</ref> and three more in September 2007.<ref name=\"2007 page\">[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=92 2007] on HCT Group website, retrieved 19 October 2009</ref>\n\nIn July 2006, HCT merged with Lambeth & Southwark Community Transport.<ref name=\"2006 page\"/>\n\nOn 1 October 2006, HCT began to operate the AccessBus service in [[Leeds]]<ref name=\"2006 page\"/> and in 2008, merged with Leeds Alternative Travel.<ref name=\"2008 page\">[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=117 2008] on HCT Group website, retrieved 19 October 2009</ref>\n\nIn March 2009, HCT Group published its first Impact Report.<ref>''[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?type=ARTICLE&articleid=41 HCT Group publishes its first Impact Report]'' on group website, retrieved 4 January 2011</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, CT Plus Yorkshire took over the [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] 701 Priory Park & Ride route,<ref>''[http://hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/33/Commencement%20of%20Hull%20Priory%20Park%20and%20Ride%20service Commencement of Hull Priory Park Park and Ride service]'' on group website, retrieved 4 January 2011</ref> with the aim of investing any surplus from its park-and-ride operation to expand a local community transport service and to set up training for long-term unemployed people in Hull.<ref>''[http://www.thisishullandeastriding.co.uk/news/Park-ride-firm-HCT-focusing-community/article-1879465-detail/article.html Park-and-ride firm HCT is focusing on the community]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}'' on ''[[Hull Daily Mail]]'' website, retrieved 4 January 2011</ref> This was withdrawn in 2014, with Stagecoach taking over the service.<ref name=\"CB_Hull_Withdrawal\" />\n\nIn February 2010, HCT Group raised \u00a35 million via a social loan.<ref name=\"ft\"/> By 2010 HCT had grown by over a hundredfold since 1993 \u2013 from a turnover of \u00a3202k to a turnover of \u00a323.3m in 2009/10.<ref name=\"scale\">'[https://www.theguardian.com/social-enterprise-network/2011/feb/28/lessons-race-scale-htc?INTCMP=SRCH Our lessons from the race for scale]' on ''[[The Guardian]]'' website, retrieved 7 March 2011</ref>\n\nIn 2017 and 2018, the group completed a series of acquisitions, purchasing Social Access, Bristol;<ref>{{cite web |title=Social Access joins the HCT Group |url=http://hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/590/Social%20Access%20joins%20the%20HCT%20Group |website=HCT Group News |accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> [[Manchester Community Transport]];<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester Community Transport joins HCT Group |url=http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/609/Manchester%20Community%20Transport%20joins%20HCT%20Group |website=HCT Group News |accessdate=15 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211010525/http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/609/Manchester%20Community%20Transport%20joins%20HCT%20Group |archivedate=11 December 2018}}</ref> CT4TC,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |title=CT4TC joins HCT Group |url=http://hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/628/CT4TC%20joins%20HCT%20Group |website=HCT Group News |accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> a Derbyshire community transport operator since renamed Derbyshire Community Transport;<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |title=CT4TC announces its new name - Derbyshire Community Transport |url=http://hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/633/CT4TC%20announces%20its%20new%20name%20-%20Derbyshire%20Community%20Transport |website=HCT Group News}}</ref> Powells, South Yorkshire;<ref>{{cite web |title=HCT Group acquire Powells Bus |url=http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/639/HCT%20Group%20acquire%20Powells%20Bus |website=HCT Group News |accessdate=15 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215141751/http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/639/HCT%20Group%20acquire%20Powells%20Bus |archivedate=15 December 2018}}</ref> and Impact Group, West London.<ref>{{cite web |title=HCT Group acquires west London operator Impact Group |url=http://hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/643/HCT%20Group%20acquires%20west%20London%20operator%20Impact%20Group |website=HCT Group News}}</ref>\n==Corporate strategy==\n[[Image:Social services transport in Kensington and Chelsea.jpg|thumb|[[Social services]] transport in [[Royal Borough of Kensington & Chelsea|Kensington & Chelsea]]]]\nHCT Group's [[corporate strategy]] is to generate [[Profit (accounting)|profit]]s from providing commercial transport services, then to use these profits to provide community transport services for people unable to use mainstream transport. The two modes, [[public transport]] and special need transport, are fully integrated under their model: \"the investment in responsive community transport services is made possible by running the commercial activity well.\"<ref name=\"action plan\"/> The ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported in 2010 that [[revenue|turnover]] had \"grown by about 25 per cent a year for the past eight years and is expected to top \u00a320m in the year to March 31, 2010, when profits will be around \u00a31m.\"<ref name=ft>''[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/41e6c628-1f11-11df-9584-00144feab49a.html#axzz1A38EItsw \u2018Social loan\u2019 for cause-based groups]'' on ''[[Financial Times]]'' website, retrieved 4 January 2011</ref> HCT's rapid growth is achieved by merging with smaller community transport organisations.<ref name=\"ambassadors\"/>\n\nHCT Group [[CEO]] Dai Powell, in an article explaining the group's strategy,<ref name=\"scale\"/> said the business aims to double in size every five or so years for the foreseeable future, seeing scale as \"...crucial. The better we do commercially, the more we can do for the communities we serve as a social enterprise\", and that the strategy is \"maximising the good that we do... to be as bold as a commercial firm, but to the benefit of our communities, not to the owners of [[capital (economics)|capital]]. It also has the advantage of keeping our social mission absolutely central to our approach.\" Powell contrasted this approach to that of many [[Voluntary sector|third sector]] organisations \"where [[risk]] is to be mitigated at worst and eliminated at best. This is simply hopeless for rapid growth.\" He describes the process as \"...so much more rewarding than spending your days \"maximising [[shareholder value]]\", whatever that means.\"''<ref name=\"scale\" />''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://bristolcommunitytransport.org.uk/ Bristol Community Transport]\n*[http://ctplus.org/ CT Plus, London]\n*[http://www.buses.gg/ Guernsey Buses]\n*[https://libertybus.je/ Liberty Bus, Jersey]\n*[http://www.ctplusyorks.org/ CT Plus Yorkshire]\n\n{{London bus operators|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Alternative trading organizations]]\n[[Category:Bus operators in Bristol]]\n[[Category:Bus operators in West Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:London bus operators]]\n[[Category:Social enterprises]]\n[[Category:Transport companies established in 1982]]\n[[Category:1982 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Group of community transport operators in Britain}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}{{Use British English|date = July 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox Bus transit\n|name            = HCT Group\n|logo            = HCTGroup.svg\n|logo_size       = 200\n|image           = Au Morandarte Flickr CT Plus EO1 on Route 388, Trowbridge Estate (Hackney Wick) (11381089715).jpg\n|image_size      = \n|image_caption   = [[Optare Olympus|Darwen Olympus]] bodied [[Alexander Dennis Enviro400]] in [[Hackney Wick]] in 2013\n|company_slogan  = Social justice and equality for all\n|parent          =   \n|founded         = 1982\n|headquarters    = [[Old Street]], [[London]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Contacting HCT Group |url=http://hctgroup.org/hct_corporate/contact_us |website=HCT Group |accessdate=4 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704131917/http://hctgroup.org/hct_corporate/contact_us |archivedate=4 July 2019}}</ref>\n|locale          = \n|service_area    = {{hlist|[[Bristol]]|[[Guernsey]]|[[Jersey]]|[[London]]|[[Yorkshire]]|[[Manchester]]|[[Derbyshire]]}}\n|service_type    = Bus services\n|routes          = \n|hubs            = \n|stations        =\n|lounge          = \n|fleet           = \n|ridership       = \n|fuel_type       = \n|operator        = \n|ceo             = Dai Powell\n|website         = [http://www.hctgroup.org/ www.hctgroup.org]}}\n\n'''HCT Group'''<ref>[http://data.companieshouse.gov.uk/doc/company/01747483 Companies House extract company no 1747483] HCT Group</ref> is a [[social enterprise]] providing transport services and community services in [[Bristol]], [[Guernsey]], [[Jersey]], [[London]] and [[Yorkshire]]. It was founded in 1982 as ''Hackney Community Transport'' in the [[London Borough of Hackney]] to provide transport services for local voluntary organisations, charities and community groups. HCT Group is registered as a [[company limited by guarantee]] (and has therefore no [[shareholders]]). The company is also a registered [[Charitable organization|charity]].<ref>[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=28 Our structure] on HCT Group website, retrieved 1 October 2009</ref>\n\nThe HCT Group was founded in 1982 and in 2014 had a fleet of 500 vehicles and a turnover of \u00a343.7m<ref>'[http://www.thenews.coop/92351/news/community/the-phone-co-op-invests-in-public-transport-social-enterprise/ The Phone Co-op invests in public transport social enterprise]' on ''[[Co-operative News]]'' website, dated 2014-12-09, viewed 17 December 2014</ref> and employs over 700 people. In June 2011 it reinvested 37% of annual profits into local community services, its best performance to date. Its chief executive, Dai Powell, joined the social enterprise as a bus cleaner.<ref>''[https://www.theguardian.com/social-enterprise-network/2011/sep/02/start-ups-growth-social-enterprises Research shows 'start-up explosion' in deprived communities]'' on ''[[The Guardian]]'' website, viewed 10 September 2011</ref>\n{{TOClimit}}\n\n==London==\n'''CT Plus''' was founded as a wholly owned trading arm of HCT in 2001, and became a [[community interest company]] in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ctplus.org/about_ct_plus|title=About CT Plus|website=CT Plus|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/04137890|title=CT PLUS COMMUNITY INTEREST COMPANY|website=Companies House|language=en|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref> The company competes for contracts in the marketplace, and its profits are used by HCT to support community transport or other objectives such as training for the long-term unemployed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/how_we_work|title=How we work|website=HCT Group|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref> In August 2019 the CT Plus brand was dropped with operations brought under the HCT Group banner.\n\n===Public services in London===\n====Ash Grove (HK)====\n[[File:CT Plus HTL10 PF52 TFX 2.JPG|thumb|[[East Lancs Myllennium Lolyne]] bodied [[Dennis Trident 2]] on [[London Buses route 388|route 388]] in June 2009]]\n[[File:YJ10EYK Optare OS7 of CT Plus, Coppermill Lane, E17 - Flickr - sludgegulper.jpg|thumb|[[Optare Solo]] on [[London Buses route W12|route W12]] in March 2010]]\n[[Ash Grove bus garage]] was CT Plus' first London garage, and is shared with [[Arriva London]]. This garage operates 10 routes, including [[London Buses route 26|route 26]] and [[London Buses route 394|route 394]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Our routes |url=http://ctplus.org/ct_plus/red_bus_routes_20 |website=CT plus |accessdate=4 July 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704132129/http://ctplus.org/ct_plus/red_bus_routes_20 |archivedate=4 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Walthamstow Avenue (AW)====\nIn November 2016, CT Plus opened a second garage in [[Walthamstow]].<ref>[https://cbwmagazine.com/ct-plus-opens-new-walthamstow-garage/ CT Plus opens new Walthamstow garage] ''[[Coach & Bus Week]]'' 2 December 2016</ref> As of March 2019, Walthamstow Avenue operates routes 20, 385, 397, W11, W12, W16 and W19.\n\n====History====\nIn 2001, CT Plus began operating its [[Transport for London]] contracted service, [[London Buses route 153|route 153]].<ref>[http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/the_hct_group_story The HCT Group story] HCT Group</ref> In 2003, it began operating routes [[London Buses route 388|388]] and [[London Buses route 394|394]].\n\n====Other London services====\n*Special Educational Needs Transport, and coach and bus hire, in [[Waltham Forest]]\n*Social services transport in [[Royal Borough of Kensington & Chelsea|Kensington & Chelsea]]\n*Day Centre & Special Educational Needs Transport in [[London Borough of Lambeth|Lambeth]]\n*Special Educational Needs Transport in [[London Borough of Southwark|Southwark]]\n*Impact Group, purchased from [[Tower Transit]] August 2018<ref>\"Impact acquired by HCT Group\" ''Coach & Bus Week'' issue 1355 15 August 2018 page 7</ref><ref>[http://www.route-one.net/articles/Business_deals/HCT_Group_purchases_Impact_as_it_grows_again HCT Group purchases Impact as it grows again] ''Route One'' 15 August 2018</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hctgroup.org/1417/HCT+Group+acquires+west+London+operator+Impact+Group/about_us/hct_group_news?page=2|title=HCT Group - All the latest news from HCT Group|website=www.hctgroup.org|access-date=2019-07-14}}</ref>\n\n=== Fleet ===\nAs at March 2017, the Transport for London fleet consisted of 120 buses.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Carr|first1=Ken|title=The London Bus Guide|date=May 2015|publisher=Visions International Entertainment|location=Boreham|isbn=978-0-9931735-3-0|page=24|edition=5}}</ref>\n\n==Outside London==\n[[Image:AccessBus in Leeds9.JPG|thumb|AccessBus in [[Leeds]]]]\nHCT also operate a number of community and mainstream bus services outside London. Services include:\n=== West Yorkshire ===\nCT plus (Yorkshire) operate from depots in Wakefield and Leeds,<ref>{{cite web |title=CT PLUS (YORKSHIRE) COMMUNITY INTEREST COMPANY |url=https://www.vehicle-operator-licensing.service.gov.uk/view-details/licence/316558 |website=Vehicle Operator Licensing |accessdate=1 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101094759/https://www.vehicle-operator-licensing.service.gov.uk/view-details/licence/316558 |archivedate=1 January 2019}}</ref> with a fleet of around 110 vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nebula.wsimg.com/34b18440c0c950ff708d657bc2804731?AccessKeyId=8B7A174C4DD908996CD8&disposition=0&alloworigin=1|title=CT Plus Yorkshire|website=Sheffield Omnibus Enthusiasts Society|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101095125/http://nebula.wsimg.com/34b18440c0c950ff708d657bc2804731?AccessKeyId=8B7A174C4DD908996CD8&disposition=0&alloworigin=1|archivedate=1 January 2019|accessdate=1 January 2019}}</ref> The services in Yorkshire consist mostly of [[West Yorkshire Metro]] tendered services: AccessBus, a [[demand responsive transport]] service providing local transport for those unable to use regular transport;<ref>{{cite web |title=AccessBus: The flexible alternative to regular bus services |url=https://www.wymetro.com/buses/rural-services/accessbus/ |website=Metro |accessdate=1 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101100736/https://www.wymetro.com/buses/rural-services/accessbus/ |archivedate=1 January 2019}}</ref> and school buses, including some '[[My bus]]' [[School bus yellow|yellow]] [[school bus]] contracts.<ref>{{cite web |title=My Bus: School buses in Leeds and Wakefield |url=http://www.ctplusyorks.org/my_bus |website=CT plus Yorkshire |accessdate=15 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215121548/http://www.ctplusyorks.org/my_bus |archivedate=15 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A few public routes are operated, around Wakefield, Pontefract and South Elmsall.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bus services |url=http://www.ctplusyorks.org/bus_services_7 |website=CT Plus Yorkshire |accessdate=1 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101095733/http://www.ctplusyorks.org/bus_services_7 |archivedate=1 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=CT Plus (Yorkshire) |url=https://bustimes.org/operators/ct-plus-yorkshire |website=Bus Times |accessdate=15 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215121249/https://bustimes.org/operators/ct-plus-yorkshire |archivedate=15 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, some private contracts are operated, including two shuttle services for the NHS.<ref>{{cite web |title=CT Plus Yorkshire wins Doncaster NHS Shuttle |url=http://www.hctgroup.org/the_hct_group/ct_plus_yorkshire/yorskshire_news/645/CT%20Plus%20Yorkshire%20wins%20Doncaster%20NHS%20Shuttle |website=CT Plus Yorkshire |accessdate=1 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101100055/http://www.hctgroup.org/the_hct_group/ct_plus_yorkshire/yorskshire_news/645/CT%20Plus%20Yorkshire%20wins%20Doncaster%20NHS%20Shuttle |archivedate=1 January 2019}}</ref> \n=== Elsewhere ===\n*[[Manchester Community Transport]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester Community Transport joins HCT Group |url=http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/609/Manchester%20Community%20Transport%20joins%20HCT%20Group |website=HCT group news |accessdate=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n*Powells Bus, [[South Yorkshire]], acquired July 2018<ref>[http://www.route-one.net/articles/Bus_routes/Debut_purchase__HCT_Group_buys_South_Yorks_Powells_Bus Debut purchase: HCT Group buys South Yorks Powells Bus] ''Route One'' 25 July 2018</ref><ref>[https://www.busandcoachbuyer.com/hct-group-acquires-powells-bus/ HCT Group acquires Powells Bus] ''Bus & Coach Buyer'' 1 August 2018</ref>\n*Routes 505, 506, 511 and 512, branded Bristol Community Transport, under contract to [[Bristol City Council]], from 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bristolcommunitytransport.org.uk/bus_services_5|title=Bus services|website=Bristol Community Transport|language=en|access-date=21 July 2018}}</ref> Since January 2019 Bristol Community Transport operate route m1 of [[MetroBus (Bristol)|Bristol Metrobus]], using 21 [[biogas]]-powered buses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/630/Bristol%20Community%20Transport%20unveiled%20as%20Metrobus%20m1%20operator|title=Bristol Community Transport unveiled as Metrobus m1 operator|website=HCT Group|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214062728/http://hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/630/Bristol%20Community%20Transport%20unveiled%20as%20Metrobus%20m1%20operator|archivedate=14 December 2018|accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Guernsey]] public bus services, branded as [[buses.gg]] <ref>[http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/247/CT%20Plus%20begins%20Guernsey%20operations%20 HCT Group \u00a6 Social Enterprise bus operator \u00a6 - All the latest news from HCT Group<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> \n*[[Jersey]] public bus services, branded as [[LibertyBus]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://libertybus.je/about/social_enterprise|title=Who are LibertyBus|website=Liberty Bus|access-date=11 December 2018}}</ref>\n*Derbyshire Community Transport<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.derbyshirect.org/|title=Derbyshire Community Transport - Derbyshire Community Transport|website=www.derbyshirect.org|access-date=2019-07-14}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Former operations ===\n\n* [[Park and ride]] bus service in [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], 2010 to 2014<ref>[http://www.thisishullandeastriding.co.uk/news/London-based-group-wins-Hull-park-ride-deal/article-1340517-detail/article.html London group wins Hull park and ride deal] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120913181616/http://www.thisishullandeastriding.co.uk/news/London-based-group-wins-Hull-park-ride-deal/article-1340517-detail/article.html |date=13 September 2012 }} on thisishullandeastriding.co.uk news website, retrieved 1 October 2009</ref><ref name=CB_Hull_Withdrawal>{{Cite web|url=https://cbwmagazine.com/stagecoach-improve-hull-park-ride/|title=Stagecoach improve Hull Park & Ride|date=6 October 2014|website=Coach & Bus Week|language=en-GB|access-date=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Community transport services==\n[[Image:Special needs education transport services in Waltham Forest0.JPG|thumb|[[Special needs]] education transport services in [[Waltham Forest]]]]\nHCT operates:<ref>[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=42 Community transport services] on HCT Group website, retrieved 1 October 2009</ref>\n*[[accessible]] [[minibus]]es for community and voluntary groups\n*'Capital Call' a door-to-door service provided by [[Minicab|Private hire vehicle]]s for users with mobility difficulties\n*'ScootAbility' [[mobility scooter]] home delivery service\n*'PlusBus' bus service for those who have difficulty accessing mainstream transport\n*'Door 2 Door' transport service provided by volunteers for [[London Borough of Hackney|Hackney]] residents\n*'Integrated Transport Solutions' transport [[contract management]] service\n*'YourCar' a door-to-door service for registered users with mobility difficulties in the London Boroughs of [[London Borough of Lambeth|Lambeth]] and [[London Borough of Southwark|Southwark]]\n\n==Education and training==\nHCT provides [[education]] services supported by the [[Learning and Skills Council]] and the [[London Development Agency]]. The courses include [[bus driver]] training, particularly for [[women]]; [[social care]] and [[management]].<ref>''[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=5 Our Learning Centre]'' on company website, retrieved 4 January 2011</ref>\n\n==Social enterprise and transport==\n[[Image:My bus at Bingley.jpg|thumb|[[West Yorkshire Metro]] [[My bus]] school bus service operated by CT Plus in [[Bingley]]]]\n[[File:CT Plus Guernsey Bus.jpg|thumb|An [[East Lancashire Coachbuilders|ELC bodied]] bus on [[Guernsey]] in November 2015]]\nThe British government has promoted the delivery of public services by [[not for profit]] organisations (the [[Voluntary sector|third sector]]).<ref name=\"AGENDA ITEM NO 16\">[https://www.wypta.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/D92FD985-A09D-4FE4-A764-6ABFFC930E2A/0/PTA21NOVEMBER2008ITEM16.pdf AGENDA ITEM NO: 16. SUBJECT: COMMUNITY TRANSPORT] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002082239/https://www.wypta.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/D92FD985-A09D-4FE4-A764-6ABFFC930E2A/0/PTA21NOVEMBER2008ITEM16.pdf |date=2 October 2011 }} on [[West Yorkshire Metro]] website, retrieved 9 October 2009</ref> British prime minister [[David Cameron]] has stated that he wants more social enterprises running public services as part of his \"[[Big Society]]\".<ref name=\"socialist\"/>\n\nCharitable legal website ''Get Legal'' described HCT's [[corporate structure]] as allowing HCT Group to \"separate the risks associated with its business in different [[limited liability]] [[Legal personality|vehicle]]s. The social mission of each of those vehicles is protected (either through [[charitable status]] or through being [[community interest company|CIC]]s) which sends a clear message to the public that the organisation is a social enterprise''.<ref>''[http://www.getlegal.org.uk/resources/case-studies/hackney-community-transport.html HCT Group case study] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100802222603/http://www.getlegal.org.uk/resources/case-studies/hackney-community-transport.html |date=2 August 2010 }} on ''Get Legal'' website, retrieved 4 January 2011</ref>\n\nHCT says it aims to \"demonstrate and promote the social enterprise [[business model]] as a highly effective and [[socially responsible]] mechanism\", and that it maintains [[Environmental policy|environmental]], [[health and safety]] and [[social policy|social policies]], and regularly measures its performance against these.<ref>''[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=7 Corporate responsibility]'' on Group website, retrieved 4 January 2011</ref> Profit is seen by company CEO Dai Powell as enabling its social goals: \"You have to be an enterprise first, because if you don't make a profit, you can't fulfil that social mission.\".<ref name=\"ambassadors\">{{cite web|url=http://socialenterpriseambassadors.org.uk/ambassador/dai-powell |title=Profile of Dai Powell on socialenterpriseambassadors.org website |date=4 January 2011 |archivedate=1 August 2011 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110801000436/http://socialenterpriseambassadors.org.uk/ambassador/dai-powell }}</ref> HCTs commercial services allowed it to invest 18 per cent of its annual profits into non-commercial [[community transport]] in 2007/08. Its mission was to increase this to 30 per cent in the subsequent five years.<ref name=\"ambassadors\"/>\n\nHCT only competes for contracts that have high levels of [[accessibility]] and quality in the specification.<ref name=\"action plan\"/> \"HCT sees the provision of high-quality [[public services]] as a goal in itself...and actively seeks user input into the design and delivery of all its services\".<ref name=\"action plan\">''[http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20101213144151/http:/www.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/media/cabinetoffice/third_sector/assets/se_action_plan_2006.pdf Social enterprise action plan: Scaling New Heights]'', British cabinet paper, retrieved 8 October 2009</ref> The CEO claims \"we don't provide poor services for poor people \u2013 the quality has to be there\u201d.<ref name=\"ambassadors\"/> HCT recruits [[Volunteering|volunteers]] to train people with [[learning disabilities|learning difficulties]] and [[physical disabilities]] to use public transport independently.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719103731/http://www.bassac.org.uk/members/work-of-members/working-with-volunteers|url=http://www.bassac.org.uk/members/work-of-members/working-with-volunteers|title= Engaging the unemployed in a volunteer led community service - HCT Group|author=British Association of Settlements and Social Action Centres website|date=4 January 2011|archivedate=19 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[West Yorkshire Metro]] noted that a community transport provider \"...spends its surpluses on transport services in the community which are not commissioned from public bodies\" but that \"Commissioning from the sector can however carry risks...organisations can lack capability and professionalism and be over reliant on individuals leading to instability\".<ref name=\"AGENDA ITEM NO 16\"/>\n\nHCT Group is no more immune to [[labour relations]] problems than any other bus operator.<ref>see for example [http://www.wrp.org.uk/news/3227 40 BUS WORKERS PICKET ASH GROVE] on [[Workers Revolutionary Party (UK)|Workers Revolutionary Party]] news website, and [http://archive.unitetheunion.org/news__events/archived_news_releases/2008_archived_press_releases/london_bus_workers_at_hackney.aspx London bus workers at Hackney to strike over dismissal of shop steward] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131217221331/http://archive.unitetheunion.org/news__events/archived_news_releases/2008_archived_press_releases/london_bus_workers_at_hackney.aspx |date=17 December 2013 }} on [[Unite the union]] news website; both retrieved 10 October 2009</ref> The ''[[Socialist Worker]]'' described HCT as \"no friend of workers\" and its workers as \"some of the lowest paid drivers in London\".<ref name=\"socialist\">'[http://www.socialistworker.co.uk/art.php?id=22694 East London bus drivers picket bosses over pay]' on ''[[Socialist Worker]]'' website, retrieved 6 January 2011</ref>\n\nHCT Group prefers social enterprises and co-ops as [[business partner]]s and suppliers;<ref>'[https://www.theguardian.com/social-enterprise-network/2011/oct/17/social-enterprises-co-ops-business-partners?newsfeed=true Why we prefer social enterprises and co-ops as business partners]' on ''[[The Guardian]]'' website, viewed 19 October 2011</ref> when they raised \u00a3500k [[impact investing|impact investment]] from the Phone Co-Op in 2014, their CEO explained with investors as well as suppliers they want to \"buy social\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anca|first1=Voinea|title=The Phone Co-op invests in public transport social enterprise|url=http://www.thenews.coop/92351/news/community/the-phone-co-op-invests-in-public-transport-social-enterprise/|website=The News Co-Op|accessdate=10 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, HCT Group secured \u00a317.8 million in funding to tackle social isolation, with the help of the investment bank ClearlySo. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukbaa.org.uk/news/clearlyso-helps-hct-group-secure-17-8-million-in-funding-to-tackle-social-isolation/|title=ClearlySo helps HCT Group secure \u00a317.8 million in funding to tackle social isolation {{!}} UK Business Angels Association (UKBAA)|last=|first=|date=|website=UK Business Angels Association|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Dai Powell.jpg|thumb|150px|Dai Powel, the [[CEO]] of HCT Group, formerly a coal miner in [[Wales]],<ref name=\"ft\"/> joined as a bus cleaner in 1990<ref name=\"origins\"/>]]\n\n''Hackney Community Transport'' was established in 1982 when 30 community groups in the [[London Borough of Hackney]] formed a pool of six vehicles with a grant from [[Hackney Borough Council]] to provide low cost [[van]] and [[minibus]] [[rental car|hire]] for local community groups, and a [[door to door]] alternative to [[public transport]] for [[people with disabilities]].<ref name=\"origins\"/> The company's services were staffed by [[Volunteering|volunteers]],<ref name=\"origins\">[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=12 Origins] on HCT Group website, retrieved 18 October 2009</ref> but over the next decade a small group of [[employee|paid staff]] built up to assist the volunteer workforce.<ref>[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=13 1986 - 1996] on HCT Group website, retrieved 18 October 2009</ref>\n\nHCT Group received loans from London Rebuilding Society to finance its entry to the bus industry.<ref name=\"rebuilding\">[http://www.londonrebuilding.com/information/89713/90262/91013/90539/hct_group/ HCT Group] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908055447/http://www.londonrebuilding.com/information/89713/90262/91013/90539/hct_group/ |date=8 September 2008 }} on http://www.londonrebuilding.com website, retrieved 8 October 2009</ref>\n\nIn 2004 HCT was contracted by EduAction to deliver 500 local [[special needs]] children to school and back each day for [[London Borough of Waltham Forest]] from a new depot in [[Leyton]].<ref name=\"2004 - 2005\">[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=18 2004 - 2005] on HCT Group website, retrieved 19 October 2009</ref>\n\nIn March 2006 HCT expanded outside London to run eight [[school bus yellow|yellow]] ''My bus'' school transport routes in and around [[City of Wakefield|Wakefield]] for [[West Yorkshire Metro]]. A further seven runs were added in September<ref name=\"2006 page\">[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=82 2006] on HCT Group website, retrieved 19 October 2009</ref> and three more in September 2007.<ref name=\"2007 page\">[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=92 2007] on HCT Group website, retrieved 19 October 2009</ref>\n\nIn July 2006 HCT merged with Lambeth & Southwark Community Transport.<ref name=\"2006 page\"/>\n\nOn 1 October 2006 HCT began to operate the AccessBus service in [[Leeds]]<ref name=\"2006 page\"/> and in 2008, merged with Leeds Alternative Travel.<ref name=\"2008 page\">[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?sectionid=117 2008] on HCT Group website, retrieved 19 October 2009</ref>\n\nIn March 2009, HCT Group published its first Impact Report.<ref>''[http://www.hctgroup.org/index.php?type=ARTICLE&articleid=41 HCT Group publishes its first Impact Report]'' on group website, retrieved 4 January 2011</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, CT Plus Yorkshire took over the [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] 701 Priory Park & Ride route,<ref>''[http://hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/33/Commencement%20of%20Hull%20Priory%20Park%20and%20Ride%20service Commencement of Hull Priory Park Park and Ride service]'' on group website, retrieved 4 January 2011</ref> with the aim of investing any surplus from its park-and-ride operation to expand a local community transport service and to set up training for long-term unemployed people in Hull.<ref>''[http://www.thisishullandeastriding.co.uk/news/Park-ride-firm-HCT-focusing-community/article-1879465-detail/article.html Park-and-ride firm HCT is focusing on the community]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}'' on ''[[Hull Daily Mail]]'' website, retrieved 4 January 2011</ref> This was withdrawn in 2014, with Stagecoach taking over the service.<ref name=\"CB_Hull_Withdrawal\" />\n\nIn February 2010, HCT Group raised \u00a35 million via a social loan.<ref name=\"ft\"/> By 2010 HCT had grown by over a hundredfold since 1993 \u2013 from a turnover of \u00a3202k to a turnover of \u00a323.3m in 2009/10.<ref name=\"scale\">'[https://www.theguardian.com/social-enterprise-network/2011/feb/28/lessons-race-scale-htc?INTCMP=SRCH Our lessons from the race for scale]' on ''[[The Guardian]]'' website, retrieved 7 March 2011</ref>\n\nIn 2017 and 2018, the group completed a series of acquisitions, purchasing Social Access, Bristol;<ref>{{cite web |title=Social Access joins the HCT Group |url=http://hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/590/Social%20Access%20joins%20the%20HCT%20Group |website=HCT Group News |accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> [[Manchester Community Transport]];<ref>{{cite web |title=Manchester Community Transport joins HCT Group |url=http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/609/Manchester%20Community%20Transport%20joins%20HCT%20Group |website=HCT Group News |accessdate=15 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181211010525/http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/609/Manchester%20Community%20Transport%20joins%20HCT%20Group |archivedate=11 December 2018}}</ref> CT4TC,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |title=CT4TC joins HCT Group |url=http://hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/628/CT4TC%20joins%20HCT%20Group |website=HCT Group News |accessdate=15 December 2018}}</ref> a Derbyshire community transport operator, since renamed Derbyshire Community Transport;<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |title=CT4TC announces its new name - Derbyshire Community Transport |url=http://hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/633/CT4TC%20announces%20its%20new%20name%20-%20Derbyshire%20Community%20Transport |website=HCT Group News}}</ref> Powells, South Yorkshire;<ref>{{cite web |title=HCT Group acquire Powells Bus |url=http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/639/HCT%20Group%20acquire%20Powells%20Bus |website=HCT Group News |accessdate=15 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215141751/http://www.hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/639/HCT%20Group%20acquire%20Powells%20Bus |archivedate=15 December 2018}}</ref> and Impact Group, West London.<ref>{{cite web |title=HCT Group acquires west London operator Impact Group |url=http://hctgroup.org/about_us/hct_group_news/643/HCT%20Group%20acquires%20west%20London%20operator%20Impact%20Group |website=HCT Group News}}</ref>\n==Corporate strategy==\n[[Image:Social services transport in Kensington and Chelsea.jpg|thumb|[[Social services]] transport in [[Royal Borough of Kensington & Chelsea|Kensington & Chelsea]]]]\nHCT Group's [[corporate strategy]] is to generate [[Profit (accounting)|profit]]s from providing commercial transport services, then to use these profits to provide community transport services for people unable to use mainstream transport. The two modes, [[public transport]] and special need transport, are fully integrated under their model: \"the investment in responsive community transport services is made possible by running the commercial activity well\".<ref name=\"action plan\"/> The ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported in 2010 that [[revenue|turnover]] had \"grown by about 25 per cent a year for the past eight years and is expected to top \u00a320m in the year to March 31, 2010, when profits will be around \u00a31m.\".<ref name=ft>''[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/41e6c628-1f11-11df-9584-00144feab49a.html#axzz1A38EItsw \u2018Social loan\u2019 for cause-based groups]'' on ''[[Financial Times]]'' website, retrieved 4 January 2011</ref> HCT's rapid growth is achieved by merging with smaller community transport organisations.<ref name=\"ambassadors\"/>\n\nHCT Group [[CEO]] Dai Powell, in an article explaining the group's strategy,<ref name=\"scale\"/> said the business aims to double in size every five or so years for the foreseeable future, seeing scale as ''...crucial. The better we do commercially, the more we can do for the communities we serve as a social enterprise''. The strategy is ''maximising the good that we do... to be as bold as a commercial firm, but to the benefit of our communities, not to the owners of [[capital (economics)|capital]]. It also has the advantage of keeping our social mission absolutely central to our approach''. Powell contrasted this approach to that of many [[Voluntary sector|third sector]] organisations ''where [[risk]] is to be mitigated at worst and eliminated at best. This is simply hopeless for rapid growth.'' He describes the process as ''...so much more rewarding than spending your days \"maximising [[shareholder value]]\", whatever that means.<ref name=\"scale\"/>''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website}}\n*[http://bristolcommunitytransport.org.uk/ Bristol Community Transport]\n*[http://ctplus.org/ CT Plus, London]\n*