s previously served as defensive coordinator at [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]], [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]], [[Penn State Nittany Lions football|Penn State]], and [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]].<ref>[https://www.ncaa.com/stats/football/fbs/current/team/22/p3]</ref>  Shoop served as the head football coach at [[Columbia University]] from 2003 to 2005.\n\n==Playing career==\nShoop is a 1988 graduate of [[Yale University]] and both played and coached under [[Carmen Cozza]]. In his senior year, he was an honorable mention selection to the 1987 All-[[Ivy League]] team. In 1988, and the early part of 1989, Shoop played in the [[United Kingdom]] for the [[Birmingham Bulls (American football)|Birmingham Bulls]].<ref>[http://www.britballnow.co.uk/history-index/list-of-britball-teams/birmingham-bulls.html]</ref>\n\nShoop pitched for the Yale Bulldogs baseball team. He earned four [[varsity letter]]s and twice won the [[Ducky Pond|Raymond W. (Ducky) Pond Pitching Award]] for outstanding pitching.\n\n==Coaching career==\nHe served as an assistant coach at Yale and as defensive coordinator from 1994 to 1996.  He was hired by [[Tom O'Brien (American football)|Tom O'Brien]] at [[Boston College]] in 1999.\n\nIn 2003, Shoop was hired by [[Columbia University]] with the hopes that he would turn around the struggling program.  He was fired shortly after the end of the 2005 with a record of 7\u201323 in his three seasons with the team.  His 2005 team went winless in the [[Ivy League]] and he never finished above 6th place.\n\nFrom 2007 to 2010, Shoop served as the defensive coordinator at [[College of William & Mary|William & Mary]].  On January 31, 2011, he was named as the defensive coordinator for the [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt Commodores]], under new head coach [[James Franklin (American football coach)|James Franklin]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://espn.go.com/blog/sec/post/_/id/19515/franklin-announces-defensive-staff| title=Franklin announces defensive staff| work=ESPN| author=Low, Chris| date=January 31, 2011| accessdate=February 1, 2011}}</ref>  He followed Franklin to Penn State to be in the same capacity for the beginning of the 2014 season.\n\nOn January 9, 2016, Shoop was announced as the defensive coordinator for the [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee Volunteers]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/college/ut/2016/01/09/tennessee-vols-bob-shoop-defensive-coordinator/78573044/| title=Vols name Bob Shoop defensive coordinator| work=The Tennessean| author=The Tenneessean| date=January 9, 2016| accessdate=January 9, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn December 10, 2017, Shoop was announced as the defensive coordinator for [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Joe Moorhead Announces Hiring of Bob Shoop, Marcus Johnson |url=https://hailstate.com/news/2017/12/10/football-joe-moorhead-announces-hiring-of-bob-shoop-marcus-johnson.aspx |website=HailState.com |publisher=Mississippi State University Athletics |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 20, 2020, Shoop was named the new safeties coach for [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Jean-Mary, Shoop Added to Defensive Staff; Harbaugh Named Special Teams Coordinator |url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2020/1/18/football-jean-mary-shoop-added-to-defensive-staff-harbaugh-named-special-teams-coordinator.aspx |website=MGoBlue.com |publisher=Board of Regents of the University of Michigan |accessdate=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nBob's brother, [[John Shoop]], is a former [[offensive coordinator]] for [[Purdue University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.purduesports.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/john_shoop_837375.html |title=John Shoop Bio |publisher=Purdue University |work=www.purduesports.com |accessdate=December 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | 