{"title_page": "Bob Polk", "text_new": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Bob Polk\n| image = Bob_Polk_SLU.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Polk from the 1970 ''Archive''\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1915|02|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Tell City, Indiana]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1986|03|18|1915|9|2}}\n| death_place = [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1936\u20131939\n| player_team1 = [[Evansville Purple Aces men's basketball|Evansville]]\n| coach_years1 = 1939\u20131943\n| coach_team1 = [[Tell City High School|Tell City HS]] (assistant)\n| coach_years2 = 1943\u20131947\n| coach_team2 = [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball|Georgia Tech]] (assistant)\n| coach_years3 = 1947\u20131961\n| coach_team3 = [[Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball|Vanderbilt]]\n| coach_years4 = 1965\u20131969\n| coach_team4 = [[Trinity Tigers men's basketball|Trinity (TX)]]\n| coach_years5 = 1969\u20131974\n| coach_team5 = [[Saint Louis Billikens men's basketball|Saint Louis]]\n| coach_years6 = 1974\u20131977\n| coach_team6 = [[Rice Owls men's basketball|Rice]]\n| overall_record = 355\u2013190\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = NCAA College Division Regional (1968)<br/>[[SEC Men's Basketball Tournament|SEC Tournament]] (1951)<br/>2 [[Southland Conference|Southland]] regular  season (1967, 1969)<br/>[[Missouri Valley Conference|MVC]] (1970)\n| awards = NCAA College Division Coach of the Year (1969)<br/>2\u00d7 [[Southland Conference|Southland]] Coach of the Year (1967, 1969)<br/>[[Missouri Valley Conference Men's Basketball Coach of the Year|MVC Coach of the Year]] (1970)\n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''James Robert Polk''' (February 28, 1915 \u2013 March 18, 1986) was an American [[basketball]] coach. Polk coached the [[Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball|Vanderbilt Commodores]], the [[Trinity Tigers]],<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/trinity-tx/|title=Trinity (TX) Tigers Index &#124; College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref> the [[Saint Louis Billikens men's basketball|Saint Louis Billikens]]<ref name=\"sports-reference2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/saint-louis/coaches.html|title=Saint Louis Billikens Coaches &#124; College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref> and [[Rice Owls men's basketball|Rice University]].<ref name=\"sports-reference3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/rice/coaches.html|title=Rice Owls Coaches &#124; College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref>    He began his college coaching career as an assistant coach a [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball|Georgia Tech]] during World War II. His first coaching job was at his high school ''alma mater'' [[Tell City#Schools|Tell City High]], in [[Tell City, Indiana]].\n\n==Early life==\nPolk was born in [[Tell City, Indiana]] and began to play basketball in the 4th grade. After high school, Polk attended the [[University of Evansville]] from 1936 to 1939. He worked part-time at several jobs, including sweeping out the University President's office, running a movie projector, bank teller and working in a tomato canning factory.<ref name=\"evpl\">{{cite web|url=http://local.evpl.org/views/viewimage.asp?ID=675617|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203131758/http://local.evpl.org/views/viewimage.asp?ID=675617 |archive-date=2014-02-03 |url-status=dead|title=View Image|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref> to help pay his college expenses. He was a guard on the basketball team under long-time Purple Aces' coach [[Bill Slyker]] from 1935-36 to 1938\u201339.\n\nIn Polk's sophomore season (1935\u201336), Evansille finished 11\u20137. This would mark the best season for the Purple Aces during Polk's college playing career.\n\n==High school coaching==\nPolk began his career in coaching by accepting a teaching and coaching job at his alma mater Tell City High School, Tell City, Indiana. Polk had graduated only 8&nbsp;years earlier (1931) after leading the Marksmen to their fifth [[Indiana High School Athletic Association|IHSAA]] Sectional title.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pastbb.homestead.com/files/history330.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-02-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128232422/http://pastbb.homestead.com/files/history330.htm |archive-date=2018-01-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Polk assisted Ivan Hollen, who also began that season, replacing future Purdue Boilermakers' Head Coach [[Ray Eddy]].\n\n==College coaching==\nAfter a four-year tenure, Polk joined the U.S. Navy, he was assigned as a physical education instructor at Georgia Tech in the Navy's [[V-12 Navy College Training Program|V-12 Program]], he also assisted Georgia Tech head coach Dwayne Keith during the 1943\u201344 and 1944-45 seasons. After the war, Georgia Tech hired him as their assistant basketball coach.\n\nIn 1943, he enlisted in the US Navy and was assigned as a physical education instructor at [[Georgia Institute of Technology]], he spent the 1943\u201344 and 1944-45 seasons as a Georgia Tech assistant to Dwayne Keith in addition to his US Navy duties, after the war ended he was hired in the same capacity by Georgia Tech.\n\nIn February 1947, Vanderbilt was pummeled by the Kentucky Wildcats in the SEC Tournament 98-29, the Commodores Athletic Director (and football coach) Red Sanders decided to upgrade the basketball program by hiring a full-time coach and offering scholarships. His search led him to Bob Polk (another candidate who was interviewed for the job was the future legend, [[John Wooden]], who had led his [[Indiana State Sycamores men's basketball|Indiana State Sycamores]] to a conference title and an invitation from the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]].\n\n===Vanderbilt===\nPolk coached the [[Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball|Vanderbilt Commodores]] from 1947 to 1961.  There, he won the 1951\u201352 SEC Tournament. Polk's Vanderbilt teams recorded one losing season in 13 seasons and finished 2nd in the SEC on four occasions. His 1954-55, 1955\u201356 and 1956\u201357 squads all finished the season in the Top 20 [[Associated Press]] poll.<ref name=\"sports-reference4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/vanderbilt/|title=Vanderbilt Commodores Index &#124; College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref>\n\nIn his 13 seasons as Vanderbilt coach, Polk mined the rich Southwestern Indiana talent fields to build a consistent winner; players such as SEC First Team members Dave Kardokus (1951) and SEC Second team members Billy Joe Adcock (1948\u201350), Al Weiss (1951), Bob Dudley Smith (1951) and Dave Kardokus. Heart problems forced Polk to resign after the 1960-61 season. When he left, Polk was the leader in wins for the Commodores (197-106 .650) and had won the 1951&nbsp;SEC Tourney.\n\nSix of his players were drafted by NBA teams; \n* Bill Depp \u2013 1961 3rd round Boston  \n* Jim Henry \u2013 1959 6th round  Minneapolis   \n* Al Rochelle \u2013 1957 5th round St. Louis    \n* Dan Finch \u2013 1954 Minneapolis   \n* George Kelley \u2013 1951 Indianapolis   \n* Billy Joe Adcock \u2013 1950 Fort Wayne \n<ref name=\"basketball-reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/friv/draft.cgi?college=vandy|title=NBA Draft Picks From Vanderbilt University &#124; Basketball-Reference.com|publisher=basketball-reference.com|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref>\n\n===Trinity===\nPolk recovered quickly from his heart attack and accepted the head coaching and athletic director position at [[Trinity University (Texas)|Trinity University]] in San Antonio, Texas. Polk quickly turned the Tigers into a power, leading them from the depths of the [[Southland Conference]] to the title in four seasons; he was named the Southland Conference Coach-of-the-Year in 1967 following a record of 16-6. His 1967-68 team was even better, the Tigers racked up a record of 23-7 and advanced to the [[1968 NCAA Men's Division II Basketball Tournament|NCAA College Division Tournament]], where the Tigers finished 3rd overall. He was also the NCAA National Coach-of-the-Year for the College Division (today's NCAA Div II) in 1968. In his four years at Trinity, Polk compiled a 70-28 record, a Southland title and a National 3rd-place finish. He was chiefly responsible for the Tigers moving to NCAA Division I classification, however, today they are a NCAA Div III school.\n\n===Saint Louis===\nFollowing his successful tenure at Trinity, Polk accepted the head coaching job at [[Saint Louis University]]; he was the 16th head coach in Billikens history and quickly turned around the program.<ref>http://local.evpl.org/views/viewimage.asp?ID=675688</ref>  In his 2nd season, he led them to a share of the [[Missouri Valley Conference]] championship and was named the Conference's Coach of the Year.<ref name=\"evpl2\">{{cite web|url=http://local.evpl.org/views/viewimage.asp?ID=675698|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221134130/http://local.evpl.org/views/viewimage.asp?ID=675698 |archive-date=2014-02-21 |url-status=dead|title=View Image|accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref>  While at St Louis, he sent two players to the NBA; Harry \u201cTree\u201d Rogers  and Robin Jones.<ref name=\"basketball-reference2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/friv/draft.cgi?college=stlouis|title=NBA Draft Picks From Saint Louis University &#124; Basketball-Reference.com|publisher=basketball-reference.com|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref>\n\n===Rice===\nIn a return to bigger conference, he accepted the head coaching position at Rice after five seasons at Saint Louis.  However, he was unable to duplicate the earlier success he enjoyed at Vanderbilt.  Polk served as the President of the National Association of Basketball Coaches during the 197475 season.\n\n==UAB==\nIn April 1977, Polk resigned from Rice and accepted a position as the assistant athletic director at the [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]] (UAB). He retired from that position in 1977. He hired [[Gene Bartow]] to build the men's basketball program.\n\n==Death==\nPolk died of heart disease at age 71 in [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee]], on March 18, 1986. He is buried in [[Tell City, Indiana]]. He was memorialized by his induction into the Tennessee Sports Hall of Fame in 1990.\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start|\n|type=coach\n|postseason\n|poll=no\n|conference\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n|name=Vanderbilt Commodores\n|startyear=1947\n|conference=[[Southeastern Conference]]\n|endyear=1961\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1947\u201348\n | name         =Vanderbilt\n | overall      =8\u201314\n | conference   =4\u201311\n | confstanding =12th\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1948\u201349\n | name         =Vanderbilt\n | overall      =14\u20138\n | conference   =9\u20135\n | confstanding =4th\n | championship =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1949\u201350\n | name         = Vanderbilt\n | overall      =17\u20138\n | conference   =11\u20133\n | confstanding =2nd\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1950\u201351\n | name         = Vanderbilt\n | overall      =19\u20138\n | conference   =10\u20134\n | confstanding =T\u20132nd\n | championship =conference tournament\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1951\u201352\n | name         = Vanderbilt\n | overall      =18\u20139\n | conference   =9\u20135\n | confstanding =T\u20132nd\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1952\u201353\n | name         =Vanderbilt\n | overall      =10\u20139\n | conferen