 the Year navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Polk, Bob}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball coaches from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Indiana]]\n[[Category:College men's basketball head coaches in the United States]]\n[[Category:Evansville Purple Aces men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:High school basketball coaches in Indiana]]\n[[Category:High school basketball coaches in the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Tell City, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Rice Owls men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Saint Louis Billikens men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Trinity Tigers men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:V-12 Navy College Training Program]]\n[[Category:Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball coaches]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Bob Polk\n| image = Bob_Polk_SLU.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Polk from the 1970 ''Archive''\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1915|02|28}}\n| birth_place = [[Tell City, Indiana]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1986|03|18|1915|9|2}}\n| death_place = [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1936\u20131939\n| player_team1 = [[Evansville Purple Aces men's basketball|Evansville]]\n| coach_years1 = 1939\u20131943\n| coach_team1 = [[Tell City High School|Tell City HS]] (assistant)\n| coach_years2 = 1943\u20131947\n| coach_team2 = [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball|Georgia Tech]] (assistant)\n| coach_years3 = 1947\u20131961\n| coach_team3 = [[Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball|Vanderbilt]]\n| coach_years4 = 1965\u20131969\n| coach_team4 = [[Trinity Tigers men's basketball|Trinity (TX)]]\n| coach_years5 = 1969\u20131974\n| coach_team5 = [[Saint Louis Billikens men's basketball|Saint Louis]]\n| coach_years6 = 1974\u20131977\n| coach_team6 = [[Rice Owls men's basketball|Rice]]\n| overall_record = 355\u2013190\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = NCAA College Division Regional (1968)<br/>[[SEC Men's Basketball Tournament|SEC Tournament]] (1951)<br/>2 [[Southland Conference|Southland]] regular  season (1967, 1969)<br/>[[Missouri Valley Conference|MVC]] (1970)\n| awards = NCAA College Division Coach of the Year (1969)<br/>2\u00d7 [[Southland Conference|Southland]] Coach of the Year (1967, 1969)<br/>[[Missouri Valley Conference Men's Basketball Coach of the Year|MVC Coach of the Year]] (1970)\n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''James Robert Polk''' (February 28, 1915 \u2013 March 18, 1986) was an American [[basketball]] coach. Polk coached the [[Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball|Vanderbilt Commodores]], the [[Trinity Tigers]],<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/trinity-tx/|title=Trinity (TX) Tigers Index &#124; College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref> the [[Saint Louis Billikens men's basketball|Saint Louis Billikens]]<ref name=\"sports-reference2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/saint-louis/coaches.html|title=Saint Louis Billikens Coaches &#124; College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref> and [[Rice Owls men's basketball|Rice University]].<ref name=\"sports-reference3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/rice/coaches.html|title=Rice Owls Coaches &#124; College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref>    He began his college coaching career as an assistant coach a [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball|Georgia Tech]] during World War II. His first coaching job was at his high school ''alma mater'' [[Tell City#Schools|Tell City High]], in [[Tell City, Indiana]].\n\n==Early life==\nPolk was born in [[Tell City, Indiana]] and began to play basketball in the 4th grade. After high school, Polk attended the [[University of Evansville]] from 1936 to 1939. He worked part-time at several jobs, including sweeping out the University President's office, running a movie projector, bank teller and working in a tomato canning factory.<ref name=\"evpl\">{{cite web|url=http://local.evpl.org/views/viewimage.asp?ID=675617|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203131758/http://local.evpl.org/views/viewimage.asp?ID=675617 |archive-date=2014-02-03 |url-status=dead|title=View Image|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref> to help pay his college expenses. He was a guard on the basketball team under long-time Purple Aces' coach [[Bill Slyker]] from 1935-36 to 1938\u201339.\n\nIn Polk's sophomore season (1935\u201336), Evansille finished 11\u20137. This would mark the best season for the Purple Aces during Polk's college playing career.\n\n==High school coaching==\nPolk began his career in coaching by accepting a teaching and coaching job at his alma mater Tell City High School, Tell City, Indiana. Polk had graduated only 8&nbsp;years earlier (1931) after leading the Marksmen to their fifth [[Indiana High School Athletic Association|IHSAA]] Sectional title.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pastbb.homestead.com/files/history330.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-02-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128232422/http://pastbb.homestead.com/files/history330.htm |archive-date=2018-01-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>  Polk assisted Ivan Hollen, who also began that season, replacing future Purdue Boilermakers' Head Coach [[Ray Eddy]].\n\n==College coaching==\nAfter a four-year tenure, Polk joined the U.S. Navy, he was assigned as a physical education instructor at Georgia Tech in the Navy's [[V-12 Navy College Training Program|V-12 Program]], he also assisted Georgia Tech head coach Dwayne Keith during the 1943\u201344 and 1944-45 seasons. After the war, Georgia Tech hired him as their assistant basketball coach.\n\nIn 1943, he enlisted in the US Navy and was assigned as a physical education instructor at [[Georgia Institute of Technology]], he spent the 1943\u201344 and 1944-45 seasons as an Georgia Tech assistant to Dwayne Keith in addition to his US Navy duties, after the war ended he was hired in the same capacity by Georgia Tech.\n\nIn February 1947, Vanderbilt was pummeled by the Kentucky Wildcats in the SEC Tournament 98-29, the Commodores Athletic Director (and football coach) Red Sanders decided to upgrade the basketball program by hiring a full-time coach and offering scholarships. His search led him to Bob Polk (another candidate who was interviewed for the job was the future legend, [[John Wooden]], who had led his [[Indiana State Sycamores men's basketball|Indiana State Sycamores]] to a conference title and an invitation from the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]].\n\n===Vanderbilt===\nPolk coached the [[Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball|Vanderbilt Commodores]] from 1947 to 1961.  There, he won the 1951\u201352 SEC Tournament. Polk's Vanderbilt teams recorded one losing season in 13 seasons and finished 2nd in the SEC on four occasions. His 1954-55, 1955\u201356 and 1956\u201357 squads all finished the season in the Top 20 [[Associated Press]] poll.<ref name=\"sports-reference4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/vanderbilt/|title=Vanderbilt Commodores Index &#124; College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|publisher=sports-reference.com|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref>\n\nIn his 13 seasons as Vanderbilt coach, Polk mined the rich Southwestern Indiana talent fields to build a consistent winner; players such as SEC First Team members Dave Kardokus (1951) and SEC Second team members Billy Joe Adcock (1948\u201350), Al Weiss (1951), Bob Dudley Smith (1951) and Dave Kardokus. Heart problems forced Polk to resign after the 1960-61 season. When he left, Polk was the leader in wins for the Commodores (197-106 .650) and had won the 1951&nbsp;SEC Tourney.\n\nSix of his players were drafted by NBA teams; \n* Bill Depp \u2013 1961 3rd round Boston  \n* Jim Henry \u2013 1959 6th round  Minneapolis   \n* Al Rochelle \u2013 1957 5th round St. Louis    \n* Dan Finch \u2013 1954 Minneapolis   \n* George Kelley \u2013 1951 Indianapolis   \n* Billy Joe Adcock \u2013 1950 Fort Wayne \n<ref name=\"basketball-reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/friv/draft.cgi?college=vandy|title=NBA Draft Picks From Vanderbilt University &#124; Basketball-Reference.com|publisher=basketball-reference.com|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref>\n\n===Trinity===\nPolk recovered quickly from his heart attack and accepted the head coaching and athletic director position at [[Trinity University (Texas)|Trinity University]] in San Antonio, Texas. Polk quickly turned the Tigers into a power, leading them from the depths of the [[Southland Conference]] to the title in four seasons; he was named the Southland Conference Coach-of-the-Year in 1967 following a record of 16-6. His 1967-68 team was even better, the Tigers racked up a record of 23-7 and advanced to the [[1968 NCAA Men's Division II Basketball Tournament|NCAA College Division Tournament]], where the Tigers finished 3rd overall. He was also the NCAA National Coach-of-the-Year for the College Division (today's NCAA Div II) in 1968. In his four years at Trinity, Polk compiled a 70-28 record, a Southland title and a National 3rd-place finish. He was chiefly responsible for the Tigers moving to NCAA Division I classification, however, today they are a NCAA Div III school.\n\n===Saint Louis===\nFollowing his successful tenure at Trinity, Polk accepted the head coaching job at [[Saint Louis University]]; he was the 16th head coach in Billikens history and quickly turned around the program.<ref>http://local.evpl.org/views/viewimage.asp?ID=675688</ref>  In his 2nd season, he led them to a share of the [[Missouri Valley Conference]] championship and was named the Conference's Coach of the Year.<ref name=\"evpl2\">{{cite web|url=http://local.evpl.org/views/viewimage.asp?ID=675698|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221134130/http://local.evpl.org/views/viewimage.asp?ID=675698 |archive-date=2014-02-21 |url-status=dead|title=View Image|accessdate=2014-04-02}}</ref>  While at St Louis, he sent two players to the NBA; Harry \u201cTree\u201d Rogers  and Robin Jones.<ref name=\"basketball-reference2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/friv/draft.cgi?college=stlouis|title=NBA Draft Picks From Saint Louis University &#124; Basketball-Reference.com|publisher=basketball-reference.com|accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref>\n\n===Rice===\nIn a return to bigger conference, he accepted the head coaching position at Rice after five seasons at Saint Louis.  However, he was unable to duplicate the earlier success he enjoyed at Vanderbilt.  Polk served as the President of the National Association of Basketball Coaches during the 197475 season.\n\n==UAB==\nIn April 1977, Polk resigned from Rice and accepted a position as the assistant athletic director at the [[University of Alabama at Birmingham]] (UAB). He retired from that position in 1977. He hired [[Gene Bartow]] to build the men's basketball program.\n\n==Death==\nPolk died of heart disease at age 71 in [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee]], on March 18, 1986. He is buried in [[Tell City, Indiana]]. He was memorialized by his induction into the Tennessee Sports Hall of Fame in 1990.\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start|\n|type=coach\n|postseason\n|poll=no\n|conference\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n|name=Vanderbilt Commodores\n|startyear=1947\n|conference=[[Southeastern Conference]]\n|endyear=1961\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1947\u201348\n | name         =Vanderbilt\n | overall      =8\u201314\n | conference   =4\u201311\n | confstanding =12th\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1948\u201349\n | name         =Vanderbilt\n | overall      =14\u20138\n | conference   =9\u20135\n | confstanding =4th\n | championship =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1949\u201350\n | name         = Vanderbilt\n | overall      =17\u20138\n | conference   =11\u20133\n | confstanding =2nd\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1950\u201351\n | name         = Vanderbilt\n | overall      =19\u20138\n | conference   =10\u20134\n | confstanding =T\u20132nd\n | championship =conference tournament\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1951\u201352\n | name         = Vanderbilt\n | overall      =18\u20139\n | conference   =9\u20135\n | confstanding =T\u20132nd\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1952\u201353\n | name         =Vanderbilt\n | overall      =10\u20139\n | conference   =5\u20138\n | confstanding =T\u20137th\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1953\u201354\n | name         =Vanderbilt\n | overall      =12\u201310\n | conference   =5\u20139\n | confstanding =T\u20138th\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1954\u201355\n | name         =Vanderbilt\n | overall      =16\u20136\n | conference   =9\u20135\n | confstanding =T\u20133rd\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1955\u201356\n | name         =Vanderbilt\n | overall      =16\u20134\n | conference   =5\u20132\n | confstanding =3rd\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1956\u201357\n | name         = Vanderbilt\n | overall      =17\u20135\n | conference   =10\u20134\n | confstanding =T\u20132nd\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1957\u201358\n | name         = Vanderbilt\n | overall      =14\u201311\n | conference   =7\u20137\n | confstanding =7th\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n| season       =1959\u201360\n | name         =Vanderbilt\n | overall      =14\u20139\n | conference   =8\u20136\n | confstanding =T\u20135th\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1960\u201361\n | name         =Vanderbilt\n | overall      =19\u20135\n | conference   =7\u20137\n | confstanding =T\u20136th\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Vanderbilt\n | overall    = 197\u2013106 ({{Winning percentage|197|106}}) \n | confrecord = 105\u201377 ({{Winning percentage|105|77}}) \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n|name=Trinity Tigers\n|startyear=1965\n|conference=[[Southland Conference]]\n|endyear=1969\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1965\u201366\n | name         =Trinity\n | overall      =12\u201310\n | conference   =3\u20135\n | confstanding =4th\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1966\u201367\n | name         =Trinity\n | overall      =16\u20136\n | conference   =4\u20134\n | confstanding =T-1st\n | championship =conference\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1967\u201368\n | name         =Trinity\n | overall      =23\u20137\n | conference   =5\u20133\n | confstanding =2nd\n | championship =\n | postseason  =[[1968 NCAA College Division Men's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Final Four]]\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1968\u201369\n | name         =Trinity\n | overall      =19\u20135\n | conference   =7\u20131\n | confstanding =1st\n | championship =conference\n | postseason   =[[1969 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Regional Quarterfinals]]\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Trinity\n | overall    =70\u201328 ({{Winning percentage|70|28}}) \n | confrecord = 19\u201313 ({{Winning percentage|19|13}}) \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n|name=Saint Louis Billikens\n|startyear=1969\n|conference=[[Missouri Valley Conference]]\n|endyear=1974\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1969\u201370\n | name         =Saint Louis\n | overall      =9\u201317\n | conference   =5\u201311\n | confstanding =7th\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1970\u201371\n | name         =Saint Louis\n | overall      =17\u201312\n | conference   =9\u20135\n | confstanding =T\u20131st\n | championship =conference\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1971\u201372\n | name         =Saint Louis\n | overall      =18\u20138\n | conference   =9\u20135\n | confstanding =3rd\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1972\u201373\n | name         =Saint Louis\n | overall      =19\u20137\n | conference   =10\u20134\n | confstanding =3rd\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1973\u201374\n | name         =Saint Louis\n | overall      =9\u201316\n | conference   =4\u20138\n | confstanding =T\u20137th\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Saint Louis\n | overall    =72\u201360 ({{Winning percentage|72|60}}) \n | confrecord = 37\u201333 ({{Winning percentage|37|33}}) \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n|name=Rice Owls\n|startyear=1974\n|conference=[[Southwest Conference]]\n|endyear=1977\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1974\u201375\n | name         =Rice\n | overall      =5\u201321\n | conference   =2\u201312\n | confstanding =8th\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1975\u201376\n | name         =Rice\n | overall      =3\u201324\n | conference   =1\u201315\n | confstanding =9th\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n | season       =1976\u201377\n | name         =Rice\n | overall      =9\u201318\n | conference   =3\u201313\n | confstanding =8th\n | championship =\n | postseason   =\n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name         =Rice\n | overall      =17\u201363 ({{Winning percentage|17|63}}) \n | confrecord   =6\u201340 ({{Winning percentage|6|40}}) \n}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record End\n|overall=356\u2013257 ({{Winning percentage|356|257}}) \n}}\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/classic/s/basketball_scandals_explosion.html|title=Explosion: 1951 Scandals Threaten College Hoops}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* [http://www.aceshof.com/person/272/ University of Evansville Hall of Fame profile]\n* [http://tshf.net/halloffame/polk-j-robert-bob/ Tennessee Hall of Fame profile]\n\n{{navboxes|list=\n{{Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Saint Louis Billikens men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Rice Owls men's basketball coach navbox}}\n{{Missouri Valley Conference Men's Basketball Coach of the Year navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Polk, Bob}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:1988 deaths]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball coaches from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Indiana]]\n[[Category:College men's basketball head coaches in the United States]]\n[[Category:Evansville Purple Aces men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:High school basketball coaches in Indiana]]\n[[Category:High school basketball coaches in the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Tell City, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Rice Owls men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Saint Louis Billikens men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Trinity Tigers men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:V-12 Navy College Training Program]]\n[[Category:Vanderbilt Commodores men's basketball coaches]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCollege coaching:Typo fixing, replaced: an Georgia \u2192 a Georgia", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Polk"}
{"title_page": "Oskar Eriksson", "text_new": "{{short description|Swedish curler from Karlstad|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox curler\n| name = Oskar Eriksson\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1991|5|29}}\n| birth_place =[[Karlstad]], [[Sweden]]|\n| Curling club = [[Karlstads Curlingklubb|Karlstads CK]], <br> [[Karlstad|Karlstad, SWE]]\n| Skip = [[Niklas Edin]]\n| Third = '''Oskar Eriksson'''\n| Second = [[Rasmus Wran\u00e5]]\n| Lead = [[Christoffer Sundgren]]\n| Alternate = [[Daniel Magnusson (curler)|Daniel Magnusson]]\n| Mixed doubles partner = [[Anna Hasselborg]]\n| World Championship appearances = 9 (2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019)\n| World Mixed Doubles Championship appearances = 1 (2019)\n| European Championship appearances = 11 (2009, 2010, 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019)\n| Olympic appearances = 3 (2010, 2014, 2018)\n| Grand Slam victories = 3 ([[The Masters Grand Slam of Curling|Masters]]: [[2016 WFG Masters|2016]]; [[GSOC Tour Challenge|Tour Challenge]]: [[2016 GSOC Tour Challenge|2016]]; [[Players' Championship]]: [[2017 Players' Championship|2017]])\n| medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[curling]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{SWE}}}}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2018 Winter Olympics|2018 Pyeongchang]]|[[Curling at the 2018 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2014 Winter Olympics|2014 Sochi]]|[[Curling at the 2014 Winter Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Curling Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 Ford World Men's Curling Championship|2013 Victoria]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 Ford World Men's Curling Championship|2015 Halifax]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2018 World Men's Curling Championship|2018 Las Vegas]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 World Men's Curling Championship|2019 Lethbridge]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2014 World Men's Curling Championship|2014 Beijing]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2017 Ford World Men's Curling Championship|2017 Edmonton]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2011 Ford World Men's Curling Championship|2011 Regina]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2012 World Men's Curling Championship|2012 Basel]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Mixed Doubles Curling Championships|World Mixed Doubles Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 World Mixed Doubles Curling Championship|2019 Stavanger]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[European Curling Championships|European Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2009 European Curling Championships|2009 Aberdeen]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2012 European Curling Championships|2012 Karlstad]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2014 European Curling Championships|2014 Champ\u00e9ry]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2015 European Curling Championships|2015 Esbjerg]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2016 European Curling Championships|2016 Renfrewshire]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2017 European Curling Championships|2017 St Gallen]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 European Curling Championships|2019 Helsingborg]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2011 European Curling Championships|2011 Moscow]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2018 European Curling Championships|2018 Tallinn]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Junior Curling Championships|World Junior Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2011 World Junior Curling Championships|2011 Perth]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2008 World Junior Curling Championships|2008 \u00d6stersund]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Winter Universiade]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2013 Winter Universiade|2013 Trentino]]|}}\n}}\n'''Oskar Eriksson''' (born 29 May 1991) is a [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[Curling|curler]] from [[Karlstad]].<ref>2020 Continental Cup Media Guide: Team Edin</ref> He currently plays third for the [[Niklas Edin]] rink. He is a four-time World Curling Champion, seven-time European Curling Champion, and the first curler in history to win gold medals in three major curling championships in a single calendar year \u2013 the World Men's Curling Championship, the European Curling Championship, and the World Mixed Doubles Championship. He is the only member of Team Sweden to have competed in all of the World Men's Curling Championships from 2011 to 2019. He won medals in all but one of these championships, as well as playing in multiple positions \u2013 as skip (silver, [[2014 World Men's Curling Championship|2014]]), third (gold, [[2015 World Men's Curling Championship|2015]], [[2018 World Men's Curling Championship|2018]], [[2019 World Men's Curling Championship|2019]] and silver, [[2017 World Men's Curling Championship|2017]]) second (bronze, [[2012 World Men's Curling Championship|2012]]), and as an alternate (gold, [[2013 World Men's Curling Championship|2013]] and bronze, [[2011 World Men's Curling Championship|2011]]). As a member of Team Niklas Edin, he has also won three Grand Slam Curling Events, as well as the Pinty's Cup, being part of the first non-Canadian men's team to do so.\n\n==Career==\n===Career Beginnings===\nEriksson began curling before he was six years old. He followed his older brothers [[Anders Eriksson (Karlstad curler)|Anders Eriksson]] and [[Markus_Eriksson_(curler)|Marcus Eriksson]] into the sport, but his skill level advanced more rapidly.<ref>https://www.vf.se/2019/12/24/plats-1-oskar-eriksson-skrev-historia-under-guldkantat-2019/</ref> He was part of a curling team at age seven,<ref>https://www.vf.se/2019/12/24/plats-1-oskar-eriksson-skrev-historia-under-guldkantat-2019/</ref> debuting in Sweden's Elite Series at the age of thirteen.<ref>https://www.nwt.se/2009/12/30/framtiden-osaker-for-lag-eriksson/</ref> He won his first Swedish Men's Curling Championship title in his junior career and has gone on to win six more championship titles since then.<ref>[[Swedish Men%27s Curling Championship]]</ref>. As a junior, Eriksson also competed at three World Junior Curling Championships, winning both a gold medal and a silver medal. At those three World Junior Championships, Eriksson skipped two different Swedish teams, winning a total of 24 games and losing only 9.\n\nEriksson made his first run a junior world championship title when he was sixteen at [[2008 World Junior Curling Championships]]. He skipped his first team, consisting of Henric Jonsson, Markus Franz\u00e9n, and Nils Karlsson, to a silver medal, losing in the final to the US team skipped by [[Chris Plys]]. In 2008, Eriksson moved to H\u00e4rnosand to join other promising curlers at H\u00e4rnosands gymnasium. He also joined Team Lindstr\u00f6m from [[Lit, Sweden|Lit]], formed by brothers [[Kristian Lindstr\u00f6m]] and [[Alexander Lindstr\u00f6m]] along with [[Christoffer Sundgren]] and [[Henrik Leek]]. The team had immediate success on the junior tour and also scored wins in the senior division.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ltz.se/artikel/lag-lindstrom-bast-i-norska-elitserien |title=Oskar kom hem \u2013 och vann|publisher=Nya Wermalands Tidningen |date= 6 January 2009|accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwt.se/2009/01/06/oskar-kom-hem-och-vann/|title=Lag Lindstr\u00f6m b\u00e4st i norden|publisher=L\u00e4nstidningen \u00d6stersund |date= 12 October 2008|accessdate=2020-04-14}}</ref> With this team, Eriksson made his second run for the gold medal at the [[2009 World Junior Curling Championships]], but reached only a fourth-place finish, losing in the bronze-medal game to the US team that was again skipped by Plys. Though the team did not qualify to compete at the championships in 2010, Eriksson and his teammates finally won a gold medal at the [[2011 World Junior Curling Championships]], defeating Team Switzerland, skipped by [[Peter de Cruz]], by a score of 6\u20135 in the final. In 2012, his teammates were no longer eligible for junior competition, so Eriksson skipped a team with Ludwig Grann, Erik \u00d6lund and Magnus Rudstr\u00f6m at the Swedish Junior Curling Championship undefeated until the finals. Team Eriksson came in second place to the team from Sundyberg skipped by his future teammate [[Rasmus Wran\u00e5]], who qualified for the World Junior Curling Championships instead.<ref>https://www.cuponline.se/teamView.aspx?cupid=1570&id=17105</ref>\n\n=== Seniors I (2009-2014): Team Lindstr\u00f6m/Eriksson and Team Edin ===\n\nShortly after joining Team Lit in 2008, Eriksson played simultaneously with two teams. His official team during this period was Team Lit, which he skipped for most of this period and was alternatively known as Team Lindstr\u00f6m and eventually Team Eriksson.<ref>https://litcurling.wordpress.com/</ref><ref name=Erikssoncareer>{{cite web|url=https://worldcurl.com/player.php?playerid=14370&view=Teams |title=Oskar Eriksson, Career Results|publisher=WorldCurl.com |date= 5 April 2020|accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref> From 2009 to the end of 2013, he also effectively became the presumptive alternate for Team [[Niklas Edin]] with [[Sebastian Kraupp]], [[Fredrik Lindberg]], and [[Viktor Kj\u00e4ll]], playing at the World Curling Championships, European Curling Championships, and 2010 and 2014 Olympic Games. During this period, however, Team Lit became more competitive with Team Edin and was well recognized as one of the top two men's curling teams in Sweden.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwt.se/2012/10/04/topplag-i-samma-bo |title=Topplag i samma bo|publisher=Nya Wermlands Tidningen |date= 4 October 2012|accessdate=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nAs an alternate for Team Edin during this period, Eriksson received numerous medals, including two gold medals at the European Curling Championships (2009 and 2012) and three World Curling Championship medals, including his first World Championship Gold medal (2013) and two bronze (2011 and 2012). At the [[2012 World Men's Curling Championship]], however, he notably played all games except three because Edin, the permanent skip, was suffering from a herniated disc in his back. Eriksson also played in the second position in the playoffs, in which Team Sweden won a bronze medal. He also made his first Olympic appearances with Team Edin, coming in fourth in the 2010 Winter Olympics and receiving a bronze medal in the 2014 Winter Olympics.\n\nWith his own team, however, Eriksson and his teammates were recognized as a very competitive team and won several international events, including the Oslo Cup (2009), Swiss Cup Basel (2013) European Masters (2013) as well as the Winter Universiade (2013).<ref name=Erikssoncareer /> In the 2013-14 season, Team Eriksson reached second place at the Swiss Cup Basel, Mercure Perth Masters, and Sweden's Eliter Series and competed in Canada on the World Curling Tour, coming in fifth place in three events and his first Grand Slam Quarterfinal at the [[2014 The National (March)|National]]. Winning the Swedish Men's Curling Championships that year as well, the team was selected to represent Sweden in the [[2014 World Men's Curling Championship]], as Team Edin had represented Sweden in the European Curling Championships. Team Eriksson reached the final and won the silver medal in their World Curling Championship debut.\n\n=== Seniors II (2014-present): Team Edin ===\n\nIn May 2014, Edin and Team Eriksson came to an agreement to form a new Team Edin, with Edin skipping the team in the fourth position and Oskar Eriksson playing third along with Kristian Lindstr\u00f6m playing second and Christoffer Sundgren in the lead position.<ref name=nwt2014>{{cite web|url=https://www.nwt.se/2014/05/13/edin-och-eriksson-bildar-supercurlinglag/ |title=Edin och Eriksson bilder supercurlinglag|publisher=Nya Wermlands-Tidningen |date= 13 May 2014|accessdate=2020-04-05}}.</ref> When Lindstr\u00f6m underwent surgery in 2016, Rasmus Wran\u00e5 took over as second. From the start, however, Edin and Eriksson's team immediately saw the potential for the new team and aimed to become the number one team in the world.<ref name=nwt2014 /> Indeed, after finishing in the top ten on the Order of Merit and prize money mist in their first two seasons as a new team, Team Edin was ranked first at the end of the [[2016\u201317 curling season]] on both lists and in first place on the prize money list in the [[2017-18 curling season]]. The team also reached the finals of the European Curling Championships every year since forming a new team, winning gold in all years but one (2014-2017 and 2019) and winning silver once (2018). The team also secured reached the finals of the World Curling Championships every year except 2016, winning three gold (2015, 2018 and 2019) and one silver (2017).\n\nAs part of Team Edin, Eriksson and his teammates have been ranked in the top 10 since they formed on the World Curling Tour Order of Merit, ranking first in 2017 and first on the money list in 2017 and 2018. The team has reached the playoffs in 20 Grand Slam of Curling Events. In 2016, Team Edin had their most successful year on tour, winning three Slams (the Masters, the Tour Challenge, and the Players\u2019 Championship) and reaching the finals (the Canadian Open) and semifinals (the National and Champions Cup), securing the Pinty\u2019s Cup. The Team has also won several other World Curling Tour events, including the European Masters (2014), Swiss Cup Basel (2016, 2018), Baden Masters (2015, 2017), Curling Masters Champery (2016, 2017), and Perth Masters (2018).<ref name=Erikssoncareer /> Team Edin has also won the [[Swedish Men's Curling Championships]] six times between 2014 and 2020, skipping the 2017 championships to prepare for the World Championships.\n\n=== Career Achievements  ===\n\nCurrently, Eriksson is the only Swedish curler to have taken part in nine consecutive [[World Curling Championships]] in the men's division (2011-2019). Eriksson has also competed in eleven consecutive [[European Curling Championships]], winning a record seven gold medals, a record that he shares only with Niklas Edin. With Team Edin, Eriksson has won four World Curling Championship gold medals (in 2015, 2018 and 2019), placing him in an elite group of curlers to hold four World Championship titles.<ref>[[List of men%27s World Curling champions]]</ref> In 2019, Eriksson became the first curler in history to hold three key gold medals in a single calendar year: the [[2019 World Men's Curling Championship|World Curling Championship]], the [[2019 European Curling Championships|European Curling Championship]], and the [[2019 World Mixed Doubles Curling Championship|World Mixed Doubles Championship]] (with Anna Hasselborg).<ref>https://www.vf.se/2019/12/24/plats-1-oskar-eriksson-skrev-historia-under-guldkantat-2019/?auth=true</ref> As part of Team Edin, Eriksson, Niklas Edin, and Christoffer Sundgren also became the first men's curlers to simultaneously hold the World Curling Championship and European Curling Championship titles in two separate calendar years (2015 and 2019).<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_men%27s_World_Curling_champions and https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_Curling_Championships</ref> Eriksson and Edin had previously become the first men's curlers to simultaneously hold those same titles in three separate competition seasons (2012-2013, 2014\u20132015, and 2017-2018).<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_men%27s_World_Curling_champions and https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/European_Curling_Championships</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Eriksson was inducted into the [[Swedish Curling Hall of Fame]].\n\n==Grand Slam record==\n{{Curling GS key}}\n{{clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Event\n! [[2013-14 curling season|2013\u201314]]\n! [[2014-15 curling season|2014\u201315]]\n! [[2015\u201316 curling season|2015\u201316]]\n! [[2016\u201317 curling season|2016\u201317]]\n! [[2017\u201318 curling season|2017\u201318]]\n! [[2018\u201319 curling season|2018\u201319]]\n! [[2019\u201320 curling season|2019\u201320]]\n|-\n| [[Elite 10]]\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|style=\"background:thistle;\"| F\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| [[2016 Elite 10|Q]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| [[2017 Elite 10|Q]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| [[2018 Elite 10 (March)|Q]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| [[2018 Elite 10 (September)|Q]]\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|-\n| [[Masters (curling)|Masters]]\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| DNP\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| Q\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| QF\n|style=\"background:#00ff00;\"| '''[[2016 WFG Masters|C]]'''\n|style=\"background:thistle;\"| F\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"| [[2018 Masters (curling)|SF]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| [[2019 Masters (curling)|Q]]\n|-\n| [[Tour Challenge]]\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| Q\n|style=\"background:#00ff00;\"| '''[[2016 GSOC Tour Challenge|C]]'''\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"| [[2017 GSOC Tour Challenge|SF]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| [[2018 Tour Challenge|Q]]\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| [[2019 Tour Challenge|QF]]\n|-\n| [[The National (curling)|The National]]\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| QF\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| DNP\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| [[2015 The National|Q]]\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"| [[2016 The National|SF]]\n|style=\"bbackground:#afeeee;\"| DNP\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| [[2018 National|QF]]\n|style=\"background:thistle;\"| [[2019 National|F]]\n|-\n| [[Canadian Open (curling)|Canadian Open]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| Q\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| Q\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| [[2015 Meridian Canadian Open|QF]]\n|style=\"background:thistle;\"| [[2017 Meridian Canadian Open|F]]\n|style=\"background:thistle;\"| [[2018 Meridian Canadian Open|F]]\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"| [[2019 Canadian Open (curling)|SF]]\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| Q\n|-\n| [[Players' Championships|Players']]\n|style=\"bbackground:#EFEFEF;\"| DNP\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| Q\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| [[2016 Players' Championship|QF]]\n|style=\"background:#00ff00;\"| [[2017 Players' Championship|'''C''']]\n|style=\"background:thistle;\"| F\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| [[2019 Players' Championship|QF]]\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|-\n| [[Champions Cup (curling)|Champions Cup]]\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"| [[2016 Humpty's Champions Cup|QF]]\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"| SF\n|style=\"background:#afeeee;\"| Q\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"| [[2019 Champions Cup|SF]]\n|style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\"| N/A\n|}\n\n==Teams==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Season\n!Skip/Fourth\n!Third\n!Second\n!Lead\n!Alternate\n!Events\n|-\n| 2005\u201306|| [[Anders Eriksson (Karlstad curler)|Anders Eriksson]] (4th) || [[Sebastian Kraupp]] (skip) || [[Viktor Kj\u00e4ll]] || '''Oskar Eriksson''' || ||\n|-\n| 2006\u201307|| '''Oskar Eriksson''' || Henric Jonsson || Markus Franz\u00e9n || Nils Karlsson || ||\n|-\n| 2007\u201308|| '''Oskar Eriksson''' || Henric Jonsson || Markus Franz\u00e9n || Nils Karlsson || || WJCC\n|-\n| 2008\u201309 || [[Kristian Lindstr\u00f6m]] (4th) || '''Oskar Eriksson''' (skip) || [[Alexander Lindstr\u00f6m]] || [[Christoffer Sundgren]] || [[Henrik Leek]] || WJCC \n|-\n| 2009\u201310 || (1) [[Kristian Lindstr\u00f6m]] (4th) <br> (2) [[Niklas Edin]] || '''Oskar Eriksson''' (skip) <br> [[Sebastian Kraupp]] || [[Alexander Lindstr\u00f6m]] <br> [[Fredrik Lindberg]] || [[Christoffer Sundgren]] <br> [[Viktor Kj\u00e4ll]] || <br> Oskar Eriksson ||  <br> ECC, [[Curling at the 2010 Winter Olympics|OG]]\n|-\n| 2010\u201311 || (1) [[Kristian Lindstr\u00f6m]] (4th) <br> (2) [[Niklas Edin]] || '''Oskar Eriksson''' (skip) <br> [[Sebastian Kraupp]] || [[Henrik Leek]] <br> [[Fredrik Lindberg]] || [[Alexander Lindstr\u00f6m]] <br> [[Viktor Kj\u00e4ll]] || [[Christoffer Sundgren]] <br> Oskar Eriksson || WJCC <br> ECC, WCC\n|-\n| 2011\u201312 || (1) [[Kristian Lindstr\u00f6m]] (4th) <br> (2) [[Niklas Edin]] || '''Oskar Eriksson''' (skip) <br> [[Sebastian Kraupp]] || [[Henrik Leek]] <br> [[Fredrik Lindberg]] || [[Alexander Lindstr\u00f6m]] <br> [[Viktor Kj\u00e4ll]] || [[Christoffer Sundgren]] <br> Oskar Eriksson || <br> ECC,